<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="HEB" stage="Final" version="C">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="John Wimbish" created="2009-10-05 05:57:06Z" when="2009-10-05 05:57:06Z" stage="Draft">drafted by Lazarus Aplugi; keyboarded by Helena Aplugi; team revision October 2008; with advisor Feb 2009 (Kupang-S); Consultant Check at UBB office in Kupang, 20-23 July 2009, Consultant: Catherine Rountree (in Florida) Advisor: Chuck Grimes (running the check by proxy); Team Coordinator: Michael Sina (Kupang-based) Team present: Lazarus Aplugi (main drafter); Lazarus Lusi (Dhao-based); Helena Aplugi (keyboard); [Rev. Dr. Ayub Ranoh Th.D. had on-going responsibilities on Alor island]</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Ibrani</p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">Sasuri hia dhèu<bt>Letter to the</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Ibrani<bt>Ibrani people</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">dhu heka parcaya Yesus Kristus<bt>who have only recently believed in Yesus Kristus</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">aa tèke eele agama bèi-baki ra<bt>and left the religion of their forefathers</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua pua Ana Na dhu kapai risi nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Na uru sèra<bt>God has sent His Child, who is greater than His previous/former spokespeople (= *prophets)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1" />Uru èèna, Ama Lamatua pake dhèu rèti lii padhai Na, ho padhai lii dènge bèi-baki èdhi dhèu Ibrani.<bt>Previously/long ago, God used His spokespeople, to speak with/to our-inc Ibrani forefathers/ ancestors.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patuu = connected to, basambung (island"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">patuu = connected to, basambung (island connected to mainland by isthmus)</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:1a" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Kata <span class="Italic">Ibrani</span> èèna, ngara leo nèti suku Yahudi. Dhèu Yahudi dhu parcaya le Yesus Kristus, dhèu peka na, &lt;&lt;dhèu Kristen Ibrani&gt;&gt;, lula rèngu leko-leo nèti a'ari ra dhèu Yahudi dhu kèpe pa'ère atora agama Yahudi dhu dhui.<bt>This word <span class="Italic">Ibrani</span>, is another name for the Yahudi ethnic group. The Yahudi people who believed in Yesus Kristus, people referred to as "Ibrani Kristen people", because they were different from their Yahudi siblings who continued to hold to the old/former Yahudi religious regulations.</bt></note>Nèngu pake rupa-rupa j'ara, sèna ka peka pahari-pahari dènge rèngu.<bt>He used various ways to speak repeatedly with them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahari-pahari = ulang kali, repeatedly"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pahari-pahari = ulang kali, repeatedly</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: At many times and in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: At many times and in many ways in the past, God, who spoke to our ancestors by the prophets,</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:1b" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ama Lamatua peka lii moa Na dènge rupa-rupa j'ara. Conto sèmi: Na peka dènge Abraham pake lii pajaji, mi Musa pake atora agama, mi Daud pake lii sod'a koa-kio, mi Yermia pake lii pakasame.<bt>God told His messages/instructions using various ways. For example: He told to Abraham using promises, to Musa using religious regulations, to Daud using songs of praise, to Yeremia using examples/parables/allegories.</bt></note><v n="2" />Te ngaa limuri ne, Na pua le Ana Na mai, sèna ka padhai lii dènge èdhi.<bt>But now, He has sent His Child, to speak with us-inc. [NOTE to daughter translations: Don't skew by overemphasize “langsung” as “face-to-face”, since that is both wrong, and not the point. Most recipients of this letter probably never had a direct encounter with the physical Jesus.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Karèi nèti uru-uru j'ara ka, Ama Lamatua hag'e nare le Ana Na,<bt>From long ago/the (very) beginning, God had chosen (selected out from many possibilities) this Child of His,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho nèd'u paredha sama-sama dènge Nèngu.<bt>to rule/govern together with Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te lod'o Na paj'aj'i liru dènge rai-haha dènge isi ra aa'i-aa'i,<bt>Cuz (elaboration), when He created the heaven/sky and earth (doublet), and all their contents,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ana Na dhu sab'a sama-sama dènge Ne kahèi.<bt>His Child was also working together with Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: in these last days has"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: in these last days has spoken to us by (his) Son, whom he [placed/made/appointed/chose] heir of all things, through whom also he made the [universe/worlds].</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Ana Lamatua ne, pad'elo dadedha Ama Na,<bt>This Child of God, exhibits/shows His Father's high-ness/glory, [NOTE to daughter translations: ‘glory’ here.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka sèmi saraa madha lod'o dhu lèke tèru.<bt>like the rays/shining of the sun which hit a mirror.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te Nèngu ne, ca ropa dènge Ama Na.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He is the same model/type/form as His Father.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa nèti Lii Holo-Nori Na dhu èra titu kèna,<bt>And from His powerful Words/Sayings,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Na pakako aa'i-aa'i ètu dedha-liru dènge rai-haha.<bt>He set-in-motion everything in heaven (doublet) and on earth (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu bhoke j'ara kahèi,<bt>He also opened the way,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho saku eele sasala-sasigo dhèu,<bt>to wipe away people's wrongs (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka ra j'aj'i mola-mèci.<bt>so that they could be/become clean/holy/pure (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Hèia Na lèpa hari asa sorga,<bt>Then He returned again to heaven,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho madhèdi ètu baboa g'ana Ama Lamatua,<bt>to sit at God's right side,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ètu era dhu kab'ua aae.<bt>in the place of greatest respect.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Who being the [brightness/radiance/reflection] of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Who being the [brightness/radiance/reflection] of his [God's] glory, and the exact [image/likeness/representation/stamp] of his [God's] [person/being/nature], and [upholding/sustaining/bearing [support &amp; movement]] all things by his powerful word, [when/after] he had [purged/cleansed/ provided purification from] our sins, sat down on the right side of the Majesty on high. Chrysostom: phws, ek phwtos: Brightness, radiance, reflection.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana Ama Lamatua kapai risi nèti ana pajuu ètu sorga<bt>God's Child is greater than the *angels (underlings in heaven)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ana-ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ètu sorga mema kapai. Te ngaa Ana Na kapai risi eele nèti rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra. Kapai dènge dadedha Ama Lamatua risi eele nèti aa'i-aa'i ra. Aa kapai dènge dadedha èèna, Na pangèd'u le mi Ana Na. Nèti èèna ka, Ana Na kapai risi eele nèti ana-ana pajuu Na ètu sorga.<bt>God's angels in heaven really are great. But His Child who is greatest, even more than all of them. The greatness and high-ness/glory of God is more than all of them. And His greatness and high-ness/glory He has already handed over to His Child. That is why His Child is greater than His angels.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Being made so much [greater/superior"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Being made so much [greater/superior [of dignity, worth, advantage, power, possibly goodness; kind not degree] than the angels, just as he has by inheritance obtained a [more excellent/outstanding/greater/superior] name than theirs.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ama Lamatua peka nèdhi mi Ana Na, aku Nèngu na,<bt>God once spoke to His Child, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Doe ne'e, Ja'a ded'e Èu ho mèd'u paredha.&gt;&gt;<bt>“Today, I am elevating/appointing You to rule.” [NOTE to daughter translations: CHECK parallel quote in Acts 13:32-33 quoting Ps. 2:7; /Ini hari, Beta angka sang Lu ko pegang parenta./ "Today, I lift You up/install You in.order.to hold authority." Ps 2:6 provides context of coronation for making sense out of this verse. Otherwise it is incoherent, as in most English translations. This fits this context better as well.]</bt><note reference="1:5a" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ama Lamatua, peka kahèi, na,<bt>God also spoke, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, Ama Na.<bt>“I am His Father.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Nèngu ne, Ana Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He is My Child.”</bt><note reference="1:5b" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Samuel 7:14, 1 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 17:13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ama Lamatua peka dènge Ana Na sèmi èèna, te ngaa Ama Lamatua peka nèdhi boe sèmi èèna, mi ana-ana pajuu Na ètu sorga.<bt>God spoke beforehand like that with/about His Child, but He never spoke that way to/about His angels in heaven. [CHECK possible ambiguous reading with /dènge/ “beforehand” or “with”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: To which of the angels"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: To which of the angels did he ever say, "You are my Son. Today I have given you birth." And again, "I will be a Father to him, and he will be a Son to me."</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Lod'o Ama Lamatua pua mai Ana Na dhu kapai risi eele èèna, Na paredha ana-ana pajuu Na ètu sorga, aku Nèngu na,<bt>When God sent His Child who is so amazing, He also commanded His angels in heaven, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Miu ana pajuu aa'i-aa'i!<bt>“All you-pl angels!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lami ho pakab'ua,<bt>Go show honour/respect,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa pahaha iisi mi Ana Ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>and worship My Child!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And again, when he brings"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And again, when he brings his firstborn into the world, he says, "Let all God's angels worship him."</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 32:43; Lukas 2:13-14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ama Lamatua padhai lii kahèi mi ana pajuu Na ètu sorga, peka na,<bt>God has also spoken to/about His angels in heaven, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a tao ana-ana pajuu Ja'a ètu sorga,<bt>“I make My underlings/angels/servants in heaven,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">j'aj'i malai sama sèmi lai ngèlu.<bt>fast/swift like (the) wind.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a tao ènu-ènu Ja'a,<bt>I make My slaves/servants2 (parallelism), [NOTE: it is not /doulos/ here, so hamba OK]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">j'aj'i nuka sèmi ai.&gt;&gt;<bt>like fire.”</bt><note reference="1:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 104:4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ama Lamatua peka dènge ra sèmi èèna, lula rèngu dhoka ana pua-paleha Na di.<bt>God spoke to/about them like that, because they are only/merely His servants3 (people who habitually take orders) (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And he says of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And he says of the angels, "Who makes his angels winds, and his [religious servants/ministers] a flame of fire."</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa mi Ana d'èlu Na, Nèngu peka dhu leo, na,<bt>But He spoke differently altogether to/about His own Child, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Èu ne, Ama Lamatua.<bt>“You-sg here are God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Èu, èèna na madhèdi ètu kadera paredha toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>You will sit in the ruling/governing seat forever.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Èu èèna na mèd'u koasa, ho paredha dènge d'ara mola.<bt>You will hold power/authority to rule/govern with a straight/honest/right insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Regularize &quot;scepter&quot; from similar quotations. LITERALLY:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">Regularize "scepter" from similar quotations. LITERALLY: But he says to the Son: "O God, your throne is forever and ever. The sceptre of your kingdom is a sceptre of [righteousness/justice].]<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="9" />D'ara Èu karej'e, ladhe mèdhi dhèu dhu mamuri mola.<bt>Your insides are happy seeing people who live straight/honest/right.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa d'ara Mu susa, ladhe mèdhi dhèu dhu mamuri koe-kapengo.<bt>But Your insides are troubled seeing people who live bent/twisted/evil (doublet). [NOTE to daughter translations: CHECK UNS's sense of /pakane'o/ in Rote sense of "twisted morally", or Sabu sense of "twisting that causes delays in reaching your goal". Should it be /babengko/?]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèti èèna ka, d'ara Èu karej'e,<bt>That is why Your insides are happy,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ka Ja'a pasuti èi lèngi mi kètu Èu,<bt>so I pour (slowly) oil on Your head,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palona = pour (like washing hair)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">palona = pour (like washing hair) ; pakosa = pour some on hands and rub together before applying</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho ded'e Èu j'aj'i Dhèu Aae, dhu risi nèti dhèu aae leo sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>to appoint You to be King greater than the other kings."</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: You have loved righteousness, and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: You have loved righteousness, and hated lawlessness. Therefore your God has annointed you with the oil of gladness above your comrades."</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:8-9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 45:7-8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ama Lamatua peka mi Ana Na kahèi, na,<bt>God also speaks/spoke to His Child, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ana, ee!<bt>“Child, ee!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Èu ne, Kètu dhu mèd'u paredha karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>You-sg are the Head/Leader who has held rule/governed from long ago.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Èu ne'e ka dhu pua liru j'aj'i, hèia na j'aj'i dènge.<bt>You are the one who commanded the sky/heaven to come into being, and so it came into being straightaway.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Èu ne'e ka dhu paredha rai-haha, hèia na j'aj'i dènge.<bt>You are the one who commanded the earth (doublet), and so it came into being straightaway.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And, &quot;You Lord, in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And, "You Lord, in the beginning, have laid the foundation of the earth, and the heavens are the work of your hands.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11-12" />Bèli-camèd'a liru dènge rai-haha laho aa'i si.<bt>Sky/heaven and earth (doublet) will completely decay.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Bèli-camèd'a liru dènge rai-haha ele aa'i si.<bt>Sky/heaven and earth (doublet) will completely disappear.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te ngaa Èu mesa mu, mamuri toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>But You yourself will live forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: They will [be ruined/be destroyed],"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: They will [be ruined/be destroyed], but you remain. They will become old like a garment.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èèna na Èu core eele liru dènge rai-haha,<bt>You will get rid of sky/heaven and earth (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka sèmi dhèu core eele kaha'i soho dhasi.<bt>like a person throws off/gets rid of filthy (also implies worn) clothes (idiom).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ceb'e = hambur (seed) ; kaha'i"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">ceb'e = hambur (seed) ; kaha'i = kain lara / kotor/ lap ; soho dhasi = old worn clothes for going out makan meting (soho doesn't stand alone) ; (young UNS heard, but not often)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Bèli-camèd'a Èu gati eele liru aa rai-haha,<bt>You will replace/change sky/heaven and earth (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka sèmi dhèu silu mèdha-papake hiu.<bt>like a person replaces/changes2 (to wear) new clothes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="silu = gati (ular ganti kulit)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">silu = gati (ular ganti kulit)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa Èu mesa Mu sèmi boe èèna.<bt>But You yourself are not like that.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula Èu mamuri toke d'ai mia-mia.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because You live forever.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: You will [roll/fold] them up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: You will [roll/fold] them up like a robe, and will change them like clothes. But you are the same, and your years will not come to an end."</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:10-12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 102:26-28</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ama Lamatua peka kahèi dènge Ana Na, aku Nèngu na,<bt>God also spoke with His Child, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ana, ee!<bt>“Child, ee!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Mai madhèdi asa era dhu kab'ua titu kèna,<bt>Come sit in the place of highest honour,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ètu baboa g'ana Ja'a ne.<bt>at My right side.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe Ja'a tao musu Èu sèra,<bt>I will make Your enemies,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">toke ra pahaha iisi mi Èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>to the point that they surrender/submit/ humble themselves to You."</bt><note reference="1:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ama Lamatua peka-padhai mi Ana Na sèmi èèna, te ngaa Na padhai lii nèdhi boe sèmi èèna mi ana-ana pajuu Na ètu sorga.<bt>God spoke like that to/about His Child, but He never spoke like that to/about His angels in heaven.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But to which of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But to which of the angels did he ever say, "Sit on my right side, until I make your enemies your footstool"?</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ana pajuu Na sèra mema panting. Te Nèngu paleha si lasi lalau-lalo'o dhèu unu Na aa'i-aa'i dhu èèna na Nèngu patabuli eele si nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Ana Ama Lamatua risi nèti rèngu era.<bt>His angels really are important. Cuz (elaboration) He commissioned/sent them to go manage/handle matters/take care of (doublet) all His people whom He will *save/rescue from their wrongs. Even that being the case, nevertheless God's Child is still more than them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText=", sèna ka padelo dènge ra"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">, sèna ka padelo dènge ra j'ara mamuri.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="@@@"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">@@@</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Are they not all ministering"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Are they not all ministering spirits, sent out to minister for those who shall be heirs of salvation?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku tule eele lii holo-nori Ama Lamatua dhu nèti mamuri<bt>Don't throw away/reject God's message that brings life/salvation</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Nèti èèna ka, èdhi hud'i kèpe ku pa'èra-èra ngaa dhu èdhi tadèngi le nèti j'ara-j'ara Ana Ama Lamatua, sèna ka èdhi baku bhèlu eele.<bt>Because of that, we-inc must hold firmly to what we have heard about God's Child, so that we do not forget it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore we ought to pay"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore we ought to pay strict attention to the things we have heard, lest at any time we would [drift away/be carried away]. dia touto may be proleptic to meépote, not back to Ch. 1.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>perissotéroos: more, a strong comparative. More than what? "Pay attention more than we did before" doesn't fit the context. "More than we pay attention to the message given by angels" is most likely. Also possible, the intensive meaning "pay particular attention" akousthéisin: the truths we have heard, handed down from Jesus. The writer of Hebrews doesn't use the term "Gospel", but that's what he's talking about<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>pararyóomen: the opposite of "stick wit" o "tink plenny", used of a ship drifting away. It implies that if we don't stick with the truth from Jesus, we'll get away from it and end up in trouble. It's like passing up an opportunity that you won't get again</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Lod'o uru-uru sèra, Lamatua pake ana pajuu Na nèti sorga, ho lole lii moa Na mi bèi-baki èdhi. Te'a boe na, lii moa sèra aa'i-aa'i ra lèke. Ladhe ra sisu paredha Na, rèngu tatu abhu huku dhu palèke dènge tatao ra.<bt>Formerly, God2 used His angels, to tell/explain His message/instructions to our-inc ancestors. It turns out that that whole message was true/spot on/right. When they transgressed those commands of His, they definitely got punished appropriate to their deeds/behaviour.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="endikon: appropriate, based on justice. R"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">endikon: appropriate, based on justice. R 3:8 God goin punish da peopo dat tink lidat! LITERALLY: For since the word spoken through angels was [firm/solid/steadfast], and every transgression and disobedience received a just [reward/retribution/punishment],<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Mema uru èèna, sèmi èèna ka. Te ngaa limuri ne, Ana Ama Lamatua bhoke le j'ara hiu, sèna ka hia mamuri mi dhèu rai-haha. Na peka le j'ara mamuri dhu be'a aae ne mi dhèu unu Na dhu pakako sasab'a Na ètu rai-haha ne. Hèia ra peka dènge èdhi, sèna ka èdhi parcaya. Te ngaa ladhe èdhi pusi-pahae boe, dui tare pala ti!<bt>That's really how it used to be like that. But now God's Child has already opened a new way to *save/give life to humans. He has already told/explained/made known this good way of life/salvation to His people who carry out His work on earth. So they told us-inc, so we believe. But if/when we don't care about it (doublet), we are in serious-trouble (bear the consequences - phrasing evokes warnings about violating oaths)!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: How shall we escape, if"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: How shall we escape, if we [neglect/do not pay attention to] such a great salvation, which at the first began to be spoken through the Lord, and was confirmed to us by those that heard him.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Te Ama Lamatua pangèd'u si koasa kahèi, sèna ka ra tao rupa-rupa tadha malaa. Na papuru Roh Na mi rèngu kahèi, ho ra ad'u-ue j'ara-j'ara leo dhu madhutu dad'èi Na. Nèti èèna ka èdhi te'a, na, aa'i-aa'i se j'ara mamuri dhu lèke tare'a-re'a.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God also gives them power/ authority so they can do various sorts of amazing signs (= *miracles). He also sent/sends down His Spirit to them, so they can do (doublet) many other things according to His will. Because of all that, that is why we-inc know that that way of salvation is really true/correct.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: God also bore witness, with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: God also bore witness, with signs and wonders, and various [miracles/powers], and gifts of the Holy Spirit, according to his own will.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nga tao ka Ana Ama Lamatua pahaha iisi Na ho j'aj'i dhèu rai-haha?<bt>Why did/does God's Child lower/humble Himself to become human?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ja'a lole lula-nèti rai-haha rupa hiu dhu bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua peka nèdhi boe dènge ana-ana pajuu Na ètu sorga, na, pe rèngu ka dhu ator rai-haha hiu èèna. Te dhu lalau ka, dhèu rai-haha.<bt>I am speaking about the new model/form of the world (doublet) which is going to happen. But God never told His angels that later they would be the one to run/look after that world (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) the ones to look after it, would be humans.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For God has not put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For God has not put the world to come, of which we speak, under subjection to the angels. perì hées lalóumen: It's the new order we are talking about<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, na, Daud dhu karèi nèdhi le kab'ua nèti dhèu rai-haha, aku nèngu na,<bt>In God's Holy Writings, Daud once asked about the value/worth of humans, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua!<bt>“God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nga tao ka Ama tao madha-dhilu mi dhèu rai-haha?<bt>Why does Father (=You) pay attention (Idiom: place eyes-ears) to humans?</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nga tao ka Ama sue si?<bt>Why does Father love them?</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te rèngu dhoka dhèu rai-haha biasa di!<bt>Cuz (elaboration) they are merely normal humans!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hyios anthroopou: not Jesus' title, but"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">hyios anthroopou: not Jesus' title, but equivalent to "a human" LITERALLY: Instead, it was testified somewhere, "What is man, that you think about him, the son of man that you care for him?<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="7" />Te ngaa Lamatua pangèd'u si koasa,<bt>But God2 (short form for referent tracking) has handed over/given power/authority to them,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ka rèngu oe sèmi ana pajuu ètu sorga.<bt>so they are almost the same as angels (in heaven).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua pakab'ua si hèi,<bt>God2 also respects/honours them,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa ded'e si,<bt>and elevates/appoints them,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: You made him a little"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: You made him a little lower than the angels. You crowned him with glory and honor, [and set him over the works of your hands.]</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">
      <v n="8" />ho ra paredha aa'i dhu Lamatua paj'aj'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>so they rule/govern everything that God2 had created.”</bt><note reference="2:6-8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 8:5-7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De madhutu sasuri Daud, Ama Lamatua ded'e dhèu rai-haha j'aj'i kètu, sèna ka ra uri aa'i-aa'i dhu Na paj'aj'i. Te ngaa èdhi tèdhi mèka na, dhèu rai-haha èci sa dhu paredha aa'i-aa'i sèmi èèna.<bt>So (consequently), according to Daud's writings, God elevated/appointed humans to be head/leader, to manage/look after everything which He had created. Whereas we-inc have never known a single human who has ruled/governed everything like that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: You have put all things"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: You have put all things in subjection under his feet." For in that he [God] put all in subjection under him [people], he [God] left nothing that is not put under him [people]. But now we do not see all things put under him [people] yet.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Te ngaa abhu ca Dhèu dhu bisa paredha aa'i-aa'i se. Nèngu èèna, nuka Yesus. Na mai pea taha ètu rai-haha ne, sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu rai-haha dhu pasae j'aj'èra, ka Na madhe hia mi èdhi. Nèti mamadhe Na, Ama Lamatua pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi dhèu rai-haha. Èle èèna ka, Ama Lamatua koa-kad'iri Ne, aa ded'e Ne padedha-dedha, sèna ka Na paredha aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i nare sèra.<bt>But there is one Person who can govern everything. He is Yesus. He came (and) lived temporarily on earth (doublet), to become a human who bore difficulty/suffering, and He died for us. From His death, God shows His goodness/ grace/kindness/generosity to humans (doublet). After that, God praised (doublet) Him and elevate/exalted/glorified Him on high, so He (could) govern everything that God had created. [EXEG: Gk genitive “suffering of death” = objective gen, Careful to lean on the side of his death resulting from his suffering, not that he suffered his whole life.] [EXEG: died for us, NLT, and from problems in Dhao with other renderings.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sili nare boe = tidak terhindar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">sili nare boe = tidak terhindar dari</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But we see Jesus, who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But we see Jesus, who was made a little lower than the angels, through the suffering of death, crowned with glory and honor; so that he by the grace of God should taste death for every person.</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />De lèke, ladhe Ama Lamatua hia Yesus pasae j'aj'èra, ho Yesus bisa bhoke j'ara mamuri pala mi dhèu rai-haha. Te Ama Lamatua neo sèna ka dhèu ae bisa mamuri bera-bera dènge Nèngu ètu sorga. Ama Lamatua ka dhu paj'aj'i aa'i mèu-mèu. Aa aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri, mamuri lula Nèngu ka.<bt>So (consequently) it is right/appropriate that God had Yesus bear/experience suffering, so that Yesus could open the way of salvation for humans (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) God wanted for many people could live together with Him in heaven. God is the one who created everything. And everything that lives, lives because of Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For it was fitting for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For it was fitting for him [God], for whom are all things, and through whom are all things, in bringing many sons to glory, to make the leader of their salvation perfect through sufferings. éprepen: not a strong expression, as if God were compelled to do something. fitting, appropriate<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>di' hòn: for whom, the reason why something happens, the person for whose sake something is done; the justifying reason why something exists. TEV equates this with creation, but the connection isn't clear. Check if Pidgin "everyting fo him" can mean "in favor of him" or "on his side"; if so, there may be an ambiguity di' hóu: by whom, the cause or origin of something, or the means by which it happens; the means of existence; he made it happen. TEV equates this with preservation, but the connection isn't clear<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>archeegòn: path-opener, way-breaker, pioneer; "open da road"? implies that he goes ahead of the others teleióosai: suggests the exaltation of Jesus: cause Jesus to have the position that was rightly his because of the way in which he suffered, or cause Jesus to be everything he was meant to be because of the way he had suffered. Does not imply that he was imperfect or inadequate to start with, but that suffering made him completely effective in that people could relate to him fully<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ama Lamatua tatu sèmi nare si dènge be'a dhèu dhu Yesus tao mola-mèci, ho j'aj'i ana-ana Na. Ama Lamatua èèna, Ama nèti Yesus. Dènge sèmi èèna, Yesus dènge rèngu, ca Ama. Nèti èèna ka, Yesus makae boe paroa mi dhèu se'e, na,<bt>God will surely accept people whom Yesus makes become clean/holy [unmarked for aspect], so they become His children/underlings. God is also Yesus' Father. In that way, Yesus and them have the same Father. That is why Yesus is not ashamed to call them, [NOTE to daughter translations: don't try to force the Gk word play on “those sanctified” and “the one sanctifying”. NLT, CEV, etc.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="@@@"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">@@@</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ladhe dhèu madhutu j'ara mola-mèci ne,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Ladhe dhèu madhutu j'ara mola-mèci ne, Ama Lamatua tatu sèmi nare si dènge be'a, ho j'aj'i ana-ana Na.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Miu se, a'ari Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>"You-pl here, are My own siblings."</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For both he who sanctifies"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For both he who sanctifies and those who are sanctified are all one. For that reason he is not ashamed to call them 'brothers'. hagiázoon: setting apart for God (Gute Nachricht) or purifying from sin ethically and ritually (TEV) reflect two related senses of the word. GN's argument is that "bring to glory" in 10 is a broad concept like "all out for God". TEV's argument is that "salvation" and "perfect" (of completing the consecration ceremony for priests, LXX Lev. 4:5 "and the priest who is now anointed and (teteleiooménos) perfect shall take some of the blood and ..." and 8:33 "you shall not go out of the Tent for seven days, until the day is fulfilled, the day of your (teleioóseoos) perfection. Seven days (teleioósei) purify your hands") suggest the priest's work of ritually purifying people from sin<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ex henòs: single origin, masculine or neuter. Neuter would be "one origin"; masculine would be "the same father (= God)" or "from one stock, common humanity". In either case it refers to Jesus and the people he is saving ouk epaischýnetai: not as though he is doing something he shouldn't, but as though some people criticize him for calling us his brothers and sisters, but he stands up for us and insists that's the way it is<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Te Yesus peka le dènge Ama Na,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) Yesus has already told His Father, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a neo peka dènge a'ari Ja'a,<bt>“I want to tell/explain to My siblings,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula-nèti babe'a Ama!<bt>about Father's (=Your) goodness!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a neo sod'a ètu talora aae rèngu,<bt>I want to sing in their midst,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula-nèti dadedha Ama!&gt;&gt;<bt>about Father's (=Your) greatness!" [NOTE: not “glory” here. Gk no object of praise.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Saying, &quot;I will declare your"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Saying, "I will declare your name to my brothers. In the middle of the congregation I will sing praise to you." tò ónomá sou: tell people what you are really like<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>tóis adelphóis mou: more than Jesus's immediate family -- all his followers hymneésoo: sing praise, perhaps with more emphasis on who a person is than on what that person has done, which is a little more on the order of thanksgiving<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="2:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 22:23</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na,<bt>Yesus also continued speaking, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a sarai-maena mi Ama Lamatua toke d'ai mia-mia.&gt;&gt;<bt>“I will trust (doublet) in God forever.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus peka hari, na,<bt>And Yesus also spoke again/further, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ladhe ku! Ja'a ka ne'e,<bt>“Have a look! I am here,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sama-sama dènge ana-ana Ama Lamatua,<bt>together with God's children,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu Na pangèd'u le mi Ja'a, ho uri si.&gt;&gt;<bt>whom He has turned over/surrendered to Me, for Me to manage/look after them.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And again, &quot;I will put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And again, "I will put my trust in him." And again, "Look! I and the children which God has given me." ésomai pepoithoòs: future perfect embodies a stative participle with passive force and effect on the topic. "Me, I goin trus God" misses that highly marked form, while "God, he da guy" locks on to the stativeness of it, at the cost of downplaying the marked position of egoò<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>édooken: not Jesus's children in a physical sense. In the context, it's God's other children he is talking about, as the next verse picks up</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 8:17, 18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Lula ana-ana Lamatua se, dhèu rai-haha biasa, nèti èèna ka Yesus hud'i j'aj'i ku dhèu rai-haha sama sèmi rèngu kahèi. Te Nèngu hud'i j'aj'i uuru ku dhèu rai-haha, heka Na bisa madhe. Ho nèti mamadhe Na, heka Nèngu bisa parame nare koasa nèti dhèu aae nidhu. Te dhèu aae bhabhelu-katub'a ne'e ka dhu nèd'u koasa, ho uri j'ara-j'ara dhu pa'èki dènge mamadhe.<bt>Because God2's children are normal humans, that is why Yesus also had to become human like them. Cuz (elaboration) He needed to first become human before He could die. So that from His death, only-then could He go snatch away power/ authority of the *devil (=king of the evil spirits). Cuz (elaboration) that evil (doublet) king, is the one who has the power/authority to manage things which are connected/tied to death.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haimatos kai sarkos: &quot;skin an blood&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">haimatos kai sarkos: "skin an blood" is the expression Pidgin speakers can relate to. LITERALLY: Therefore, since the children are partakers of flesh and blood, he himself likewise partook of the same, that through death he might destroy him that had the power of death, that is the devil.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>parapleesíoos metéschen: took on their nature in just the same way katargeéseei: render something inoperative, rather than destroy it physically. It happens when a superior force enters its realm and takes over<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>krátos échonta tóu thanátou: dominion over the realm of death (Herodotus uses the genitive in this way)</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Aa nèngu kahèi tao dhèu rai-haha madha'u dènge mamadhe, toke ra madhutu dad'èi na, nuka sèmi ènu sa. Te ngaa limuri ne, Yesus bisa patalale le dhèu rai-haha nèti d'ara madha'u.<bt>And he also made humans afraid about dying, to the point that they follow his desires, just like slaves. But now, Yesus can already free/release/ save2 humans from that fear. [CHECK understanding “afraid of death” vs. “afraid and dead” Grammar possibly ambiguous, but leans towards former.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Consistent with metaphorical references to slaves"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">Consistent with metaphorical references to slaves in Romans. LITERALLY: And release those, who were slaves all their lives because of their fear of death.<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Te dhu lèke, nuka Yesus mai boe ho soru-bara ana-ana pajuu ètu sorga. Te ngaa Na mai sèna ka soru nare èdhi, nuka ana-èpu Abraham.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) in fact, Yesus did not come to help (doublet) the angels. But He came to help us-inc, that is Abraham's descendants (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For surely he did not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For surely he did not [concern himself with/help] angels, but with the offspring of Abraham.</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Nèti èèna ka, Yesus j'aj'i sama sèmi èdhi, dhu j'aj'i le a'ari Na. Dènge j'ara ne'e Nèngu j'aj'i mi kètu agama èdhi dhu kapai risi eele, ho soru-bara èdhi sèna ka madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua. Yesus pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na kahèi mi èdhi. Aa ladhe Na peka ngaa, Na tao madhutu sèmi èèna kahèi. Uru èèna, bèi-baki èdhi manèngi kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi, sèna ka tao korban, ho Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo rèngu. Limuri ne, Yesus mesa Na ka dhu j'aj'i korban, sèna ka Lamatua saku eele sasala èdhi.<bt>Because of that, Yesus became exactly like us-inc who are His siblings. In that way, He can be our *highest priest, to help (doublet) us follow God's will. Yesus also shows His goodness/grace/kindness/generosity to us. And whatever He says, He does it. Formerly, our ancestors (doublet) asked the *high priest of the Yahudi religion to make a *sacrifice, so God2 would wipe away their wrongs. Now, Yesus himself is the one who has become a sacrifice so that God2 wipes away our-inc wrongs. [EXEG &amp; KEY TERMS: should be "high priest" here, rather than just "priest". KM Key Terms paradigm from other books is /kapala agama/ (head of religion) = "priest", &gt; /kapala agama Yahudi pung bos-bos/ (bosses of the Yahudi priests) = "chief priests", -- /kapala agama dong pung bos besar/ (big boss of the head of religion) = "high priest". This parallels terminological sets of other hierarchical structures. This book sometimes uses for "high priest" /kapala agama paling tinggi/ (highest head of religion), which may work in the context of this book of Hebrews, but takes it out of the terminological set. Question for consideration of team: In some contexts with high repetition of "high priest" can one start with the full form /kapala agama dong pung bos besar/ (big boss of the head of religion) = "high priest", and then track it through that passage with a reduced form /itu kapala agama tu/ "that (aforementioned) priest"?]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: So he had to be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: So he had to be made like his brothers in every way, in order to be a merciful and faithful high priest in his service to God, to make reconciliation for the sins of the people. hothen: his qualifications for the job<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>adelphóis: all other human beings hiláskesthai: not to cool down somebody who is angry, but to deal with the sin problem that has been getting in the way of people getting it right with God<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Lod'o Yesus mamuri ètu rai-haha ne, Na abhu j'aj'èra ae-ae. Abhu kahèi dhu dadugu Ne, sèna ka ad'u-ue sasala. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Nèngu manahu boe. Nèti èèna ka, ladhe abhu dhu dadugu-rariu èdhi, sèna ka tao sasala, Yesus ka dhu bisa soru-bara èdhi ho baku manahu.<bt>When Yesus was alive on this earth (doublet), He got/experienced many difficulties/sufferings. There were also those who (tried to) tempt/persuade Him to do (doublet) wrong. Even that being the case, nevertheless He did not fall (morally, politically). Because if that, if there are those who (try to) tempt/persuade (doublet) us-inc to do wrong, Yesus is already able to help (doublet) us so we don't fall.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="solo mako = buju2"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">solo mako = buju2</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Because he himself has suffered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Because he himself has suffered when he was tempted, he is able to help those who are tempted.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana Ama Lamatua kapai risi nèti Musa<bt>God's Child is greater than Musa</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />De sèmi ne'e, a'ari! Ama Lamatua hag'e nare le miu, aa cap miu dhèu d'ara mola, sèna ka èèna na miu mamuri bera-bera dènge Ne ètu sorga. Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i pangee ku pabe'a-be'a lula-nèti Yesus ne. Te èdhi dhu mangaku le, na, Nèngu ne Dhèu Pajuu-paleha Ama Lamatua, aa Nèngu kahèi Kètu Kapai Risi Agama èdhi.<bt>So (consequently) it's like this, siblings! God has chosen you-pl and stamped/branded/ categorised you as clean/holy insides people, so that you will live together with Him in heaven! Because of that, you-pl must think carefully/in detail about Yesus. Cuz (elaboration) we-inc have confessed/ acknowledged that He is God's Emissary/ commissioned one/apostle, and He is also our-inc High Priest.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="@@@"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">@@@</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore, holy brothers, who share"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore, holy brothers, who share the heavenly calling, consider Jesus, the Apostle and High Priest of our profession. "Head Priest" for a specific individual, "head priest" for the office in general.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>epouraníou: from God in Heaven, or a call to go to Heaven. The epì prefix may localize it to a call to go to heaven, though UBS doesn't favor this view apóstolon: ambassador, one sent on a special mission. TEV downplays it as "whom God sent". In Pidgin we have usually said "send um all ova da place", but here is the only place in the New Testament where it is applied to Jesus coming to the world<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>archieréa tées homologías heemóon: the genitive ties our confession loosely to Jesus as High Priest, so "head pries fo us guys" may be needed to make the connection</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Miu se, dhu mamuri mola le,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Miu se, dhu mamuri mola le, sama sèmi ji'i, aa bèli-camèda miu mamuri dènge Ama Lamatua ètu sorga kahèi.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Lod'o Ama Lamatua pua Yesus mai, Yesus tao madhutu aa'i dad'èi Lamatua. Dènge j'ara ne, Nèngu nuka sèmi Musa. Te Musa tao madhutu dad'èi Lamatua kahèi, lod'o na ladhe-leru bèi-baki èdhi uru sèra.<bt>When God sent Yesus here, Yesus did according to all of God's will. In that way, He was like Musa. Cuz (elaboration) Musa also did according to God2's will, when he served (doublet) our-inc ancestors (doublet) long ago.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: He [Jesus] was faithful to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: He [Jesus] was faithful to the one [God] who appointed him, just as Moses was faithful in all his [God's] household. pistòn: God could trust him completely to carry out his instructions, especially as priest. Note the initial position, highlighting the quality. "Faithful" embraces not only the idea of carrying out an assignment, but of being the kind of person you could trust to carry it out<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>poieésanti: designate, give him an assignment. The UBS suggestion of "choose" won't work here, because Pidgin "pick" implies that there were other candidates</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 12:7</note><v n="3" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Yesus kapai risi nèti Musa. Te Yesus sama sèmi lamatua èmu. Aa mema lèke, lula lamatua èmu kapai risi nèti ana pua-paleha ètu d'ara èmu.<bt>Even that being the case, nevertheless Yesus is greater/more amazing than Musa. Cuz (elaboration) Yesus is like a head/master of a household. And it is right/true, because the head of household is greater/more amazing than the servants/ workers in that house. [NOTE to daughter translations: although in the Gk this is literally “builder” here, Miller notes that in this verse the Gk has the sense of “founder” of a family who founds, builds and furnishes a family/clan. The Kupang may not be the best fit enough here, so see if your language can do better.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For this one [Jesus] was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For this one [Jesus] was worthy of more glory than Moses, just as the one who builds a house has more honor than the house. oíkou: house, but fits better with "take care God's ohana" in Verse 2. So in Verse 3 it probably shouldn't be just the building. "Start one ohana" works. The key is that Moses was part of the ohana he was helping. Verses 3 and 4 play on different senses of the Greek word; Pidgin doesn't match those senses. "God's house" in the sense of the Jerusalem temple isn't even in focus in either part<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>dóxees: glory; Jesus gets more credit than Moses timeèn: the builder is honored more than the house, or the founder of the lineage is honored more than the lineage that comes from him<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Dhèu èci-èci ka pa'uri d'ara èmu na. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua ka dhu uri aa'i mèu-mèu.<bt>Each person organizes/manages/sets up his own (separate) household. But God manages/oversees everything. [NOTE to daughter translations: try to preserve the “build” verb if possible, but don't force the collocation if it doesn't work. Try bekin. Or manage.] [CHECK /dara èmu/ or /dara èmu-kamali/; use the former]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For every house is built"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For every house is built by someone. But God is the builder of everything.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />De Musa tao madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua, lod'o na j'aj'i ana pua-paleha nèti isi èmu Lamatua. Te lod'o èèna, na peka mema le ngaa dhu bèli-camèd'a Ama Lamatua neo tao.<bt>So (consequently), Musa did according to God's will, when he became a servant/worker (doublet) in God2's household. Cuz (elaboration) at that time, he foretold what God was going to do. [NOTE: TB not helpful here, so don't derail discussions by consulting it.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Moses was indeed faithful as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Moses was indeed faithful as a servant in all his house, for a testimony of those things which were to be spoken later. oikooi: "peopo" rather than "ohana" because he calls them "bruddas an sistas," which is more personal.<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>pistòs: as in Verse 2, not just that he actually did it, but that God could trust him to do it hoos therápoon: a trustworthy servant who worked for God<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Masi ka Yesus madhutu kahèi dad'èi Ama Lamatua, te ngaa Nèngu ana pua-paleha dhu sama boe sèmi Musa. Lula Nèngu ne, Kristus, Ana Ama Lamatua dhu Ama Lamatua hag'e nare le karèi nèti uru ka, sèna ka pua mai asa rai-haha ne. Aa Kristus ne'a mèu uri isi èmu Ama Na. De ladhe èdhi kèpe pa'èra-èra lalèka èdhi, aa ma'ète boe sanao-maena èdhi mi Kristus, èdhi bisa j'aj'i isi èmu Na kahèi.<bt>Even though Yesus also did according to God's will, nevertheless He was not a servant/worker (doublet) like Musa. Because He was/is the Kristus, God's Child whom He had chosen beforehand from long ago, to send here to this world (doublet). And Kristus knows how to correctly/properly manage/ oversee His Father's household. So (consequently), if/when we-inc hold firmly to our beliefs, and we do not cease to hope in Kristus, we also can become (a member of /part of) His household.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But Christ as a son"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But Christ as a son over his [God's] house, whose house we are, if we hold fast the [confidence/courage] and the [pride/ boasting] [of/in] [the hope/what we hope for]. dè: Christ unexpectedly in contrast to Moses<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>hoos huiòs: not "was God's Son" but "Christ was in the character of a son in charge of the family home or family line. He's still following out the household or lineage metaphor parresían: openness and freedom with which believers approach God, and as a consequence, the courage with which they approach even enemies<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>kaúcheema tées elpídos: boasting, pride, here not in a negative sense from pride, but more positive, like boldness and confidence -- we know what's going to happen, and we feel very positive about telling people about it.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku tèke eele parcaya miu sama sèmi bèi-baki miu, lula rèngu bisa boe ae rare d'ara ra ètu rai dhu Ama Lamatua pajaji tèke le<bt>Don't leave behind/abandon your-pl belief like your ancestors', because they didn't rest in the land that God had promised</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i pasa dhilu paie-iie, ho nanene pabe'a ngaa dhu Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci peka, na,<bt>That's why you-pl must fasten ears well to listen carefully to what it is that God's Holy Spirit has said, that,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ae rare dara = istirahat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">ae rare dara = istirahat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Doe ne'e, ropa miu tadèngi lii Ama Lamatua,<bt>“This day, when you-pl listen to what God has to say,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: So, as the Holy Spirit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: So, as the Holy Spirit says, "Today if you will hear his voice, dió: in view of all this, as a result of what I have just been telling you, linking in a general way with what has gone before<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>eàn: more like English "when" than "if" -- he's about to tell them what God said, and he wants them to obey it phoonées autóu: In the context of Verse 6, probably Christ's voice, rather than the voice of God. "Hearing his voice" doesn't mean "hear the sound but pay no attention"; it refers to the content, not the medium, and stands in antithesis to "don't be stubborn", so it must mean "hear and heed" or "pay attention and change" or "listen to what he says"<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="8" />mage miu kètu hadhu,<bt>you-pl should not be stubborn (Idiom: rock head),</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakètu eete = sembarangan, sonde mau"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pakètu eete = sembarangan, sonde mau tau</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sama sèmi dhèu sèra,<bt>like those people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu lasi-mai èpa nguru tèu ètu pad'a sod'a.<bt>who went going-coming for 40 years in the empty land. [CHECK /rai goro/]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai goro = tampa sunyi (rare),"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">rai goro = tampa sunyi (rare), afraid if you go there ; pad'a soda = wide empty area/field</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te rèngu ro'o heka puai-pahae Musa,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) they didn't want to pay attention to/give consideration to Musa anymore,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">toke Ama Lamatua mesa Na<bt>to the point that God himself</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">oe taha nare heka d'ara Na.<bt>very nearly lost patience with them. [EXEG: from Ex. Summ. that they tested God's patience.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Do not be stubborn as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Do not be stubborn as you were in the rebellion, during the time of testing in the wilderness, parapikrasmóoi: rebellion against Moses' leadership<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>peirasmóu: pushed God hard to see if he would let them get away with what they were doing</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9-10" />Pangee ku laa!<bt>Just imagine!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èpa nguru tèu kateme Ja'a tao rupa-rupa tadha malaa<bt>(For) 40 years I made various sorts of *amazing signs</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ètu katanga madha ra!<bt>before their eyes!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa ra loe boe sèku Ja'a.<bt>But they didn't cease to test my mettle/character/ patience continually. (to see what He is made of/how respond)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: When your ancestors tested me,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: When your ancestors tested me, tried me, and saw my actions forty years. dokimasíaai: put to the test<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>éidon tà érga mou: either "in spite of the fact that they had seen the good I had done them for forty years past" or "and they saw the harm I did to them for the next forty years". The latter fits in better with Verse 17. mou: There is a shift from "the Holy Spirit saying" in Verse 7 to "God saying" in Verse 9<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a nasa dènge ra, peka na,<bt>That is why I was angry with them, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Miu se, seli-kolane!<bt>‘You-pl here are too much!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te miu soro kabodho tèke eele j'ara Ja'a,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) You have turned your back and abandoned My way (=rejection),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho madhutu j'ara miu dhu koe-kapengo!&gt;<bt>so you could follow your own crooked (doublet) path!’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: So I was angry with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: So I was angry with that generation, and said, "[Their hearts are always going astray/ they are always disloyal], and they [have not known my ways/ refuse to obey my commands]. planóontai: stray from the path, go the wrong way, make the wrong choice, are disloyal to me<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>téei kardíaai: their minds and wills are directed away from God's will</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="11" />Ropa kèdhi bhabhelu miu, Ja'a ru'a.<bt>When I see your evil, I want to vomit (=can't tolerate it).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ru'a = mau muntah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">ru'a = mau muntah</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a dhoo miu, peka na,<bt>That is why I curse (doublet) you, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">&lt;Miu bisa boe mai ho ae mere d'ara mi, sama-sama dènge Ja'a.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>‘You may no longer come to rest together with Me.’”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: So I swore in my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: So I swore in my wrath, 'They will never enter into my rest.' eiseleúsontai: enter. Could refer to entering the land where they would rest<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>katápausin: resting place; not to be equated with eireénee. Relaxing and strengthening after hardship, or finding peace and prosperity after a period of trial and testing</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:7-11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 95:7-11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />De a'ari aa'i-aa'i! Mage nèti miu abhu ca dhèu dhu tao bhelu, toke nèngu parcaya heka, hèia na soro kabodho mi Ama Lamatua dhu mamuri toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>So (consequently), siblings! Be careful lest there are those among you-pl who do evil, to the point that he does not believe anymore, and then turns his back on God who lives forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Brothers, [pay attention/be careful] that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Brothers, [pay attention/be careful] that none of you have an evil, heart of unbelief that turns away from the living God.</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Be'a risi bèli-bèli miu pa'èra d'ara, èci dènge èci. Baku pamata ia ka! Lula miu dhu malai lèke tipu ka tao sasala, toke miu kètu hadhu aa pusi-pahae boe Ama Lamatua.<bt>It is better, each day you strengthen/encourage each other's insides. Don't delay anymore! Because you-pl are easily/quickly decieved to do wrong/sin, to the point that you also become stubborn, and don't pay attention to/care for (doublet) God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But encourage each other every"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But encourage each other every day as long as it is called 'Today', that no one be hardened by the deceitfulness of sin. allá: in contrast to having an evil heart<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>apáteei tées hamartías: you do something wrong, and that deceives you and gets you off the track</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Èdhi bisa pa'angalai dènge Yesus Kristus, sad'i baku pama'ète sanao mi Nèngu, nuka sèmi ropa èdhi heka parcaya Nèngu.<bt>We-inc can be mutual friends with Yesus Kristus, as long as we do not cease to hope in/depend on Him, like when we had just begun to believe in Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For we have been made"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For we have been made [partakers in /sharers in] Christ, if we hold firm to the end the confidence we had at first. métochoi: partners, like the fishermen in Luke 5:7. Used in 1:9, 3:1, 6:4, and 12:8, in the sense of sharing a common experience. It doesn't mean "divvying up the inheritance", which is one sense of "share" in English<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, peka le kahèi, na,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God's Holy Spirit has spoken, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Doe ne'e, ladhe miu tadèngi lii Ama Lamatua,<bt>“This day, if/when you-pl hear what God is saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">miu baku kètu hadhu sama sèmi dhèu se'e se,<bt>you-pl should not be stubborn, like those people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu lasi-mai toke èpa nguru tèu ètu pad'a sod'a,<bt>who went going-coming for 40 years in the empty land,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te rèngu lab'a Musa.&gt;&gt;<bt>cuz (elaboration) they opposed/rebelled against Musa.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: As was said, &quot;Today if"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: As was said, "Today if you will hear his voice, do not harden your hearts as in the rebellion." This needs to be word for word the same as 7b-8a. It's a resumption of the quotation, this timing leading up to "rebelled", which is where Verse 16 takes off<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="3:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 95:7-8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />De ja'a neo karèi sèmi ne'e: cee ka dhu uru èèna nanene Musa, hèia ra pusi-pahae heka ne? Dhèu sèra nuka bèi-baki èdhi dhu Musa lere si nèti rai Masir.<bt>So (consequently), I want to ask like this: who was it who had been listening to Musa, and then no longer cared about/attended to him? Thos people were our-inc ancestors (doublet) whom Musa had led/brought out from the land of Masir (=Egypt).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Who were they who heard"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Who were they who heard and rebelled? Wasn't it all who were led out of Egypt by Moses?</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Aa dhèu cee ka dhu tao d'ara Ama Lamatua pana magoro d'ai èpa nguru tèu èèna? Dhèu sèra nuka bèi-baki èdhi. Te mamuri ra koe-kapengo ètu d'ara pad'a sod'a, toke ra madhe, ka padhane si ètu nèi.<bt>And who was it that made God's insides really hot (=angry) for 40 years? Those people were our ancestors (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) they lived crooked (doublet) in the empty land, until they died, and then were buried there (remote).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And with whom was he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And with whom was he angry for forty years? Wasn't it those who sinned, [whose bodies were left/ who fell down dead] in the wilderness?</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Aa cee ka dhu lèke kutuk nèti Ama Lamatua, toke bisa boe maso asa rai èèna, sèna ka ae rare d'ara ra sama-sama dènge Lamatua? Dhèu sèra nuka bèi-baki èdhi. Te rèngu se ro'o boe nanene Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>And who was it who were cursed by God to the point they were not allowed to enter into that land, to rest together with God2? Those people were our ancestors. Cuz (elaboration) they didn't want to listen to/obey God.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And to whom did God"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And to whom did God swear that they would never enter his rest but to those who did not believe.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:16-18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 14:1-35</note><v n="19" />De me'a le, si? Bèi-baki èdhi bisa boe maso asa d'ara rai èèna, ho ae rare d'ara ra sama-sama dènge Ama Lamatua, lula ra parcaya boe Ne.<bt>So (consequently), it is already clear, right? Our ancestors (doublet) couldn't enter into that land, to rest together with God, because they did not believe/trust in Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And we see that they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And we see that they could not enter in because of unbelief.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ladhe èdhi parcaya Yesus Kristus, èdhi bisa mamuri padame dènge Ama Lamatua, nuka sèmi èdhi ae tare d'ara dènge Ne<bt>If/when we believe in Yesus Kristus, we can live at (relational) peace with God, just like we are resting with Him</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Te ngaa èdhi hud'i pangee madhera ku, lula Lamatua dhu pajaji era, na, dhèu unu Na bisa ae rare d'ara ra sama-sama dènge Nèngu. De mage dhoka abhu nèti miu dhu tule eele lii pajaji Lamatua ne.<bt>But now we-inc must think long (Idiom: = think through the implications), because God2 still promises that His people can rest together with Him. So (consequently), may it not be that there are those among you-pl who throw away/reject what God2 has promised.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: A promise was left to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: A promise was left to us of entering into his rest. Therefore let us fear, lest, any of you be found to have come short of it. katápausin: place of rest, quoting 3:11<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>dokéei: not "seem", but "turn out, be judged by God to have failed" autóu: God's rest -- if expressed with "give", it still doesn't necessarily require "you guys", unless that's more natural in Pidgin<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Te èdhi dhu tadèngi le Lii Lolo Be'a, sama sèmi bèi-baki èdhi uru sèra tadèngi. Te ngaa, lula rèngu lèka boe lii èèna, rèngu abhu boe oto ngaa-ngaa.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) we-inc have heard that Good News, just like our ancestors (doublet) also heard (it) long ago. But because they didn't believe that voice/news/ message, they got no benefit/advantage/profit whasoever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For the Good News was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For the Good News was announced to us just as to them. But the message that was heard did not profit them, because it was not mixed with faith by those who heard it. pístei: there is an implication, because of the "we had the Gospel preached to us too", that unlike them, we believed it. That is spelled out in the next verse<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Te ngaa ladhe èdhi parcaya, èdhi bisa ae tare d'ara bera-bera dènge Ama Lamatua. Te uru èèna, Nèngu dhu pajaji le dènge bèi-baki èdhi, te ngaa lula Na nasa, hèia Na peka dènge ra, na,<bt>But if we believe, we can rest together with God. Cuz formerly, He is the one who had promised like that to our ancestors (doublet), but becuase He was angry, He told them, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a taha heka ladhe kèdhi tatao bhabhelu miu ne.<bt>“I cannot stand any longer to watch your evil deeds/behaviour.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a dhoo miu, peka na,<bt>That is why I curse (doublet) you saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Miu bisa boe maso,<bt>‘You are no longer allowed to enter,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho ae mere d'ara sama-sama dènge Ja'a.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>to rest together with Me.’” [same as 3:11]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Aa te ngaa èdhi te'a le, na, lod'o Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i liru dènge rai-haha, Nèngu ator nare le, sèna ka dhèu-dhèu unu Na bisa ae rare d'ara, ho mamuri bera-bera dènge Ne.<bt>Whereas we know that when God created the sky and earth (doublet), He had already arranged so that His people could rest, to live together with Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For we who have believed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For we who have believed do enter into rest. As he said, "As I have sworn in my wrath, they will never enter into my rest," although the works were finished from the foundation of the world. geneethéntoon: the things he was going to do were already in place, planned ahead. Not, God finished working at creation, and hasn't done anything since<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="4:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 95:11</note><v n="4" />Ètu lii lolo nèti Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i liru dènge rai-haha, dhu suri, Ama Lamatua ae nare d'ara, peka na,<bt>In the story about God creating heaven and earth (doublet), it is written about God resting, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Lamatua sab'a nare aa'i le,<bt>“[After] God2 had finished doing/working all that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">hèia asa bèli èèna, lèke dènge lod'o ka pidhu,<bt>then the following day, right on the seventh day,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Na ae nare d'ara.&gt;&gt;<bt>He rested.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Because it says in a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Because it says in a certain place of the seventh day like this: "God rested the seventh day from all his works." pou: somewhere, in a part of the text he doesn't feel he needs to identify for these readers<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="4:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 2:2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Aa dhu suri ètu era leo hari, Ama Lamatua peka dènge bèi-baki èdhi, na,<bt>And written in a different place, God spoke to our-inc ancestors (doublet), saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Miu bisa heka maso,<bt>“You-pl may no longer enter,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho ae mere d'ara mi sama-sama dènge Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>to rest together with Me.” [same as 3:11]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And in this place again,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And in this place again, "They will never enter into my rest." en toútooi pálin: in the same quotation from the Old Testament that I was just discussing<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="4:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 95:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />De dad'èi Ama Lamatua ka, dhèu unu Na ae rare d'ara ra sèna ka mamuri sama-sama dènge Ne. Te ngaa bèi-baki èdhi dhu tadèngi uuru lii lolo be'a ne, rèngu bisa boe maso, lula rèngu tao boe madhutu dad'èi Lamatua.<bt>So (consequently), God wants for His people to rest to live together with Him. But our ancestors (doublet) who first heard that good news, they could not enter, because they did not follow/obey God2's will.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore since it is left"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore since it is left for some to enter in, and those to whom it was first announced did not enter because of unbelief, katápausin: still the same quotation first given in 3:11 being repeated<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu, Lamatua hag'e nare lod'o èci, sèna ka dhèu unu Na bisa ae rare d'ara ra sama-sama dènge Nèngu. Te Na pake Daud ho padhai lii, peka na,<bt>But eventually, God2 chose a (different) time, for His people to be able to rest together with Him. Cuz (elaboration) He used Daud to speak, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Doe ne'e, ladhe miu tadèngi lii Ama Lamatua,<bt>“This day, if/when you-pl hear God speaking,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">mage miu tao d'ara mi adhu sèmi hadhu,<bt>don't make your insides hard like rock (=cold-hearted, unreceptive, hard-hearted),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">te ngaa nanene paie-iie.&gt;&gt;<bt>but listen carefully.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Again, he set a certain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Again, he set a certain day, saying by David after so long a time in the place already quoted, "Today, if you hear his voice, do not harden your hearts."</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 95:7-8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Lod'o Daud peka na, &lt;&lt;doe ne'e&gt;&gt;, nèngu paj'uj'u boe asa lod'o dhu Yosua lere ana-èpu nèti bèi-baki se asa rai Kana'an. Te lod'o Daud padhai lii ne, rèngu aa'i-aa'i dhu madhe nèbhu le.<bt>When Daud spoke saying, “this day”, he was not pointing to that day when Yosua lead the ancestors' children/offspring into the land of Kana'an. Cuz (elaboration) when Daud spoke that, all of them were long dead.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For if Joshua had given"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For if Joshua had given them rest, he would not have talked later about another day. ouk àn ... elálei: God is probably the subject, but may not need to be made explicit<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="4:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 31:7, Yosua 22:4</note><v n="9" />Nèti èèna ka èdhi te'a, na, Lamatua ator le lod'o dhu leo èci, sèna ka dhèu-dhèu unu Na bisa ae rare d'ara ra, ho mamuri pa'èci dènge Ne.<bt>Because of that, we know that, God2 is the one who had arranged a different time, for His people to be able to rest, to live united/joined with Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: So there remains a sabbath"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: So there remains a sabbath rest for the people of God. sabbatismòs: may have been invented by the author, from Hebrew shavat. A rest like when God rested on the seventh day. Another angle is that you could say that all human history has been part of God's rest day, but not all humans have gotten in on the resting part. It's still talking about resting, but shifts the emphasis to the time, and away from Joshua's actual occupation of the Promised Land<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Aa dhèu dhu maso le sèna ka ae nare d'ara na sama-sama dènge Ama Lamatua, nèngu dhu ae nare le nèti sasab'a-la'a na, sama sèmi Lamatua kahèi ae nèti sasab'a-la'a Na, lèke dènge lod'o ka pidhu.<bt>And a person who enters to rest together with God, s/he has ceased from his work/responsibilities (doublet), just like God2 also stopped His work right at the seventh day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For he who has entered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For he who has entered into his rest, has also ceased from his own works just as God did from his own. CHIASM: This one seems not to work, and needs to be recast as a parallelism, possibly because it's short and obvious. Other chiasms don't necessary cause trouble, especially if they are long enough.<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>autóu: God causes people to rest. It isn't their doing ho gàr eiselthoòn: not a reference to a specific person, but anybody who fits the qualifications. Pidgin's nonspecific "you" seems less awkward here than "anybody" or "whoeva" or "somebody" or "peopo", because the others are third person and they get crossed up with God, who is also third person<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>katápausin: getting away from the "land where they can rest" meaning and into more of a "situation in which you can rest" meaning, now that we've left Joshua</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 2:2</note><v n="11" />De bori pa'èra ho miu bisa maso ae mere d'ara, sèna ka mamuri sama-sama dènge Ama Lamatua. Mage dhoka abhu dhu j'aj'i boe maso, lula nèngu nanene boe Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua, cakaraa bèi-baki èdhi sèra.<bt>So (consequently) strive/struggle/work hard so you-pl can enter (and) rest together with God. May it not be that there are those who are not able to enter, because s/he does not want to listen to/obey God2's Words/Saying, like those ancestors of ours-inc.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore let us make every"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore let us make every effort to enter into that rest, so that nobody will fall by following the same example of unbelief.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Te Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua ka dhu paj'uj'u j'ara mamuri dhu lèke. Lii se'e dhu dènge koasa ho maso asa d'ara èdhi, sèna ka pasoro ngangee dènge dad'èi èdhi aa'i-aa'i. Te Lii Holo-Nori se, dhu madèka titu kèna, risi nèti hela madèka dhu bisa sabhi eele isi, aa j'ue eele kalua dènge sèg'i rui, sèna ka pasabhoka aa'i.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God's Words/Sayings show the right/true/correct way of life. These words have the power/authority to enter into our-inc insides, to compare all our thoughts and our desires. Cuz (elaboration) those Words/Sayings are really sharp, more than a sharp sword/machete which can cut away meat (off bones), cut/separate tendons and split bones, to reveal/expose everything.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jojo = test to see how"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">jojo = test to see how many carats the gold is (jojo hualaa), 9ct, 24ct, etc. ; pasoro = banding, timbang ; madèka = tajam ; hela = parang ; sabhi = cut meat off bones ; d'ole = marrow, sumsum (BI) ; kalua = urat ; sèg'i = belah (tulang) ; pasabhoka = reveal, open up (nothing hidden).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For the Word of God"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For the Word of God is alive/living, and active/ effective, and sharper than any two-edged sword, penetrating even to the separating/dividing of soul and spirit, and of joints and marrow, and is a discerner/judge of the thoughts/reflections/ideas and intentions/attitudes/ motives of the heart. distomos: Check Revelation, match 1:16 and 2:12.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ètu dedha-liru dènge rai-haha, abhu boe èci sa dhu pahuni nèti Ama Lamatua, te Nèngu bisa nèdhi aa'i mèu-mèu. Aa bèli-camèd'a èdhi hud'i lati asa katanga madha Na, sèna ka ti dhaa aa'i, ngaa dhu èdhi ad'u-ue.<bt>Throughout the whole sky and earth (doublet), there is nothing which can be hidden from God, cuz (elaboration) He can see everything clearly. And later we-inc must go before Him (as in reporting to an authority), to respond/account for on everything we have done (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: There is no creature that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: There is no creature that is [hidden/covered] before him, but everything is uncovered and open/exposed to his eyes to whom we have to [give account/deal]. pròs hòn heemíin ho lógos: includes the idea of a reckoning, more than just a statement that God will be our judge. UBS suggests it's not just talking about the final judgment, but the continual process of living without being able to hide anything from God<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yesus j'aj'i le kètu kapai risi agama dhu risi nèti ama agama dhu uru sèra<bt>Yesus has become a *high priest who is more than priests of old</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Èdhi hud'i kèpe ku pa'èra-èra lalèka èdhi, lula Ana Ama Lamatua, Yesus, dhu j'aj'i le kètu kapai risi agama èdhi. Te Nèngu ètu le madha Ama Lamatua ètu sorga, sèna ka sarii èdhi.<bt>We-inc must hold firmly to our belief2, because God's Child, Yesus, has become our *highest priest (see discussion at Heb. 2:17). Cuz (elaboration) He is already in front of God in heaven, to defend (oral, legal) us.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Since we have a great"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Since we have a great high priest, who has gone into heaven, Jesus the Son of God, let us hold firmly to what we profess/confess. archieréa: this is not new information. It's a return to 2:17, picking up an argument. It shouldn't be highlighted<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>mégan: outstanding, prominent dieleelythóta: one who has gone clear through to the ultimate Heaven, another way of talking about the presence of God. Like Matthew, this writer would rather not mention God by name if he doesn't have to<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>homologías: stating publicly what we believe, going on record that we trust Christ</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Na bisa sarii èdhi dènge be'a, lula ne'a, èdhi dhèu rai-haha biasa. Ladhe abhu dhu dadugu-rariu èdhi ho tao sala, na, èdhi manahu malai. Yesus abhu dadugu-rariu kahèi sama sèmi èdhi, te ngaa Na manahu nèdhi boe.<bt>He is able to defend us well, because He understands that we are human. If there are (those) who (try to) persuade/goad (doublet) us-inc to do wrong/sin, we fall/succumb easily/quickly. Yesus has also experienced tempting/testing/ been bothered (doublet) like us, but He has never fallen.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For we do not have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For we do not have a high priest who cannot sympathize with the feeling of our weaknesses, but one who was in every way tempted like we are, but did not sin.</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Nèti èèna ka, mai ti pabani d'ara ho ara lati asa madha Ama Lamatua dhu ètu kadera paredha Na. Te Nèngu ne, d'ara hua iia. De ladhe èdhi sabaj'a mi Nèngu, tatu Na neo pad'elo rasa kasia Na, ho soru-bara èdhi lèke dènge lod'o na.<bt>Because of that, let's be bold/ have the courage to come before God on His governing/ ruling chair. Cuz (elaboration) He is good/gracious/ kind/generous. So (consequently), if/when we pray to Him, surely He will show/demonstrate His mercy/pity to us and help (doublet) us at the right time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Nèti èèna ka, èdhi madha'u boe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Nèti èèna ka, èdhi madha'u boe lati manèngi Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi èèna ho soru èdhi.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore let us come boldly"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore let us come boldly before the throne of grace, that we may obtain mercy, and find grace to help in time of need. tóoi thrónooi tées cháritos: another indirect way of speaking about God. It's God who is gracious, and he is the one we approach; the throne is incidental<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>eúkairon: right at the time we need it, not delayed boeétheian: meet our need, or other people's -- it is left open<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1" />Dhèu dhu ded'e rare j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama, sasab'a na, hud'i soru-bara dhèu, sèna ka rèngu pabe'a dènge Ama Lamatua. Nèngu hud'i sèmi nare ku mèdha persembahan dènge badha korban, ho saraka asa Lamatua. Nèngu kahèi hia badha korban, sèna ka Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo dhèu.<bt>The person whom they elevated/appointed to become the *high priest, his job/responsibility was to help (doublet) people to be in a reciprocally right relationship with God. He must receive their *offerings and their animal sacrifices/animals for sacrifice, to turn over/surrender them to God2. He must also sacrifice animals so God2 would wipe away people's wrongs (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sèna ka rèngu bisa patadha dènge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">sèna ka rèngu bisa patadha dènge Ama Lamatua.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For every high priest is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For every high priest is chosen from among men and is appointed to represent them in matters related to God, to offer gifts and sacrifices for sins.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu re'a boe j'ara mamuri dhu lèke, do dhèu dhu rai eele nèti j'ara èèna, kètu agama ne pasusa boe rèngu. Nèti d'ara hua iia na, nèngu lii mako dènge ra, lula nèngu kahèi dhèu rai-haha dhu mud'a manahu, sama sèmi rèngu.<bt>If there is a person who doesn't know/ recognise the right/true way of life, or (there is) a person who has gone off-track/deviated from that way, that *priest doesn't make trouble for them. He is kind/ gracious/good to them, because he also is a human who can fall easily just like them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="metriopathew: moderate one's feeling, deal gently,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">metriopathew: moderate one's feeling, deal gently, capacity for calm and gentle judgment, moderation, leniency [make gentle kine] planaw: go astray, be misled, wander about, be deluded, be deceived<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>LITERALLY: He is able to deal gently with those who are ignorant and are going astray, since he himself is subject to weakness.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Lula nèngu kahèi dhèu rai-haha sama sèmi rèngu, nèti èèna ka kètu agama ne hud'i hia badha korban, ho Lamatua saku pamèu sasala nèngu mesa na.<bt>Because he is also a human like them, that is why that *priest must also make an animal sacrifice so God2 will wipe away his own wrong(s).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: This is why he has"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: This is why he has to make sacrifices for his own sins, as well as for the sins of the people.</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 9:7</note><v n="4" />Dhèu bisa boe ded'e iisi na, sèna ka j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama. Te dhoka Ama Lamatua di dhu dènge hak, sèna ka hag'e nare dhèu sèmi èèna, nuka sèmi uru-uru sèra Na ded'e Harun, a'a Musa.<bt>A person may not elevate/appoint himself to become *high piest. Cuz (elaboration) only God is the one who has the rights to choose a person like that, just like long ago when He elevated/appointed Musa's older-sibling Harun.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: No one takes this honor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: No one takes this honor upon himself; he must be called by God, just as Aaron was.</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 28:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge Kristus. Na ded'e boe iisi Na, ho j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama. Te uru èèna, Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka dhu ded'e Ne, peka na,<bt>It is the same way with Kristus. He did not appoint Himself to become *highest priest. Cuz (elaboration) long ago, God himself is the one who appointed Him, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Èu ne, Ana Ja'a,<bt>“You are My Child,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Doe ne'e, Ja'a ded'e Èu ho mèd'u paredha.&gt;&gt;<bt>today I have appointed you to rule/hold government.” [EXEG: this verse quoting Ps. 2:7 in KM Acts 13:32-33 builds on the context of coronation from Ps. 2:6. Otherwise, outside of adoption or coronation, why would anyone make this non-sensical statement that is incoherent in most English translations?]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: So Christ also did not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: So Christ also did not take upon himself the glory of becoming a high priest. But God said to him, "You are my Son; today I have become your Father."</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ètu era leo nèti Sasuri Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, dhu suri kahèi, peka na,<bt>In a different place in God2's Holy Writings, He also wrote, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Èu j'aj'i kètu agama dhu ca ropa dènge ca dhèu dhu mamuri uru èèna, nuka Melkisedek,<bt>“You are/will become a *priest of the same type/model/kind as a person who lived long ago, named Melkisedek. [NOTE to daughter translations: if what was assumed general knowledge to Jews, but not to your crowd needs clarification, try: /yang satu model deng satu orang yang idop dolu-dolu, andia Melkisedek./ See Dhao.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Èu ne, j'aj'i ama agama toke"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Èu ne, j'aj'i ama agama toke dai mia-mia, ; Èu j'aj'i kètu agama dhu ca ropa dènge Melkisedek, dhu mamuri uru èèna.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa Èu j'aj'i kètu agama toke d'ai mia-mia.&gt;&gt;<bt>but (contrary to expectation) you will be a priest forever.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sama sèmi ama agama Melkisedek dhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">sama sèmi ama agama Melkisedek dhu uru-uru èèna.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And it says in another"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And it says in another place, "You are a priest forever, of the [priestly] order of Melchizedek."</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ètu lod'o oe èle mamuri Yesus ètu rai-haha ne, Na loe boe sabaj'a dènge tangi d'ara pèd'a, manèngi Ama Lamatua sèna ka hia Ne a'èra. Te ne'a, na, koasa Lamatua bisa hia Ne mamuri. Hèia Ama Lamatua sèmi nare lii manèngi Yesus, lula Na madhutu mola-mola dad'èi Lamatua.<bt>When Yesus' life on this earth was about to end, He prayed without ceasing with cries of grief, asking God to give Him strength. Cuz (elaboration) He knew that God2's power/authority could save Him. And God accepted Yesus' request, because He truly followed/obeyed God2's will.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: During the days of Jesus'"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: During the days of Jesus' life on earth, he offered up prayers and petitions with loud cries and tears to the One who could save him from death, and he was heard because of his reverent submission.</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 26:36-46, Markus 14:32-42, Lukas 22:39-46</note><v n="8" />Te Yesus ne, Ana Ama Lamatua. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Nèngu hud'i pasae ku j'aj'èra, ho ne'a madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) that Yesus is/was God's Child. Even that being the case, nevertheless He had to experience difficulty/suffering, to know/learn how to follow/obey God2's will.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Although he was a son,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Although he was a son, he learned obedience from what he suffered.</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Èle èèna ka, Na tao madhutu mola-mola dad'èi Lamatua aa'i-aa'i. Nèti èèna ka, Nèngu j'aj'i le Kapua Mamuri bagi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu parcaya Ne, ho mamuri taruu dènge Ama Lamatua.<bt>So He really did truly follow/obey all of God2's will. That is why now He has become the Tree/Source of Life/Salvation for all people who believe in Him, so they can live continually with God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Being made perfect, he became"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Being made perfect, he became the source of eternal salvation fo all who obey him.</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Te Lamatua ded'e nare le Yesus j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama, ca ropa dènge Melkisedek, dhu j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama uru sèra.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God2 has already appointed Yesus to be *high priest, who is the same model/type/kind as the high priest Melkisedek from long ago.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And was designated by God"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And was designated by God to be high priest, just like Melchizedek.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku tèke eele parcaya miu mi Kristus<bt>Don't put away/get rid of your belief in Kristus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />J'ara ae era dhu ja'a neo lole dènge miu lula-nèti Kristus dènge Melkisedek, te ngaa ako carui paled'a j'ara se'e, lula miu nuka sèmi ana iiki dhu me'a mèu mèka dènge be'a.<bt>There are still many things which I want to say to you-pl about Kristus and Melkisedek, but it is difficult for me to clarify those things, because you-pl are still like small children who are not yet able to fully understand well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: We have much to say"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: We have much to say about this, but it is hard to explain because you have become [slow to learn / dull of hearing].</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Aa te ngaa, miu dhu parcaya nèbhu le. Madhutu iia-iia na, miu j'aj'i le mese ho aj'a-nori dhèu leo. Te ngaa te'a boe na, miu cakaraa ana rara iisi hiu, dhu ne'a mèka na'a, te ne'a dhoka ninu susu di. Miu parluu dhèu era ho aj'a miu lula-nèti j'ara-j'ara dhu carui mèka nèti Sasuri Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci.<bt>Whereas in fact, you have already believed for a long time. What should be the case, is that you-pl should already be teachers, so you could teach (doublet) other people. But contrary to what one would expect, you are still like newborns who are not yet able to eat, cuz (elaboration) you only know how to just drink milk. You still need people to teach you basic things/issues from the *God2's Holy Writings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For by this time you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For by this time you ought to be teachers, but you need someone to teach you the beginning truths of God's Word all over again. You need milk, not solid food!</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ja'a pakasame miu dènge ana rara iisi hiu, lula miu me'a mèka j'ara-j'ara dhu carui boe nèti Kristus, sèna ka miu bisa mamuri mola.<bt>I compare you to newborns like that, because you do not yet truly understand the various things that are not really difficult about Kristus so that you can live straight/righteous.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Everyone who uses milk, being"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Everyone who uses milk, being still an infant, is not acquainted with the teaching about righteousness.</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:12-13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 3:2</note><v n="14" />Te ngaa lod'o ana iiki ne kapai, nèngu ninu heka susu, te ngaa na'a nganga'a dhu sakaa. Èèna èci èèna ka, dènge dhèu aj'a ne toke ne'a mèu a'aj'a Lamatua, sèna ka ne'a mia ka dhu be'a, aa mia ka dhu karehe.<bt>But when a small child grows up, he doesn't drink milk anymore but eats solid food. That is like a person teaches him/her to the point that s/he truly understands God2's teachings, so that s/he knows which (of choices) is/are good, and which is/are evil.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But solid food is for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But solid food is for the [mature / grown up], who by constant use have trained themselves to distinguish good from evil.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1" />De miu hud'i aj'a paie-iie ku a'aj'a dhu carui risi, lula miu dhu aj'a nèbhu ae le a'aj'a dhu carui mèka lula-nèti Kristus. Nèti èèna ka limuri ne, baku dhoka aj'a pahari-pahari a'aj'a dhu carui mèka sèra, nuka sèmi: dhèu hud'i tèke eele ku sasala rèngu aa'i-aa'i; a'aj'a lula-nèti dhèu hud'i parcaya ku Ama Lamatua;<bt>So (consequently), you-pl must learn/study the more difficult lessons/teachings, because you have been learning for a long time the not very difficult teachings about Kristus. That is why now, you should not need to study over and over the not difficult teachings, like: people having to leave behind/abandon all their wrongs; teachings about people needing to believe in God;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore, let us leave the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore, let us leave the elementary teachings about Christ and go on to maturity. Let us not lay again the foundation of repentance from acts that lead to death, and of faith in God,</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />a'aj'a lula-nèti sarani; a'aj'a lula-nèti bane ai mi dhèu sèna ka dhèu èèna sèmi nare Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci; a'aj'a lula-nèti Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari dhèu nèti mamadhe ra; aa a'aj'a dhu èèna na dhèu lasi asa katanga madha Lamatua, ho sèmi rare lii pama'ète, dhu peka na, cee ka dhu bisa mamuri taa-taa dènge Ne, aa cee ka dhu bisa boe.<bt>teachings about *baptism; teachings about placing hands on people so they receive God2's Holy Spirit; teachings about God causing people to live again from their death; and teachings about people later going before God2 to receive His decision/judgement about who may live continually with Him, and who cannot. [EXEG: HS has support from Ex.Summ, and Miller, but may be a bit narrow.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soro ; bane = sonto dari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">soro ; bane = sonto dari atas</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: instruction about baptisms, the laying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: instruction about baptisms, the laying on of hands, the resurrection of the dead, and eternal judgment.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Te ngaa ladhe Lamatua hia ijin, na, èdhi j'aj'i heka ana iiki dhu te'a dhoka tinu susu di. Te ja'a neo aj'a j'ara-j'ara dhu carui risi hari.<bt>But if/when God2 give permission/allows it, na, let's no longer be small children who only know how to drink milk. Cuz (elaboration) I want to teach things that are even more difficult. [NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And this we will do,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And this we will do, if God permits.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4-6" />Aa te ngaa, abhu le dhèu dhu re'a mèu lii a'aj'a Kristus, aa dhu rasa le d'ara hua iia Lamatua kahèi, toke Na hia si Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci. Rèngu re'a le Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua, aa rasa le koasa Na dhu Na neo pake lod'o èle rai-haha ne. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa dhèu se tèke eele le parcaya ra, aa ra soro kabodho mi Kristus. Nèti èèna ka, bisa heka abhu j'ara ho rèngu bisa lèpa hari manèngi abho, sèna ka mamuri pabe'a hari dènge Ama Lamatua. Te ladhe dhèu ro'o boe ele-ho'a, èèna sama sèmi rèngu ka dhu paku pamadhe hari Ana Ama Lamatua ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha, hèia ra nyanyèi Ne ètu madha dhèu ae-ae.<bt>Whereas in fact, there are people who clearly understand Kristus' teachings, and they have already felt/experienced God2's goodness/grace/ kindness/ generosity, to the point that He gave them His Holy Spirit. They already know God2's Words/Sayings, and they have already felt/ experienced His power/authority which He will use when the world ends. Even that being the case, nevertheless they have thrown away/gotten rid of their beliefs, and have turned their backs on Kristus. Because of that, there is no longer a way for them to come back and ask forgiveness (focus on social action), to live in a right.relationship with God. Cuz (elaboration) if a person doesn't want to *repent like that, that is like they are the ones who nail to death again God's Child on the *cross (doublet), and then they mocked/ridiculed Him before many people. [NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nyanyèi = olok-olok (lit. stick out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">nyanyèi = olok-olok (lit. stick out and wiggle tongue as a sign of despising s.o., KM = loo lida</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te dènge j'ara rèngu soro kabodho"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Te dènge j'ara rèngu soro kabodho èèna, nuka sèmi rèngu ka dhu paku pamadhe Ana Ama Lamatua ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha, hèia ra nyanyèi Ne ètu madha dhèu ae-ae.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="light and truth? OK in doublet."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">light and truth? OK in doublet. LITERALLY: It is impossible for those who have once been enlightened, who have tasted the heavenly gift, who have shared in the Holy Spirit,<span class="Italic">(4) </span>LITERALLY: who have tasted the goodness of the word of God and the powers of the coming age, LITERALLY: if they fall away, to be brought back to repentance, because on their own account they are crucifying the Son of God all over again, and subjecting him to public disgrace.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Dhèu sèmi sèra, èci èèna ka dènge rai dhu hèu mèngi boe, nèti èèna ka abhu boe hua-hela dhu be'a. Te ngaa ladhe abhu ka èj'i, rai dhu hèu mèngi bisa hia hua-hela dhu dènge guna mi lamatua oka. Hèia Ama Lamatua papuru mamèngi-nale, sèna ka hua-hela nèti rai ne asa tabha ae.<bt>People of that sort, are like infertile land that produces/ yields produce (doublet) which isn't good. But if/when there is rain, fertile land can yield produce (doublet) that is useful for the farmer/garden master/owner. Then God sends down blessings (doublet), to make that land's produce (doublet) increase greatly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hoa = gugur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">hoa = gugur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Land that drinks in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Land that drinks in the rain often falling on it, and that produces a crop useful to those for whom it is cultivated, receives the blessing of God.</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu soro kabodho mi Kristus, nuka sèmi rai dhu pènu dènge dhudhu dènge sete di. Aa dhudhu-sete se guna boe mi ngaa-ngaa èci sa. Nèbhu boe, Ama Lamatua mai ho huku rai èèna. Hèia Na labhu pakèpu aa'i dhudhu dènge sete se, dhu gaguna ra aad'o.<bt>But the person who turns his back on Kristus, is like land that is full of thorns (doublet-two iconic kinds). And those thorns (doublet) have no use whatsoever. In a short time, God will come to punish that land. Then He will burn off those thorns (doublet) which have no use.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sete = sejenis duri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">sete = sejenis duri</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But land that produces thorns"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But land that produces thorns and thistles is worthless, and is in danger of being cursed. In the end it will be burned.</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 3:17-18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />A'ari pasue! Masi ka ja'a ako padhai lii bia ciki, te ngaa ja'a ke'a kahèi, na, miu rai eele boe Kristus. Te miu parcaya Ne kahèi, aa mamuri miu kahèi abhu hua-hela dhu be'a.<bt>Dear siblings! Even though I am speaking a little heavy/harshly/severely, nevertheless I also know that you have not fled from Kristus. Cuz (elaboration) you-pl believe in Him, and your lives also have good yield/produce (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Dear friends, even though we"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Dear friends, even though we speak like this, we are confident of better things in your case--things that accompany salvation.</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />De sanèd'e, te d'ara Ama Lamatua mola, aa Na bhèlu boe èi kabhèsu miu. Te miu sab'a bia le, sèna ka soru-bara dhèu unu Na sèra, aa mi sue si. Mema karèi nèti uru ka, miu pakako le sasab'a Na. Aa miu pakako taruu sasab'a Na era.<bt>So (consequently) remember, God's straight/right/ just insides, and He doesn't forget your sweat/efforts (=will reward you). Cuz (elaboration) you-pl have worked hard to help (doublet) His people, and you love them. Really, from long ago, you have carried out His work. And you are still carrying out His work.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: God is not unjust; he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: God is not unjust; he will not forget your work, and the love you have shown him as you have helped his people, and continue to help them.</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Te limuri ne, ja'a d'èi ladhe miu sab'a èra risi hari, sèna ka tao madhutu taruu toke pa'èle. Dènge sèmi èèna, miu bèli-camèd'a sèmi mere babe'a aa'i-aa'i dhu miu sanao nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>But2 now, I want you to work even harder, to keep doing that until the end/it is finished. In that way, you will later receive every good thing that you are hoping for from God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: We want each of you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: We want each of you to show this same diligence to the very end, in order to make your hope sure.</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Sad'i miu baku bai-eed'a! Miu hud'i laladhe nèti dhèu dhu parcaya nèbhu le mi Ama Lamatua. Te rèngu tino sanao-maena mi Nèngu, toke ra sèmi rare aa'i dhu Lamatua pajaji le.<bt>As long as you don't become lazy (doublet)! You-pl must observe people who have believed in God for a long time. Cuz (elaboration) they keep hoping/trusting (doublet) in Him, until they have received what He has already promised. [CHECK /tino/ here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="noothroi: contrasts with spoudeen in 11,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">noothroi: contrasts with spoudeen in 11, meaning eagerness LITERALLY: We do not want you to become lazy, but to imitate those who through faith and patience inherit what has been promised.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13-16" />Conto nuka sèmi Abraham. Uru èèna, Ama Lamatua pa'èki lii pajaji dènge ne pake lii subha. Ladhe dhèu rai-haha ded'e subha, nèngu tema pake kolongara Ama Lamatua, sèna ka Lamatua j'aj'i sakasii na, lula Lamatua risi nèti nèngu. Aa ladhe paraga dènge lii langu, dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a, na, lii dhu dhèu ne peka èèna lèke tare'a, lula na subha pake kolongara Ama Lamatua. Èèna mema j'ara dhèu rai-haha kèna. Te ngaa lod'o Ama Lamatua ded'e subha dènge Abraham, Lamatua pake kolongara Nèngu unu Na, lula abhu boe dhu risi nèti Nèngu. Na jaji, peka na,<bt>For example, Abraham. Long ago, God bound a promise with him using an oath. If/when a human takes an oath, s/he usually/often used God's name, so God2 is his witness, because God2 is more than him. And if/when there is a dispute, everyone knows that what that person is saying is true, because s/he has sworn an oath using God's name. That is the way of humans. But when God made an oath with Abraham, God2 used His own name, because there is none who is greater than Him. He promised that,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: When God made his promise"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: When God made his promise to Abraham, since there was no one greater fo him to swear by, he swore by himself,</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Èèna na, Ja'a hia mèngi-nale ae-ae,<bt>“I will give many blessings (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">mi èu dènge ana-èpu mu,<bt>to you-sg and your descendants.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Bèli-camèd'a rèngu bèba-kacanga,<bt>They will later increase (in number) (doublet),</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bèba-kacanga"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">bèba-kacanga</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">toke dhèu bisa boe ige rare si.&gt;&gt;<bt>to the point that people can't (successfully) count them.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: saying, &quot;I will surely bless"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: saying, "I will surely bless you, and give you many descendants."</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:13-16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 22:16-17</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ama Lamatua padadha nare sèmi èèna, hèia Abraham parcaya, aa sanao-maena taruu mi Lamatua, masi ka d'ai nèbhu ae ku, heka sèmi nare ngaa dhu Lamatua pajaji sèra.<bt>[When] God had finished promising like that, then Abraham believed and kept hoping/trusting (doublet) in God2, even if/though it would be a long time before he received what God2 had promised.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dai nèbhu j'oo aae = lama-lama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">dai nèbhu j'oo aae = lama-lama dulu ; j'oo aae = sedikit banyak, sedikit besar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And so after waiting patiently,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And so after waiting patiently, Abraham received what was promised. LITERALLY: People swear by someone greater than themselves, and the oath confirms what is said and puts an end to all argument.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Dènge j'ara ne, èdhi te'a, ladhe Lamatua pa'èki lii pajaji dènge dhèu unu Na, Nèngu pa'èki lii pajaji ne pake subha, ho j'aj'i mi tate'a, ngaa dhu Na moa èèna, mema lèke aa ub'a boe.<bt>In that way, we-inc know if/when God2 makes a promise with His people, He binds that promise using an oath, to be an established.statute, that what He promises, is really true and doesn't change.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Because God wanted to make"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Because God wanted to make the unchanging nature of his purpose very clear to the heirs of what was promised, he confirmed it with an oath.</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Te abhu dua j'ara dhu bisa boe ub'a. Ka èci, nuka lii pajaji Ama Lamatua. Aa èci hari, nuka lii subha Lamatua, dhu Na pake j'aj'i mi tate'a nèti lii pajaji Na. De ladhe Ama Lamatua dhu moa le j'ara èci, tatu Na tao madhutu, lula Nèngu bisa boe omo koso. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi baku pangee rupa-rupa dènge lii pajaji Na. Èdhi dhu rai lati le, sèna ka tenge mamuri nèti Nèngu, de limuri ne, èdhi dhoka mate di, ho sanao dhoka mi Nèngu di.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) there are two things that cannot change. The first, is God's promise. And the other, is His oath which He used to guarantee (establish.statute) His promise. So (consequently), when God2 has promised something, He will certainly do according to it, because He cannot lie/decieve/empty talk/BS. That is why we-inc do not need to be worrying about His promise. We have run/rushed to Him to find life/salvation, so (consequently) now we need to keep waiting and keep hoping/trusting only in Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bii = takut"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">bii = takut</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="running away to God: provides a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">running away to God: provides a positive emphasis. LITERALLY: God did this so that, by two unchangeable things in which it is impossible for God to lie, we who have fled to take hold of the hope offered to us, may be greatly encouraged.<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Dènge j'ara ne'e, d'ara èdhi taleo nuka sèmi koha dhu rai eele nèti d'ara rii, ho la'e panahu ètu hèb'a-namo. Te era maena èdhi dhoka Kristus di, dhu j'aj'i le kètu kapai risi agama èdhi. Uru èèna, lèke dènge lod'o kalela dhèu Yahudi, kètu kapai risi agama rèngu maso asa Kama Luri Mola-Mèci re bèla gorden, sèna ka paraga dènge Ama Lamatua ètu èèna.<bt>In that way, our insides are wide/safe/calm, like a boat which has fled from the waves, to come to anchor (vb) at an anchorage/harbour (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) our place of hope is just Kristus who is/has become our *highest priest. Formerly, on the Yahudi holiday/feast day, the *high priest entered the Most Holy Room via/past the cloth curtain (as door curtain), to meet with God there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luri = keramat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">luri = keramat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: We have this hope as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: We have this hope as an anchor for the soul, firm and secure. It enters the inner sanctuary behind the curtain,</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 16:2</note><v n="20" />Te ngaa limuri ne, Yesus dhu la'e uuru le, ho bhoke j'ara hia èdhi. Te Nèngu kètu kapai risi agama kahèi, dhu ca ropa dènge Melkisedek, dhu uru èèna. Te ngaa Yesus kapai risi nèti kètu agama uru èèna, lula Na ae nèdhi boe pakako sasab'a-la'a Na.<bt>But now Yesus has gone ahead to open a way for us. Cuz (elaboration) He is also *high priest, who is of the same type/model as Melkisedek from long ago. But He is greater/more impressive than the old model head priest(s), because He never ceased/s to carry out His work/responsibilities (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: where Jesus, who went before"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: where Jesus, who went before us, has entered on our behalf. He has become a high priest forever, after the priestly order of Melchizedek.</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:4</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Melkisedek, kètu kapai risi agama, dedha risi nèti kètu agama Lewi dènge ana-èpu na<bt>Melkisedek is a high priest who is higher than the priest Lewi and his descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="7" />
      <v n="1-3" />Uru èèna, Melkisedek j'aj'i dhèu aae kota Salem. Nèngu kahèi kètu agama nèti dhèu-dhèu dhu pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele èèna. Ngara Melkisedek ne, sasoa na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu Aae D'ara Mola&gt;&gt;. Aa dhèu aae Salem, sasoa na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu Aae Dame&gt;&gt;. Èci sa re'a boe j'aj'aj'i Melkisedek ne nèti mia. Èci sa re'a boe kahèi ina dènge ama na, aa bèi-baki na. Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu re'a lod'o rara iisi na, aa lod'o mamadhe na. Dhèu re'a dhoka, nèngu dhèu aae kota Salem, aa kètu agama nèti Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa nèngu ne, nuka sèmi Ana Ama Lamatua, lula nèngu ama agama dhu pakako taruu sasab'a na kahèi.<bt>Long ago, Melkisedek was the king of the city of Salem. He was also *priest for people who worshipped the Highest God. Melkisedek's name means, “King with the Straight Insides”. And the King of Salem means “King of Peace”. Nobody knows Melkisedek's origins. Nobody knows his mother, his father, and his ancestors (doublet) either [NOTE: RL-driven order]. There is nobody who knows the day of his birth, and the day of his death. People only know that he was king of the city of Salem, and *priest to/for God. But he is also like God's Child, because he is also a priest who continually carries out his work. [DISCOURSE: reorganized for background-foreground issues.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: 1-3 Nèngu kahèi kètu agama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Diperhatikan: 1-3 Nèngu kahèi kètu agama nèti dhèu-dhèu dhu sogo-tagu Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi èèna. (kalau sebutan untuk Tuhan Allah sebagai kètu agama dhu dedha risi eele?)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ca tèka, pèri-pèri dhèu aae dènge sordad'u ra mai parame rèti mèdha-panyau angalai Abraham. Ka Abraham dènge angalai na lasi pamusu dènge dhèu aae se, toke Abraham segi si. Hèia mèdha-panyau nèti angalai na sèra, Abraham nèti aa'i hari. Ropa Abraham lèpa asa rai na, hèia Melkisedek kalua nèti kota Salem, ho la'e soru ne. Ka na hia Abraham berkat, peka na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele èèna, hia èu mèngi-nale.&gt;&gt; Èle ka Abraham hia Melkisedek ca pala nèti canguru pala, nèti mèdha aa'i-aa'i dhu na parame nare hari sèra. Abraham pabagi hia ne, lula Melkisedek ne kètu agama nèti Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele.<bt>One time, there were several kings who came with their soldiers to snatch away things from Abraham's friends. Then Abraham and his friends went warring against the kings, to the point that Abraham defeated them. Then the belongings of his friends, Abraham got them back again. When Abraham was returning (home) to his land/place, then Melkisedek came out from the city of Salem to greet him. And he gave a blessing1 to Abraham, saying, “May the Highest God, give blessing2 to you-sg.” After that Abraham gave to Melkisedek one part from ten parts, from all the things which he had retrieved. He divided out like that, because Melkisedek was priest of the Highest God.</bt><note reference="7:1-3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 14:17-20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />De pangee paie-iie Melkisedek ne! Abraham bagi hia ne ca pala nèti canguru pala, nèti mèdha aa'i-aa'i dhu be'a risi dhu na parame nare hari. De dhu lèke, nuka Melkisedek ne dhèu kapai.<bt>So (consequently) think carefully about this Melkisedek! Abraham divided out to him one part of ten parts, from all the best things which he had taken back. So (consequently) it is clear/right/true, that Melkisedek was an important person.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Just think how great he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Just think how great he was: Even the patriarch Abraham gave him a tenth of the [plunder / spoils]!</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Aa te ngaa lod'o sèra, Ama Lamatua ded'e mèka dhèu j'aj'i ama agama. Toke d'ai ku lod'o Lewi, ana-èpu èci nèti Abraham, heka Ama Lamatua ded'e ne dènge ana-èpu na, sèna ka j'aj'i ama agama hia mi ana-èpu Abraham aa'i-aa'i ra. Èle èèna ka, Ama Lamatua papuru atora Na dhu peka na, dhèu nèti suku Lewi dènge hak ho abhu ca pala nèti canguru pala nèti rui-j'aj'èra a'ari ra suku leo sèra ètu Isra'el.<bt>Whereas in fact, at that time God had not yet elevated/appointed people to be *priest. Until the time of Lewi, a grandchild of Abraham's, only-then did God appoint him and his descendants (doublet) to be *priests to all of Abraham's descendants (doublet). After that, God also sent down/ established a regulation that people from the tribe of Lewi have the rights to receive one part of ten parts of produce/yield (doublet) from their siblings of other tribes in Isra'el.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaj'ako = -4 (UNSs + Lena"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">kaj'ako = -4 (UNSs + Lena not know) ; lusi = -3, cece</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Now the law requires the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Now the law requires the descendants of Levi who become priests to collect a tenth from the people--that is their brothers--even though their brothers are descended from Abraham.</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 18:21</note><v n="6" />Te ngaa Melkisedek ne, ana-èpu boe nèti Lewi. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Abraham bagi hia ne ca pala nèti canguru pala, lula na pangee, na, Melkisedek ne dhèu kapai. Lod'o èèna Abraham dhu sèmi nare le lii pajaji nèti Ama Lamatua ho hia ne berkat. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Melkisedek peka kahèi, na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele èèna, hia èu mèngi-nale.&gt;&gt;<bt>But that Melkisedek, was not Lewi's descendant (doublet). Even that being the case, nevertheless Abraham gave him one part of ten parts, because he considered Melkisadek to be an important person. At that time, Abraham had already received the promise from God to bless him. Even that being the case, nevertheless Melkisedek also spoke, saying, “May the Highest God, give blessings to you-sg.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: [The one without genealogy from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: [The one without genealogy from them / This man, however, did not trace his descent from Levi, yet he] received a tenth from Abraham and blessed him who had the promises.</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ne'e ne ka j'aj'i mi tadha, na, Melkisedek ne, dhèu kapai. Lula dhèu dhu hia berkat tatu kapai risi nèti dhèu dhu sèmi nare berkat.<bt>This is also a sign/proof that Melkisedek was an important person. Because the person who gives blessing is surely more important/greater than the person who receives the blessing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And without doubt the lesser"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And without doubt the lesser person is blessed by the greater.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ama agama aa'i-aa'i ra dènge hak abhu ca pala nèti canguru pala. Te ngaa, lula rèngu dhèu rai-haha biasa, nèbhu-nèbhu ra madhe kahèi. Kètu agama Melkisedek abhu kahèi ca pala nèti canguru pala. Te ngaa na mamuri taruu, lula Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua peka boe na, nèngu madhe.<bt>All *priests have the right to receive one part of ten parts. But because they are only normal humans, eventually they also die. The priest Melkisedek also received one part of ten parts. But he lived continually, because God2's Holy Writings do not tell that he died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: In the one case, the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: In the one case, the tenth is collected by men who die; but in the other case, by him who is declared to be living.</Message></Annotation><v n="9-10" />Lula Abraham bagi hia Melkisedek ca pala nèti canguru pala nèti mèdha na sèra, dhèu bisa pangee, na, Abraham tago nare kahèi ana-èpu na dhu rara iisi mèka. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, èdhi bisa pangee, na, nèngu b'ae mema le unu ana-èpu na Lewi, ca pala nèti canguru pala.<bt>Because Abraham divided out to Melkisedek one part from ten parts (= *tithe) from his things, someone might think that, he also carried/covered costs of his unborn descendants (doublet). In that way, we-inc can consider that he already paid beforehand his great-grandson Lewi's *tithe.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èdhi bisa pama'ète sèmi ne'e: ropa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">èdhi bisa pama'ète sèmi ne'e: ropa Abraham hia ca pala nèti canguru pala mi Melkisedek, na bae mema le kaj'ako na Lewi ca pala nèti canguru pala.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: One might even say that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: One might even say that Levi, who collects the tenth, paid the tenth through Abraham. Because when Melchizedek met Abraham, Levi was still in the body of his ancestor.</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:9-10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu Yahudi pangee, na, hini ana-èpu abhu le ètu d'ara ngi'u bèi-baki ra.<bt>Yahudi people consider that the seed of a person's descendants are already existng in their ancestor's body(s).</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Èdhi parluu kètu agama rupa hiu, lula kètu agama rupa dhui bisa boe saku eele sasala dhèu<bt>We-inc need a new model/type of *priest, because the old model of priest is incapable of wiping away a person's wrongs</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Lod'o ana-èpu Lewi sèra j'aj'i ama agama, Lamatua pili nare Harun, a'a Musa, ho j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama dhu partama. Sasab'a nèti ama agama sèra, nuka soru-bara dhèu, sèna ka mamuri mola, pabe'a dènge Ama Lamatua. Masi ka rèngu mamuri madhutu atora agama aa'i-aa'i sèra, te ngaa kètu agama ca ropa dènge Harun, lake nare boe tao dhèu se mola-mèci. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu parluu kètu agama leo, dhu ca ropa dènge Melkisedek.<bt>When Lewi's descendants (doublet) became *priests, God2 chose Musa's older-sibling Harun to become the first *high priest. The priests' job/ responsibilities were to help (doublet) people so they would live clean/holy and be in right relationship with God. Even if they lived following all the religious regulations, nevertheless a priest of the model/type of Harun was not capable of making them truly clean/holy (doublet). That is why they needed a different *priest, whose model/type was like Melkisedek. [EXEG: Miller]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lake nare boe = sonde mampu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">lake nare boe = sonde mampu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: If indeed perfection could have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: If indeed perfection could have been attained through the Levitical priesthood (for [on the basis of it / under it] the law was given to the people), why was there still need for another priest to come--one like Melchizedek, not one named after Aaron?</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Te ngaa ladhe kètu agama rupa hiu gati eele kètu agama rupa dhui, tatu atora dhui hud'i gati eele kahèi.<bt>But if the new type of priest replaces the old type of priest, the old regulations must also undergo/experience change/ replacement.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For when there is a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For when there is a change of the priesthood, there must also be a change of the law.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />De te'a mèu le, kètu agama rupa hiu èèna, nuka Yesus. Te rara iisi Ne, nèti boe suku Lewi, te ngaa nèti suku leo. Madhutu atora Musa, kètu agama ca ropa dènge Harun, dhoka mai nèti suku Lewi di, bisa boe nèti suku leo.<bt>So (consequently) it is already clear, the priest of the new type is Yesus. Cuz (elaboration) He was born not the tribe of Lewi, but from a different tribe. According to Musa's regulations, a *priest of Harun's type could only come from the tribe of Lewi, and may not come from a different tribe.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: The one of whom these"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: The one of whom these things are said belonged to a different tribe, and no one from that tribe has ever served at the altar.</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Te ngaa dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu re'a, na, Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus, j'aj'i nèti suku Yahuda. Madhutu atora Musa, abhu mèka dhu j'aj'i kètu agama nèti suku ne'e.<bt>But everyone knows that our-inc Head/Leader, Yesus Kristus, was born from the tribe of Yahuda. According to Musa's regulations, there are no *priests from that tribe.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For it is clear that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For it is clear that our Lord descended from Judah, and in regard to that tribe, Moses said nothing about priests.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa Ama Lamatua pake heka atora dhui, lula abhu le Yesus dhu j'aj'i kètu agama rupa hiu, nuka sèmi Melkisedek.<bt>But God no longer uses those old regulations, because now there is already Yesus, who became a priest of the new model, like Melkisedek.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And it is even clearer:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And it is even clearer: another priest like Melchizedek has appeared,</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Te madhutu atora Musa, kètu agama rupa dhui hud'i mai ku nèti suku Lewi. Te ngaa Yesus mai boe nèti suku èèna. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Ama Lamatua ded'e Ne, sèna ka j'aj'i kètu agama rupa hiu, lula Nèngu dènge koasa ho mamuri toke d'ai mia-mia, aa abhu boe dhu bisa palaho Ne.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) according to Musa's regulations, *priests of the old type must come from the tribe of Lewi. But Yesus didn't come from that tribe. Even that being the case, nevertheless God elevated/ appointed Him to be a *priest of the new type, because He has the power/authority to live forever, and there is nobody who can destroy/ruin Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: One who has become a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: One who has become a priest, not on the basis of his ancestry, but on the basis of the power of an indestructible life.</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Te Sasuri Lamatua suri, peka na,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God2's Writings wrote, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Èu j'aj'i kètu agama ca ropa dènge Melkisedek, dhu uru èèna,<bt>“You are/will become a *priest of the same type/model/kind as the Melkisedek of long ago,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa Èu j'aj'i kètu agama toke d'ai mia-mia.&gt;&gt;<bt>but (contrary to expectation) You will be a priest forever.” [NOTE to daughter translations: match with phrasing in Heb. 5:6]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For it is declared: &quot;You"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For it is declared: "You are a priest forever, just like Melchizedek."</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Sasoa na, atora dhui dènge boe koasa, sèna ka soru-bara dhèu rai-haha. Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua pake heka atora dhui, dhu uru èèna Na pangèd'u mi Musa.<bt>That means, the old regulation do not have the power/authority to help (doublet) humans. That is why God no longer uses those old regulations, which He had formerly handed over to Musa.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="atheteesis: legal technical term for when"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">atheteesis: legal technical term for when a formal arrangement is declared invalid or annulled. The verb it is based on also includes the idea of setting something aside or refusing to recognize it. LITERALLY: The former regulation is set aside because it was weak and useless<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Te masi ka dhèu mamuri madhutu atora dhui sèra, te ngaa sasala ra era. Nèti èèna ka, limuri ne, Ama Lamatua bhoke le j'ara dhu be'a risi, ho èdhi bisa mamuri padame dènge Ne.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) even if/though a person lives according to those old regulations, nevertheless they still have their wrongs. That is why now, God has already opened a better way so that we-inc can live at peace/reconciled (relationally) with Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: (for the law made nothing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: (for the law made nothing perfect), and a better hope is introduced, by which we draw near to God.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yesus ne Kètu Agama dhu kapai risi nèti kètu agama rupa dhui sèra aa'i-aa'i<bt>Yesus is a Priest greater than *priests of the old type</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20-21" />Uru èèna, lod'o Ama Lamatua ded'e ana-èpu Lewi ho j'aj'i ama agama, Lamatua pajaji boe, aa subha boe ngaa-ngaa dènge rèngu. Te ngaa lod'o Ama Lamatua ded'e Yesus j'aj'i kètu agama, Na pajaji, peka na,<bt>Formerly, when God elevated/appointed Lewi's descendants (doublet) to be *priests, God2 did not promise, and did not swear any sort of oath with them. But when God appointed Yesus to be *priest, He promised, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: In addition, there is also"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: In addition, there is also God's vow. There was no such vow when the others were made priests.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, Lamatua!<bt>&lt;&lt;I am Lord/Master!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a subha, Ja'a ub'a boe ngaa-ngaa dhu Ja'a pajaji le.<bt>I swear an oath, (that) I will not change anything I have promised.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a ded'e Èu j'aj'i kètu agama,<bt>I appoint You-sg to be *priest,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka Èu pakako taruu sasab'a-la'a Mu.&gt;&gt;<bt>so You can carry out Your job/responsibilities (doublet) continually.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But he [Jesus] became a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But he [Jesus] became a priest with a vow, when God said to him, "The Lord has sworn, and will not change his mind, 'You are a priest forever.'"</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Dènge lii pajaji sèmi èèna, Ama Lamatua pake Yesus j'aj'i mi tate'a hia èdhi, dhu peka na, Nèngu neo pa'èki lii pajaji dhu be'a risi dènge èdhi.<bt>By promising like that, God uses/used Yesus to be a guarantee to us-inc that He is wanting to bind a promise which is even better for us.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: [Because of this vow /"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: [Because of this vow / To such an extent], Jesus has become the guarantee of a better covenant.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Uru èèna, kètu agama rupa dhui gati taruu, lula ra madhe. Nèti èèna ka, hud'i abhu ku kètu agama ae-ae.<bt>Formerly, *priests of the old type were replaced continually, because they die. That is why there needed to be many priests.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Now there were many of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Now there were many of those priests, since death prevented them from continuing in office.</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Te ngaa Yesus, kètu agama rupa hiu dhu mamuri taa-taa, aa Na loe boe pakako sasab'a-la'a Na. Nèti èèna ka, parluu boe dhèu gati Ne.<bt>But Yesus is a *priest of the new type who lives continually, and He also never ceases to carry out his job/responsibilities (doublet). That is why there is no need for someone to replace Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But because Jesus lives forever,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But because Jesus lives forever, he has a permanent priesthood.</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Nèti èèna ka, Yesus bisa hia mamuri mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu neo mai re Nèngu asa madha Ama Lamatua. Nèngu bisa tao sèmi èèna, toke d'ai mia-mia la'e. Aa Nèngu j'aj'i dhèu d'ara, dhu loe boe manèngi Ama Lamatua ho soru-bara rèngu.<bt>Because of that, Yesus is able to save everyone who wants to come to God through/via Him. He is able to do that forever. And He is their insider (loan) who never ceases to ask God to help (doublet) them. [EXEG: Ellingsworth] [CHECK /orang dalam/, /ai g'ana/]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu dara = orang dalam (example"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">dhèu dara = orang dalam (example going to a test, èu abhu dhèu dara, do?)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Aa Nèngu loe eele boe ciki"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Aa Nèngu loe eele boe ciki sa sabaj'a hia dhèu.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore he is able to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore he is able to save completely those who come to God through him, because he always lives to intercede for them.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Yesus kètu kapai risi agama dhu lalau-lalo'o èdhi. Te Nèngu ne, Dhèu mola-mèci dhu dènge boe sasala ngaa-ngaa. Nèngu ne, sama boe dènge dhèu rai-haha biasa, dhu re'a dhoka ad'u-ue sasala di. Te Ama Lamatua dhu nedhe Ne padedha-dedha, risi nèti aa'i-aa'i dhu ètu sorga dènge rai-haha.<bt>That Yesus is a *high priest who serves (doublet) us-inc. Cuz (elaboration) He is a clean/holy/pure (doublet) Person who has no wrongs/sins whatsoever. He is not the same as normal humans, who only know/able how to do wrong. Cuz (elaboration) God has lifted Him up very high (=exalted Him), above everything in heaven and on earth (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Such a high priest meets"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Such a high priest meets our need--one who is holy, blameless, pure [undefiled], set apart [separate] from sinners, exalted above the heavens.</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Nèti èèna ka, Yesus be'a risi nèti kètu agama rupa dhui aa'i-aa'i ra. Uru sèra, rèngu bèli-bèli hud'i roro badha tao korban, sèna ka Ama Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo rèngu unu ra. Èle ku, heka ra tao korban hia dhèu biasa kèna. Te ngaa Yesus parluu boe tao korban pahari-pahari sèmi èèna, lula Na saraka ngi'u Na ca tèka èèna ka di, sèna ka j'aj'i korban. Ne'e ne d'ai aa'i kèna, ho Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>That is why Yesus is better than all *priests of the old type. Formerly, they had to sacrifice animals every day, so God would wipe away their own wrongs (doublet). After that, only-then could they do sacrifices for the common people. But Yesus does not need to make sacrifices repeatedly, because He has already surrendered/ turned over Himself just one time to be a sacrifice. That is enough for God2 to wipe away everybody's sins (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Unlike the other high priests,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Unlike the other high priests, he does not need to offer sacrifices day after day, first for his own sins, and then for the sins of the people. He made a sacrifice once for all when he offered himself.</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 9:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Madhutu atora Musa, rèngu ded'e dhèu rai-haha biasa ho j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama. Te ngaa sasala ra era. Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua tao lii pajaji hiu, peka na, Nèngu ded'e Ana Na j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama. Te Ana Na, madhutu taruu dad'èi Na.<bt>According to Musa's regulations, they appointed normal humans to be *high priests. But they still have/do wrongs. That is why God made a new promise that He was going to appoint His Child to be *high priest. Cuz (elaboration) His Child, always followed/ obeyed His will.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For the law appoints men"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For the law appoints men who are weak as high priests; but the vow, which came after the law, appointed the Son, who has been made perfect forever.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua pake Kristus sèna ka pa'èki lii pajaji hiu dhu be'a risi nèti lii pajaji dhui<bt>God used Kristus to bind a new promise which is better than the old promise</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="8" />
      <v n="1" />De lii padhai ja'a dhu kab'ua, sèmi ne'e ka: limuri ne, èdhi dènge le kètu kapai risi agama dhu be'a risi nèti uru sèra. Nèngu ne'e, nuka Yesus. Nèngu dhu madhèdi nèd'u paredha ètu sorga, ètu baboa g'ana Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele.<bt>So (consequently), the important/valuable thing I have to say is this: now we-inc already have a *high priest who is better than those from long ago. He is Yesus. He is sitting holding rule/governing in heaven, at the right side of the Highest God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: The point of what we"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: The point of what we are saying is this: We do have such a high priest, who sat down at the right hand of the throne of the Majesty in heaven,</Message></Annotation><note reference="8:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:1</note><v n="2" />Aa Na pakako sasab'a Na ètu era sabaj'a dhu asli ètu sorga. Era ne'e ne, pa'ue-ai Ama Lamatua mesa Na, nèti boe dhèu rai-haha.<bt>And He is carrying out His job/responsibilities in the original place of prayer/worship in heaven. That place, God himself is the one who made (doublet) it, not humans who made it. [EXEG: Ex. Summ. “the real thing, the original, not a copy”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="skeenee: for the heavenly &quot;tent&quot;, which"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">skeenee: for the heavenly "tent", which is hardly what you would use for a weekend family campout at the beach, the generic "place" seems more appropriate, since portability is not a factor. For the earthly one, portability was necessary. LITERALLY: and who serves in the sanctuary, the true tabernacle set up by the Lord, not by man.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Kètu kapai risi agama tema nèti mèdha persembahan dènge korban hia Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, Yesus hud'i nèti korban kahèi.<bt>The *high priest normally brings offerings and sacrifices to give to God. That is why Yesus must also bring sacrifice.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gifs &gt; presents? LITERALLY: Every high"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">gifs &gt; presents? LITERALLY: Every high priest is appointed to offer both gifts and sacrifices, and so it was necessary for this one also to have something to offer.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Te ngaa Yesus pakako boe sasab'a Na ètu rai-haha. Lula ètu rai-haha ne, abhu le ama agama dhu hia mèdha persembahan dènge korban asa Ama Lamatua madhutu atora Musa.<bt>But Yesus does not carry out His job/responsibilities on earth. Because on earth there are already *priests who give offerings and sacrifices to God, according to Musa's regulations.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: If he were on earth,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: If he were on earth, he would not be a priest, for there are already men who offer the gifts prescribed by the law.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ra pakako sasab'a ra ètu d'ara Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i, dhu ca ropa dènge era sabaj'a dhu asli ètu sorga. Te lod'o Musa neo tao Paleo ne, Ama Lamatua pasanèd'e ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e paie-iie! Èu hud'i tao ku palèke mola-mola dènge rupa dhu Ja'a pad'elo dènge èu ètu kolo ledhe nèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>They carry out their job/responsibilities in the Tent of Prayer, whose model/type was according to the asli/original place of prayer/worship in heaven. Cuz (elaboration) when Musa wanted to make that Tent, God reminded/ warned him, saying, “Remember well! You-sg must correctly make it according to the model which I have shown you on that mountain!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="skeenee: &quot;place&quot; generic as before LITERALLY:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">skeenee: "place" generic as before LITERALLY: They serve at a sanctuary that is a copy and shadow of what is in heaven. That is why Moses was warned when he was about to build the tabernacle, "See to it that you make everything according to the pattern shown you on the mountain."<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="8:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 25:40</note><v n="6" />Te ngaa sasab'a Yesus ne, kapai risi nèti ama agama rupa dhui aa'i-aa'i ra. Te limuri ne, Ama Lamatua pa'èki le lii pajaji dhu be'a risi, lula Na pake Yesus j'aj'i kalete kahèi, sèna ka dhèu rai-haha bisa padame dènge Ama Lamatua.<bt>But Yesus' job/ responsibilities are far more impressive/greater than those of the old model of *priest. Cuz now, God has already bound a better promise, because He also used Yesus to be a bridge/go-between so humans could be able to be at peace/reconciled (relationally) with God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But the priestly ministry Jesus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But the priestly ministry Jesus has [received / obtained] is as superior to theirs as the covenant of which he is mediator is superior to the old one, and is founded on better promises.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Uru èèna, Na pa'èki lii pajaji dènge Musa, ropa Na papuru atora sèra. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa dhèu rai-haha bisa boe mamuri mola-mèci madhutu atora ne. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu bisa boe pabe'a dènge Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, limuri ne, parluu abhu lii pajaji dhu be'a risi hari.<bt>Long ago, He bound a promise with Musa when He handed down/established those regulations. Even that being the case, nevertheless humans are not able to live clean/holy/pure (doublet) according to those regulations. Because of that, they are not able to be in reciprocally right relationship with God. That is why now there is a need for an even better promise.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="an: note &quot;neva get&quot; instead of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">an: note "neva get" instead of "neva have" - if no problem had ever developed, rather than if there had been no problem LITERALLY: For it there had been nothing wrong with the first covenant, there would have been no need for another.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Te lod'o uru sèra, Ama Lamatua dhu kai le dhèu unu Na, lula rèngu sisu pahari-pahari atora Na. Ropa Na taha nare heka d'ara, hèia Na nasa, ka peka, aku Nèngu na,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) formerly, God scolded His people, because they had repeatedly transgressed His regulations. When He could no longer stand it/restrain His insides, He was angry, and so He said,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Nanene paie-iie, te Ja'a ne Lamatua!<bt>“Listen carefully, cuz (elaboration) I am Lord/Master!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Tatu Ja'a neo pa'èki hari lii pajaji hiu<bt>Surely I will bind a new promise</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge dhèu Isra'el sèra,<bt>with the people of Isra'el,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa dènge suku Yahuda.<bt>and the tribe of Yahuda.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But God found fault with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But God found fault with the people, and said, "The time is coming," says the Lord, "when I will make a new covenant with the house of Israel, and with the house of Judah.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9" />Lii pajaji dhu Ja'a neo pa'èki dènge rèngu èèna,<bt>That promise that I will bind with them,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sama boe dènge lii pajaji uru èèna<bt>is not the same as that promise which I previously bound</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu hia mi bèi-baki ra.<bt>with their ancestors (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te uru èèna, Ja'a kadhèi kacui-aai ra,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) previously I held their hand,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho lere si kalua nèti rai Masir.<bt>to lead them out from the land of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakalua = take them out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pakalua = take them out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa rèngu tao boe<bt>But they did not do</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">madhutu ngaa dhu ra pajaji dènge Ja'a.<bt>according to what they had promised Me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a pusi-pahae heka si.<bt>That is why I already do not want to pay attention/care about (doublet) them anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: It will not be like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: It will not be like the covenant I made with their forefathers, when I took them by the hand to lead them out of Egypt, because they did not remain faithful to my covenant, and I turned away from them,' says the Lord."</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="10" />Lii pajaji dhu èèna na Ja'a pa'èki dènge suku Isra'el,<bt>That promise that I will bind with the tribe(s) of Isra'el,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">isi na sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>its content is like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe Ja'a tao atora Ja'a ètu d'ara ngangee ra.<bt>“I will place My regulations in their inner thoughts.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pe Ja'a suri paredha Ja'a, ètu d'ara rèngu.<bt>I will write My commands in their insides.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Hèia Ja'a j'aj'i Lamatua ra,<bt>Then, I will be their God2,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa rèngu j'aj'i dhèu unu Ja'a.<bt>and they will be My people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: This is the covenant I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: This is the covenant I will make with the house of Israel after that time, says the Lord. I will put my laws in their minds and write them on their hearts. I will be their God, and they will be my people.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Bèli-camèd'a rèngu parluu heka aj'a-nori angalai ra,<bt>Later they will not need to teach (doublet) their friends anymore,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge a'ari ra, peka na,<bt>and their siblings will say,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">&lt;Miu hud'i tadhe ku Lamatua!&gt;<bt>‘You must know (personal acquaintence, not head knowledge) God2!’</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra tadhe mèu Ja'a,<bt>cuz (elaboration) all of them know Me well,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">mulai nèti ana iiki-iiki toke d'ai kapai aae.<bt>beginning from the smallest/most insignificant to the largest/most important.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: No longer will a man"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: No longer will a man teach his neighbor, or a man his brother, saying, 'Know the Lord,' because they will all know me, from the least of them to the greatest.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />Lula Ja'a neo pad'elo rasa kasia Ja'a mi rèngu,<bt>Because I want to/am going to show My mercy to them,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Masi ka miu ad'u-ue j'ara dhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Masi ka miu ad'u-ue j'ara dhu lèke boe, te ngaa èèna na, Ja'a kasia miu.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nèti èèna ka Ja'a pabhèlu eele sasala-sasigo ra aa'i-aa'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>that is why I will (completely) forget all their wrongs.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: I will have mercy on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: I will have mercy on their transgressions, and will remember their sins no more."</Message></Annotation><note reference="8:8-12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 31:31-34</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Lod'o Lamatua padhai lii nare, Na neo pa'èki lii pajaji hiu dènge ra, sasoa na, lii pajaji dhui pake heka. Nèbhu heka, na ele.<bt>When God spoke saying, He was going to bind a new promise with them, that meant the old promise now no longer was in effect anymore. Soon, it would disappear.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&quot;no good&quot; rather than &quot;poho&quot;, which"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">"no good" rather than "poho", which carries the idea of deteriorating and does not work well with "deal" LITERALLY: By calling this covenant "new," he has made the first one obsolete; an what is obsolete and aging will soon disappear.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yesus j'aj'i korban dhu be'a risi nèti korban dhu dhui sèra<bt>Yesus is a sacrifice who/which is better than the old sacrifices</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="9" />
      <v n="1" />Ja'a neo pasanèd'e miu sèmi ne'e: lod'o Ama Lamatua pa'èki hiu-hiu lii pajaji dènge bèi-baki èdhi, Nèngu papuru atora kahèi, sèna ka ra tao era manèngi-mangaj'i, ho ra bisa pahaha iisi mi Nèngu madhutu dad'èi atora sèra.<bt>Now I want to remind you like this: when God first bound that promise with our-inc ancestors, He also handed down regulations so1 they could build a place of prayer/worship, so2 they could worship2 Him according to the ways/requirements of those regulations.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="men oun: continuation LITERALLY: Then indeed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">men oun: continuation LITERALLY: Then indeed the first covenant had regulations for worship and also an earthly sanctuary.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ètu era manèngi-mangaj'i ne, abhu madha èmu dènge paleo aae cue. Ètu d'ara kama re madha nèti paleo ne, abhu era tatèka labhu dènge mei èci dhu ama agama tèke roti dhu rèngu neo hia Ama Lamatua. Kama re madha ne, ra peka na, <span class="Italic">Kama Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua.</span><bt>In that place of prayer (doublet), there is a yard (Port. loan: kintal) and a big tent. In that tent's front room, there is a place to place lamp(s), and a table which the *priests use to place bread which they give to God. It is that front room, which they call, <span class="Italic">God's Clean/Holy (doublet) Room.</span></bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Needs picture? LITERALLY: A tabernacle was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">Needs picture? LITERALLY: A tabernacle was set up. In its first room were the lampstand, the table, and the consecrated bread. This was called the Holy Place.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="9:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 26:1-30, 25:23-40</note></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\lb00259c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10cm;textWrapping:none" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Abhu kahèi bèla bhabhiri kapai ca bèla dhu pa'abhe kama leo èci, dhu ra peka na, <span class="Italic">Kama Luri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua.</span><bt>There is also a large cloth curtain hung to block off another room which they refer to as <span class="Italic">God's Most Holy Room. [CHECK if people think this is same or different than Kama Luri.]</span></bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhabhiri = pele"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">bhabhiri = pele</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Behind the second curtain was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Behind the second curtain was a room called the Most Holy Place,</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 26:31-33</note><v n="4" />Re madha bèla bhabhiri ne, abhu mei hualaa cue, era tunu raa aj'u hèu mèngi hia Ama Lamatua. Aa ètu d'ara Kama Luri Mola-Mèci èèna, abhu boaraka hualaa èci, dhu ra peka na, <span class="Italic">Boaraka Pajaji.</span> Ètu d'ara boaraka ne, rèngu tao mèdha uuru sèra, sèna ka pasanèd'e dhèu lula-nèti j'ara lii pajaji Ama Lamatua dhu Na pa'èki dènge rèngu. Ètu era ne'e, abhu kahèi toples hualaa cue dhu isi roti <span class="Italic">manna.</span> Roti ne'e ka dhu uru èèna Ama Lamatua papuru mai nèti dedha-liru hia mi bèi-baki èdhi, lod'o rèngu manganga ètu d'ara pad'a sod'a. Ètu d'ara boaraka ne, abhu kahèi tatea unu Harun, dhu uru èèna sub'u dadana hiu. Abhu kahèi hadhu kabela, dhu uru èèna Ama Lamatua pake ho dule atora Na dhu pangèd'u mi Musa.<bt>In front of that curtain, there is a gold table, a place to burn aromatic tree sap to God. And inside that Most Holy Room is a gold trunk/box, which they refer to as <span class="Italic">Promise Trunk.</span> Inside that trunk, they place old/archaic/antique things to remind people about God's promise which He had bound with them. In that place there is a gold stoples/jar, which is filled with <span class="Italic">manna</span> bread. That is the bread which long ago God had sent down from the sky (doublet), to our ancestors (doublet) when they were hungry in the empty land. In that trunk there is also Harun's staff which had once grown off-shoots. There are also the flat stones which God used to carve His regulations which He handed down to Musa. [CHECK /dule/] [EXEG: basis of location in relation to curtain, see discussion in Bruce, Ellingsworth, Miller. Unknown cultural objects. Have to make lots of implicit info explicit. IS A FTN needed? What would it say?]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèdha katagu = sogu-tagu ; mèdha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">mèdha katagu = sogu-tagu ; mèdha uuru sèra = ancient stuff, like in a museum ; dule = carve</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: which had the golden altar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: which had the golden altar of incense and the gold-covered chest [ark] of the covenant. This chest contained the golden jar of manna, Aaron's rod that had budded, and the stone tablets of the covenant.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhu uru èèna sub'u nèdhi sèmi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">dhu uru èèna sub'u nèdhi sèmi dadana hiu sa.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 30:1-6, 25:10-16, 16:33, Sensus 17:8-10, Kalua nèti Masir 25:16, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 10:3-5</note><v n="5" />Ètu katanga boaraka ne, abhu dhu dule rupa dua ana dhèu dhu saraga titu kèna. Ana dhèu se, rupa ra nuka sèmi ana pajuu nèti sorga dhu dènge èla, dhu titu baa èla, ho bhiri boaraka ne, lula era ne j'aj'i mi tadha, ho pad'elo rasa kasia Ama Lamatua mi dhèu rai-haha. Te ngaa limuri ne, ja'a pamadhera heka lii lole nèti mèdha-panyau se.<bt>On the cover of that trunk there are carved two beautiful statues. Those statues have the shape/ form like God's winged underlings from heaven who are standing with their wings opened wide covering/ protecting the trunk, because that place shows God's mercy/pity to humans. But now, I don't have time to tell in detail about those things (doublet). [CHECK ana dhèu = patung] [NOTE to daughter translations: these are /cherubim/ &gt; ana bua basayap, not /anggelos/ ana bua, so NOT same as ana bua biasa.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katanga1 = tutupan, cover ; katanga2"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">katanga1 = tutupan, cover ; katanga2 = piring rotan, tempat makanan ; katanga madha = in front of, di hadapan ; ana dhèu = patung ; èla = sayap</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The &quot;angels&quot; were statues. LITERALLY: Above"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">The "angels" were statues. LITERALLY: Above the chest were the cherubim of the Glory, overshadowing the place of atonement [mercy seat]. But we cannot discuss these things in detail now.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="9:5" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani peka na, ana pajuu nèti sorga dhu dènge èla, ètu ne'e, ngara na &lt;<span class="Italic">kerubim</span>&gt;. Ana pajuu nèti sorga biasa, ra pangare na, &lt;<span class="Italic">anggelos</span>&gt;. Rèngu se, dènge boe èla. Ladhe ètu <span class="Italic">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka</span> 3:24, dènge <span class="Italic">Kalua nèti Masir</span> 25:18-22.<bt>The Yunani language writings say, God2's winged underlings from heaven here are <span class="Italic">‘kerubim</span>’. God's common/normal underlings from heaven, they refer to as <span class="Italic">‘anggelos</span>’. They are not winged. Also see Genesis 3:24. and Exodus 25:18-22.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Rèngu pangèci mèdha-panyau ètu d'ara Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua mema sèmi èèna ka. Bèli-bèli, ama agama sèra maso-kalua kama re madha ne, sèna ka ra pakako sasab'a ra ètu èèna.<bt>Their arranging/organising things inside God's Tent of Prayer was really like that. Every day the *priests would enter-exit into the front room to carry out their job/responsibilities there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pangèci = manyimpan, mengatur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pangèci = manyimpan, mengatur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: When everything had been arranged"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: When everything had been arranged like this, the priests entered regularly into the outer room to carry on their ministry.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 18:2-6</note><v n="7" />Te ngaa dhodhoka kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi di, dhu bisa maso la'e asa d'ara Kama Luri Mola-Mèci èèna. Aa nèngu maso leli boe, te ngaa maso sa d'ara dhoka ca tèu ca tèka. Aa ladhe na maso, nèngu hud'i nèti dènge raa badha korban, ho pici asa katanga Boaraka Pajaji ne. Sasoa nèti raa ne, sèna ka Ama Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo nèti kètu agama dènge dhèu-dhèu unu na aa'i-aa'i, masi ka sasala dhu rèngu ad'u-ue dènge boe d'ara mase'a.<bt>But only the Yahudi *high priest was allowed to enter into that Most Holy Room. And he was not allowed to enter just any old time, but (he) only entered once a year. And if/when he entered, he must take the blood of a sacrificed animal, to sprinkle/ pour on the cover of that Promise Trunk. The purpose/meaning of that blood, was so that God would wipe away the wrongs (doublet) of that *priest and all his people, even the wrongs that they had done (doublet) without being aware.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pici = percik"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pici = percik</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But only the high priest"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But only the high priest entered the inner room, and that only once a year, an never without blood, which he offered for himself and for the sins the people had committed in ignorance.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 16:2-34</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ama Lamatua pake le Roh Mola-Mèci Na, sèna ka hia èdhi te'a, na, ladhe bèla bhabhiri abhu era ètu j'ara maso asa d'ara Kama Luri Mola-Mèci èèna, sasoa na, dhèu rai-haha bisa mèka maso asa madha Ama Lamatua, ladhe pake atora dhui era.<bt>God has already used His Holy Spirit to give understanding to us, that, if that curtain was still blocking the entrance into the Most Holy Room, that would mean that, humans could still not be able to enter before God, as long as the old regulations were still in force/valid. [EXEG: NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ama Lamatua pake le Roh Mola-Mèci"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Ama Lamatua pake le Roh Mola-Mèci Na, sèna ka hia èdhi te'a na, ladhe bèla bhabhiri abhu era ètu j'ara maso asa dara Kama Mola-Mèci Risi Eele èèna, sasoa na, dhèu bisa mèka lasi asa madha Ama Lamatua.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: The Holy Spirit was showing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: The Holy Spirit was showing by this that the way into the Most Holy Place had not yet been opened as long as the first tent was still standing.</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Se'e se j'aj'i mi conto dhu Roh Lamatua pake, sèna ka aj'a-nori èdhi dhu mamuri limuri ne. Uru èèna, bèi-baki èdhi rèti mèdha persembahan dènge badha korban rèngu asa ama agama, sèna ka Ama Lamatua saku eele sasala ra. Masi ka rèti korban ae-ae sèmi èèna, te ngaa korban sèra bisa boe pamèu d'ara ra, aa bisa boe pa'ele rasa sala ètu d'ara rèngu.<bt>All that is an example which God2's Spirit uses to teach (doublet) us-inc who are living now. Formerly, our ancestors (doublet) brought their offerings and animal sacrifices to the *priest, so God would wipe away their wrongs. Even if they bring many sacrifices like that, nevertheless those sacrifices cannot cleanse/purify their insides, and cannot cause to disappear the sense/feeling of wrong in their insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamèu = bersihkan ; pa'ele ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pamèu = bersihkan ; pa'ele = hilangkan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: This is an illustration for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: This is an illustration for the present time, indicating that the gifts and sacrifices being offered were not able to clear the conscience of the worshiper.</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />De, ngaa dhu rèngu tao sèra, dhoka madhutu atora agama di. Abhu atora dhu paredha, peka na, rèngu bisa boe ra'a ne'e, aa bisa boe rinu èèna. Abhu atora dhu leo peka na, rèngu hud'i pamèu ku ngi'u ra dènge mèdha dhu ra pake madhutu dad'èi atora. Aa te ngaa, madhutu iia-iia na, atora aa'i-aa'i sèra, ator dhoka ngi'u re li'u di, te ngaa ator boe d'ara dhèu. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa atora sèra hud'i pakako taruu, toke Ama Lamatua gati dènge atora dhu hiu.<bt>So (consequently), what they have done, is only to follow religious regulations. There are regulation(s) which command that they cannot eat this, and cannot drink that. There are other regulation(s) which say they must wash themselves/their bodies and their tools/instruments that they use according to the ways/requirements of the regulations. Whereas in fact, all those regulations merely manage/regulate the outside part of a person, but they cannot manage/ regulate a person's insides. Even that being the case, nevertheless those regulations must/had to keep on going, until God replaced them with new regulations.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: They are only a matter"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: They are only a matter of food and drink and various ceremonial washings -- external regulations applying until the time of the new order.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Te ngaa limuri ne abhu le Dhèu dhu uru èèna Ama Lamatua padhadha tèke, nuka Kristus. Na mai le sèna ka j'aj'i kètu agama kapai risi èdhi, aa Na tao le j'ara dhu be'a hia èdhi.<bt>But now, there already is that Person whom God had promised2 beforehand from long ago. He is Kristus. He has come to be our-inc *high priest, and He has already done good things for us.</bt><note reference="9:11" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani dhu be'a risi, suri na, &lt;&lt;Na tao <span class="Italic">le</span> j'ara dhu be'a hia èdhi.&gt;&gt; Te ngaa abhu sasuri cahag'e hari dhu suri na, &lt;&lt;Na <span class="Italic">neo</span> tao j'ara dhu be'a hia èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>The best Yunani language writings write, saying, “He <span class="Italic">has</span> done good things for us.” But there are some other writings which say, “He <span class="Italic">is going to</span> do good things for us.”</bt></note>Na pakako sasab'a-la'a Na, sama sèmi kètu agama rupa dhui, te ngaa Na sab'a ètu era sabaj'a dhu be'a risi eele. Era manèngi-mangaj'i Na, ètu boe rai-haha ne, te j'aj'i boe nèti pa'ue-ai dhèu rai-haha.<bt>He carries out His job/responsibilities (doublet), like the *priests of the old model, but He works in a place of prayer/worship which is far better. That place of prayer (doublet) of His, is not on earth, cuz (elaboration) it wasn't humans that made (doublet) it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ktisis just &quot;this world&quot; LITERALLY: When"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">ktisis just "this world" LITERALLY: When Christ came as high priest of the good things that are already here, he went through the greater and more perfect tabernacle that is not man-made, that is to say, not a part of this creation.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Kristus maso asa d'ara Kama Luri Mola-Mèci èèna kahèi, ho paraga dènge Ama Lamatua, sama sèmi dhu kètu kapai risi agama dhu rupa dhui se tao ca tèu ca tèka. Aa lod'o Na maso la'e, Na nèti raa hia Ama Lamatua kahèi. Te ngaa raa ne leko-leo. Te Kristus nèti boe raa badha korban. Dhu nèti, nuka raa Nèngu unu Na, lula Nèngu madhe le j'aj'i korban hia èdhi. Te ngaa Kristus maso, nèti raa Na dhoka ca tèka di, sèna ka patabuli eele èdhi nèti koasa sasala-sasigo èdhi toke d'ai mia-mia la'e.<bt>Kristus also enters into the Most Holy Room, to meet God like the *high priests of the old model did once a year. And when He enters, He also brings blood to give to God. But this blood is different. Cuz (elaboration) Kristus doesn't bring blood from an animal sacrifice. What He brings, is His own blood, because He died (perfective) to be/become a sacrifice for us-inc. But Kristus enters bringing His blood just one time to free/release/rescue/save us-inc from sin forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: He did not enter by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: He did not enter by means of the blood of goats and calves; but he entered the Most Holy Place once for all by his own blood, having obtained eternal redemption.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />De raa Kristus èèna, mema kab'ua risi nèti raa badha. Te madhutu atora Musa, dhèu dhu tao sala sèra, kaj'alu, ka nia boe maso ho manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua. Rèngu hud'i lasi ku asa kètu agama ho tao korban, sèna ka raa korban se pamèu hari rèngu. Nèti korban sèra, ae ka dhu pake raa kahib'i dènge raa sapi. Abhu kahèi atora èci, dhu peka na, ladhe dhèu goi lèke dhèu madhe, nèngu kaj'alu ètu madha Lamatua. Ladhe na neo hari j'aj'i mola-mèci, kètu agama hud'i nare ku ahu sisa nèti sapi èni dhu ra tunu. Èle, na nèti ahu èèna, ho la'e ceb'e asa dhèu dhu kaj'alu èèna, ho sèna ka na mola-mèci hari.<bt>So (consequently), Kristus' blood, really is more valuable than the blood of animals. Cuz (elaboration) according to Musa's regulations, people who do wrong are filthy/defiled, and not worthy/appropriate to enter (implied: into a house of worship) to worship (doublet) God. They must go to a priest to make a sacrifice, so that the blood of that sacrifice can cleanse/purify them again. Many sacrifices used the blood of goats and the blood of cows. There was also a regulation that said if a person touched a dead person, he was already dirty/filthy/ defiled before God2. If s/he wanted to become clean/pure/holy (doublet) again, the *priest must take the ashes leftover from burning up a juvenile cow. Then he brought those ashes, to go sprinkle/pour on that defiled person, so that he could become clean/pure (doublet) again. [EXEG: Bruce, Miller, Ellingsworth; higher structure modelled on CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&quot;clean outside&quot; would sound like some"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">"clean outside" would sound like some kind of disease, not ritually or morally clean. LITERALLY: The blood of goats and calves, and the ashes of a heifer sprinkled on those who are ceremonially unclean, sanctify them, so they are outwardly clean.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cab'e = hambur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">cab'e = hambur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Hèia ama agama hud'i nare ku"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Hèia ama agama hud'i nare ku raa kahibi, do raa sapi, dènge nèti sapi èni dhu tunu pakèpu. Èle, na nèti raa dènge ahu ne, la'e ceb'e asa dhèu dhu kaj'alu deo na, ho sèna ka na mola-mèci hari.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 16:15-16, Sensus 19:9,17-19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />De ladhe raa badha bisa tao dhèu j'aj'i mola-mèci, risi-risi hari dènge raa Kristus! Te raa Kristus èèna ka dhu patalale èdhi nèti koasa sasala-sasigo, aa pamèu d'ara èdhi kahèi. Te sasala èdhi ka dhu cèri eele èdhi nèti Ama Lamatua. Lod'o Yesus Kristus madhe sèmi èèna, Roh Ama Lamatua dhu mamuri taa-taa, soru-bara Ne, sèna ka Na soro iisi Na asa Lamatua, nuka sèmi badha korban dhu dènge boe tadha karehe ciki sa hèi ètu ngi'u na. De limuri ne èdhi bisa le pahaha iisi dènge d'ara kateme mi Ama Lamatua dhu mamuri dènge boe too-lane.<bt>So (consequently) if the blood of an animal is able to make clean/pure (doublet) the outside part of a defiled person, how much even more the blood of Kristus (statement, not rhetorical question)! Cuz (elaboration) Kristus' blood has freed/released/saved us from wrongs (doublet), and also cleansed/purified our insides. Cuz (elaboration) our wrongs make us (be) cut off/separated off from God. When Yesus Kristus died like that, God's Spirit who lives forever, was helping (doublet) Him so He could turn over/surrender Himself to God2, like an animal sacrifice which has not even a little blemish on its body. So (consequently), now, we-inc can already worship wholeheartedly God who lives forever without end. [NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="like Verse 9. TERM: apollymi: &quot;cut"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">like Verse 9. TERM: apollymi: "cut us off from God" or active "cut ourself off from God."<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>LITERALLY: How much more, then, will the blood of Christ, who through the eternal Spirit offered himself unblemished to God, cleanse our consciences from acts that lead to death, so that we may serve the living God!</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Lula raa Kristus dhu kab'ua risi eele èèna, ka Ama Lamatua pake Ne, ho ator lii pajaji hiu hia mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama Lamatua paroa nare si, j'aj'i dhèu unu Na. Te lod'o Kristus madhe ho hia mamuri mi dhèu, Nèngu sui nare kahèi bèi-baki èdhi nèti sasala dhu ra ad'u-ue uru-uru sèra, lod'o Ama Lamatua pa'èki lii pajaji dhui dènge ra. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu bisa mamuri taa-taa dènge Ama Lamatua kahèi.<bt>Because of Kristus' blood which is most valuable, God used Him, to arrange a new promise for all the people whom God had called to be/become His people. Cuz (elaboration) when Kristus died to save people, He also *redeemed/ransomed our ancestors (doublet) from the wrongs which they had done (doublet) long ago, when God bound the old/previous promise with them. Because of that, they also can live forever with God. [EXEG: Careful about noise from the English word ‘mediator’. The Gk word can have the force of 1) “go-between” (which most people default to), or 2) the one who arranges (LN “guaranteeing the certainty of the arrangement”). The first sense doesn't actually fit this context, so TB ‘perantara’ really skews the focus. TEV “the one who arranges” is much better in this context.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For this reason Christ is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For this reason Christ is the mediator of a new covenant, that those who are called may receive the promised eternal inheritance--now that he has died as a ransom to set them free from the sins committed under the first covenant.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ja'a pakasame dènge dhèu abhu pusaka, nuka sèmi ca dhèu ama dhu tao sasuri pajaji, ho hia ana na pusaka. Te ngaa ladhe ama na madhe, heka ana èèna abhu pusaka sèra.<bt>I use the example of a person receiving inheritance, like a father makes a will (lit. letter of promise) to later give an inheritance to his child. But that child can only get/obtain that inheritance, if/when his father has died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: In the case of a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: In the case of a will, it is necessary to prove the death of the one who made it,</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Te ladhe ama na dhae madhe mèka, ana na bisa mèka abhu pusaka dhu ama na padhadha ètu d'ara sasuri pajaji èèna.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) when that father has not yet died, his child is not yet able to get/obtain that inheritance which the father has already promised in that will.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: because a will is in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: because a will is in force only when somebody has died; it never takes effect while the one who made it is living.</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Èci èèna ka dènge lii pajaji Ama Lamatua dhu partama, dhu Na pa'èki dènge bèi-baki èdhi sèra. Ladhe abhu dhu madhe uuru, heka rèngu abhu ngaa dhu Lamatua jaji. Nèti èèna ka, korban rèngu pake raa badha ho j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, abhu dhu madhe le.<bt>It is also like that with God's first promise which He bound with our ancestors (doublet). They can only receive what God2 has promised, if there is one who dies first. That is why their sacrifices used the blood of animals as sign/proof that there was some(thing/one) that had already died. [NOTE to daughter translators: blood is introduced in vs.18 as example of broader principle in 17, and flowing on into 19. So don't replace it with ‘death’ here by treating it as metonymy--it needs to be blood here. See NLT.] [EXEG: CEV undertranslated here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: This is why even the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: This is why even the first covenant was not put into effect without blood.</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Uru èèna, Musa oru nare bèi-baki èdhi, ka na peka aa'i paredha dhu abhu ètu d'ara atora dhu Lamatua papuru mai. Èle èèna ka, Musa roro sapi dènge kahib'i sèna ka nare raa, ka na pab'ali dènge èi. Musa nare dhari mea kahèi, ka na pa'èki dènge pèri-pèri ana aaj'u dhu rèu lutu. Hèia na cèb'u asa d'ara raa èèna, ka pici mi Sasuri Lamatua, aa mi dhèu unu na aa'i-aa'i si.<bt>At that time, Musa gathered3 our ancestors (doublet), so he could tell them all the commands which were in those regulations that God2 had handed down. After that, Musa killed cows and goats, to get their blood, then mix it with water. Musa also took a red string/rope/ cord to tie the trunks/stems/stalks of fine leaves. Then he dipped them into that blood, to shake/brush it on God's Writings, and on all the populace/people. [NOTE to daughter translations: Look at entry and picture for ‘hisop’ in Kamus Alkitab bhs Kupang, and discuss best wording for tying a bunch of these together.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pago tangke daon."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pago tangke daon.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: When Moses had proclaimed every"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: When Moses had proclaimed every commandment of the law to all the people, he took the blood of calves and goats, together with water, scarlet wool and branches of hyssop, and sprinkled the scroll and all the people.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani, peka na, rèu ne, ngara na ὕσσωπος (<span class="Italic">hussopos</span>). Baca ètu d'ara <span class="Italic">Kamus Pengantar Alkitab</span> sasuri nèti ‘hisop’.<bt>The Yunani language Bible says the name of these leaves is ὕσσωπος (<span class="Italic">hyssopos</span>). Read the entry in the <span class="Italic">Introductory Bible Dictionary </span>for ‘hisop’.</bt></note><v n="20" />Lod'o Musa pici raa ne, na padhai lii kahèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Raa ne'e ne j'aj'i mi tadha, dhu peka na, Ama Lamatua dhu pa'èki lii pajaji dènge miu. Ladhe miu madhutu aa'i paredha Na, bèli-camèd'a Nèngu hia aa'i dhu Na pajaji le sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Musa shook/brushed that blood, he also spoke, saying, “This blood is a sign that God is binding a promise with you-pl. If you do according to all His commands, He will also give everything that He has promised.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: Mark 14:24 blood of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">TERM: Mark 14:24 blood of the covenant. LITERALLY: He said, "This is the blood of the covenant, which God has commanded you to keep."<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="9:19-20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 24:6-8</note><v n="21" />Musa pici raa asa Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i kahèi, dènge asa mèdha aa'i-aa'i ètu sèra, dhu ra pake ho pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua.<bt>Musa also shook/brushed blood at/on the Tent of Prayer, and all the things there which they used to worship God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: In the same way, he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: In the same way, he sprinkled with the blood both the tabernacle and everything used in its ceremonies.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 8:15</note><v n="22" />Te madhutu atora Lamatua, aa'i-aa'i dhu kaj'alu hud'i pamèu ku pake raa. Nèti èèna ka, ladhe dhèu rai-haha neo j'aj'i mola-mèci nèti sasala ra, hud'i dènge ku raa korban.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) according to God2's regulations, everything that is filthy/defiled, must be cleansed/ purified using blood. Because of that, if humans want to become clean/pure (doublet) from their wrongs, there must be blood from a sacrifice.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: In fact, the law require"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: In fact, the law require that nearly everything be cleansed with blood, and without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 17:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ngaa dhu ja'a lole nèti j'ara bèi-baki èdhi dènge Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i, se'e se dhoka conto di, sèna ka èdhi bisa te'a mèu, era manèngi-mangaj'i Ama Lamatua dhu asli ètu sorga. Te ladhe kètu agama rupa dhui neo lasi asa d'ara Paleo èèna ho manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua, rèngu hud'i pamèu aa'i-aa'i ku pake raa badha korban. Era manèngi-mangaj'i Ama Lamatua ètu sorga kahèi hud'i mèu taruu-taruu. Te ngaa hud'i pake ku raa korban dhu kab'ua risi eele nèti raa badha.<bt>What I am narrating about our ancestors (doublet) and their Tent of Prayer, all that is merely an example, so that we-inc can understand God's original/real place of prayer/worship in heaven. Cuz (elaboration) if a *priest of the old model wants to go into that Tent to worship (doublet) God, they must cleanse/purify everything first, using the blood of an animal sacrifice. God's place of prayer (doublet) in heaven must also be clean/pure/holy. But blood must be used from a sacrifice which is even more valuable than an animal's blood.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: It was necessary, then, for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: It was necessary, then, for the copies of the heavenly things to be purified with these sacrifices, but the heavenly things themselves with better sacrifices than these.</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Kama Luri Mola-Mèci dhu Kristus maso èèna, ètu boe d'ara Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i dhu dhèu rai-haha tao. Te Paleo dhu ètu rai-haha èèna, dhoka conto di nèti dhu asli. Te ngaa Kristus la'e unu Na asa sorga ho sarii èdhi ètu madha Ama Lamatua.<bt>That Most Holy Room which Kristus enters, is not in the Tent of Prayer which humans made. Cuz (elaboration) that Tent on earth is only an example of the asli/original. But Kristus goes directly in heaven himself to defend us before God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Like 9:8 LITERALLY: For Christ did"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">Like 9:8 LITERALLY: For Christ did not enter a man-made sanctuary that was only a copy of the true one; he entered heaven itself, now to appear for us in God's presence.<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Uru èèna, kètu kapai risi agama hud'i maso ku la'e asa d'ara Kama Luri Mola-Mèci èèna ca tèu ca tèka, aa nèti dènge raa badha hia Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa Kristus aad'o sèmi èèna. Te Nèngu parluu maso dhoka ca tèka di, nèti dènge raa Nèngu unu Na.<bt>Formerly, the *high priest had to enter repeatedly each year into that Most Holy Room, and take animal's blood to God. But Kristus is not like that. Cuz (elaboration) He only needs to enter once, bringing with Him His own blood.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Nor did he enter heaven"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Nor did he enter heaven to offer himself again and again, the way the high priest enters the Most Holy Place every year with blood that is not his own.</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Te ladhe tèu mai-tèu mai, hud'i Na maso sama sèmi kètu agama dhu uru sèra, sasoa na, Nèngu hud'i madhe ku pahari-pahari karèi nèti j'aj'aj'i rai-haha toke deo ne'e, sèna ka saku eele aa'i sasala nèti dhèu èci-èci. Te ngaa Na tao boe sèmi èèna. Te ropa d'ai lod'o na, Nèngu madhe j'aj'i korban dhoka ca tèka èèna di, ho core eele aa'i sasala dhu dhèu ad'u-ue.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if He must enter each year like the old/former *priest, that means that He must die repeatedly beginning from the earth's beginnings until now in order to wipe away all (individual) people's wrongs. But He does/did not do that. Cuz (elaboration) just at the right time He became a sacrifice one time only, to get rid of all wrongs which people did/do. [EXEG: See discussion in Kupang, Nov 2012.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Then Christ would have had"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Then Christ would have had to suffer many times since the creation of the world. But now he has appeared once for all at the end of the ages to do away with sin by the sacrifice of himself.</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Dhu lèke ka, dhèu rai-haha madhe dhoka ca tèka di. Èle èèna, nèngu hud'i la'e asa madha Ama Lamatua ho Ama Lamatua parisa ne.<bt>It is clear (perfective) that humans die only once. But after that s/he must come before God (implying before an authority) so God examines him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Just as man is destined"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Just as man is destined to die once, and after that to face judgment,</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Sèmi èèna kahèi Kristus. Nèngu madhe, aa saraka ngi'u Na ho j'aj'i korban ca tèka èèna ka. Aa bèli-camèd'a Na lèpa hari mai. Te ngaa Na mai uri heka sasala dhèu, lula Na tao pa'èle aa'i le sasab'a èèna. Te ngaa dhu Na uri, nuka pala mamuri hia mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu sanao-maena mi Nèngu.<bt>It is the same with Kristus. He died and turned over/ surrendered Himself to become a sacrifice only once. And He will also come back again. But He does not come to arrange/deal with people's wrongs anymore, because He has already fully taken care of that responsibility. But what He is going to deal with/ handle/manage, is saving everyone who is/has been hoping/trusting (doublet) in Him. [EXEG: Bruce, Miller]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: so Christ was sacrificed once"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: so Christ was sacrificed once to take away the sins of many people; and he will appear a second time, not to bear sin, but to bring salvation to those who are waiting for him.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 53:12</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kristus madhe dhoka ca tèka di, sèna ka dhèu bisa mamuri pabe'a taruu dènge Ama Lamatua<bt>Kristus died just one time, so people could live in right-relationship with God continually</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="10" />
      <v n="1" />Ladhe tare'a-re'a dhèu neo re'a mèu dad'èi Ama Lamatua, atora dhu Na pangèd'u asa bèi-baki èdhi sèra, dhae led'a iia mèka. Te aa'i-aa'i se nuka sèmi sanabhu nèti j'ara-j'ara hua iia dhu Lamatua neo hia èdhi. De masi ka dhèu madhutu aa'i atora, aa rèti dènge badha korban taruu-taruu, te ngaa bisa boe saku pamèu sasala rèngu.<bt>If we-inc truly want to understand the will/ ways/things of God, those regulations which He handed over to our ancestors (doublet) are still unclear. Cuz (elaboration) all of them are only a shadow of the good things that God2 wants to give us. So (consequently) even if/though people completely follow those regulations, and keep bringing animal sacrifices, nevertheless that can not make their wrongs truly/completely clean/holy/pure. [CHECK /sanabhu/, may not be widely known.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sanabhu = bayang-bayang (UNS do know"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">sanabhu = bayang-bayang (UNS do know it) ; mamaho = sombar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: The law is only a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: The law is only a shadow of the good things that are coming--not the realities themselves. For this reason it can never, by the same sacrifices repeated endlessly year after year, make perfect those who draw near to worship.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Te ladhe atora ne bisa tao eele sasala dhèu, na, rèngu rèti heka badha korban, lula rèngu rasa heka sala. Te ngaa sèmi boe èèna.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if those regulations can/could make their wrongs truly/really disappear, na, they would not bring animal sacrifices anymore, because they no longer feel wrong anymore. Whereas in fact it is not like that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tao eele here = bekin hilang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">tao eele here = bekin hilang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: If it could, would they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: If it could, would they not have stopped being offered? For the worshipers would have been cleansed once for all, and would no longer have felt guilty for their sins.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Te tèu mai-tèu mai rèngu manèngi pahari-pahari ho Ama Lamatua saku eele sasala ra,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) each year they keep asking repeatedly for God to wipe away their wrongs,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But those sacrifices are an"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But those sacrifices are an annual reminder of sins.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />lula, tatu boe raa badha dènge koasa, sèna ka saku eele sasala dhèu toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>because it is not probable/possible that the blood of animals has power/authority, to truly wipe away people's wrongs forever. [EXEG: Bruce, Miller]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: because it is impossible for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: because it is impossible for the blood of bulls and goats to take away sins.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5-6" />Nèti èèna ka, Kristus peka sèmi ne'e, lod'o Na mai asa rai-haha ne, aku Nèngu na,<bt>That is why Kristus spoke like this when He came to this world:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua!<bt>“God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ama d'èi boe badha korban dènge mèdha persembahan dhu rèngu rèti.<bt>Father (=You) don't like the animal sacrifices and (other) offerings that they bring.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rèngu roro pamadhe badha ae-ae,<bt>They ritually slaughter a great many animals,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka j'aj'i korban.<bt>to be sacrifices.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ka rèngu tunu badha sèra,<bt>And they burn/roast those animals,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho manèngi abho.<bt>to ask forgiveness.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa d'ara Ama karej'e boe.<bt>Even that being the case, nevertheless God2's insides are not happy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti èèna ka, Ama pua Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne,<bt>That is why Father ordered Me to come to this world,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu rai-haha sama sèmi rèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>to become human like them.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore, when Christ came into"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore, when Christ came into the world, he said, "Sacrifice and offering you did not desire, but a body you prepared for me; with burnt offerings and sin offerings you were not pleased.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Hèia Kristus tuhu hari lii, aku Nèngu na,<bt>And then, that Kristus also spoke, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ama! Ja'a ka ne'e le!<bt>“Father! I am already here!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a mai sèna ka tao madhutu dad'èi Ama,<bt>I came to do according to Father's will,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">nuka sèmi dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama dhu suri mema lula-nèti Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>like Father's *spokesman/prophet has written beforehand about Me.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Then I [Christ] said, 'Here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Then I [Christ] said, 'Here I am--it is written about me in the scroll--I have come to do your will, O God'"</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:5-7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 40:7-9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />De dhu Kristus peka partama, nuka:<bt>So (consequently), what Kristus had said first was:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua karej'e boe dènge badha korban, aa mèdha persembahan dhu rèngu rèti.<bt>“God is not happy with the animal sacrifices and (other) offerings which they brought.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rèngu roro pamadhe badha ae-ae,<bt>They ritually slaughter a great many animals,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka j'aj'i korban.<bt>to be sacrifices.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Hèia ra tunu badha sèra,<bt>And then they burn/roast those animals,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho manèngi abho.<bt>to ask foregiveness.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa masi ka sèmi èèna, d'ara Lamatua karej'e boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>But even that being the case, God2's insides are not happy.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De masi ka rèngu tao madhutu le pamèci dènge atora Musa, te ngaa d'ara Ama Lamatua karej'e boe ciki sa.<bt>So (consequently), even though they did exactly according to Musa's regulations, nevertheless God's insides are not happy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: First he said, &quot;Sacrifices and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: First he said, "Sacrifices and offerings, burnt offerings and sin offerings you did not desire, nor were you pleased with them" (although the law required them to be made).</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Lod'o Kristus padhai lii, peka na,<bt>When Kristus spoke, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a mai, sèna ka tao madhutu dad'èi Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>“I came to do according to God2's will/way.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Sasoa na, Kristus mai sèna ka tao eele j'ara dhui, ho gati dènge j'ara hiu.<bt>That means that Kristus came to get rid of the old way, to replace it with a new way.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Then he [Christ] said, &quot;Here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Then he [Christ] said, "Here I am. I have come to do your will." He sets aside the first to establish the second.</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Te dad'èi Lamatua ka, Yesus Kristus j'aj'i korban ho madhe dhoka ca tèka di hia èdhi dhèu rai-haha. Dènge j'ara ne'e, Na pamèu èdhi toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God2's will is that Yesus Kristus became a sacrifice to die one time for we-inc humans. In that way, He cleansed/purified us-inc forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And by that will, we"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And by that will, we have been made holy through the sacrifice of the body of Jesus Christ once for all.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Bèli-bèli kètu agama rupa dhui pakako taruu sasab'a ra, aa roro pamadhe badha korban. Aa te ngaa korban se, dènge boe koasa sèna ka saku eele sasala dhèu.<bt>Each day, the *priests of the old model kept carrying out their job/responsibilities, and kept ritual killing animal sacrifices. Whereas in fact, those sacrifices did not have power/authority to wipe away people's wrongs.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hesteeken: take his place, show up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">hesteeken: take his place, show up for work LITERALLY: Day after day every priest stands and performs his religious duties; again and again he offers the same sacrifices, which can never take away sins.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="10:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 29:38</note><v n="12" />Te ngaa Kètu Kapai Risi Agama èdhi, nuka Kristus, saraka ngi'u Na ho madhe sèna ka j'aj'i korban hia èdhi. Nèngu j'aj'i korban dhoka ca tèka èèna di. Dènge tao sèmi èèna, Na bhoke j'ara sèna ka saku eele sasala èdhi dhèu rai-haha aa'i-aa'i ti. Èle èèna, heka Nèngu la'e madhèdi ètu baboa g'ana Ama Lamatua, ètu era dhu kab'ua risi eele.<bt>But our-inc *High Priest, that is Kristus, surrendered/ handed over Himself to die as a sacrifice for us. He was a sacrifice just one time. By doing that, He has opened the way to completely wipe away all our all of our human wrongs. After that, then He went (and) sat at God's right side, in the place of highest respect/ honour.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But when this priest had"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But when this priest had offered for all time one sacrifice for sins, he sat down at the right hand of God.</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ètu era nèi, Na mate toke Ama Lamatua tao musu Na sèra mai pahaha iisi mi Nèngu.<bt>In that place (remote), He is waiting until God makes His enemies surrender/be in subjection to Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: footstool. Regularized? LITERALLY: Since that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">TERM: footstool. Regularized? LITERALLY: Since that time he waits for his enemies to be made his footstool,<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="10:12-13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:1</note><v n="14" />Korban Nèngu dhu ca tèka èèna, pama'ète eele koasa sasala-sasigo nèti dhèu dhu Kristus pamèu si.<bt>That one-time sacrifice of His, completely breaks/severs the power/authority of sin/wrong (doublet) for the people whom Kristus cleanses/purifies. [CHECK metaphor for killing or breaking the power of s.t.] [NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Na saraka ngi'u Na dhoka ca"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Na saraka ngi'u Na dhoka ca tèka di. Dènge j'ara ne dhèu dhu Na cap nare sèra, ra peka na rèngu dènge heka sasala, Na tao pamèu taruu dara si.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: because by one sacrifice he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: because by one sacrifice he has made perfect forever those who are being made holy.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci peka j'ara dhu sèmi èèna kahèi hia mi èdhi. Te Na padhai lii nèdhi, peka na,<bt>God's Holy Spirit has also told/explained/made known that same matter to us-inc. Cuz (elaboration) He once spoke, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: The Holy Spirit also testifies"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: The Holy Spirit also testifies to us about this. First he says,</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />&lt;&lt;Lamatua miu peka sèmi ne'e:<bt>&lt;&lt;God2 tells/makes known like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a pa'èki lii pajaji hiu dènge dhèu unu Ja'a,<bt>I bind a new promise with My people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a tao atora Ja'a ètu d'ara ngangee ra,<bt>I place My regulations in their thoughts.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge suri paredha Ja'a ètu d'ara ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>and I write My commands in their insides.’”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: &quot;This is the covenant I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: "This is the covenant I will make with them after that time, says the Lord. I will put my laws in their hearts, and I will write them on their minds."</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 31:33</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia Na peka hari, na,<bt>Then He says further, that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Èèna na Ja'a sanèd'e heka sasala ra.<bt>“I will not remember their wrongs anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Ja'a pabhèlu eele tatao rèngu dhu karehe,<bt>And I have (completely) forgotten their bad deeds, [NOTE to daughter translations: KM /bekin-bekin/ is ONLY negative. Reflect that with s.t. like “their bad deeds”.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lod'o rèngu sisu atora Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>when they transgressed My regulations.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Then he adds: &quot;Their sins"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Then he adds: "Their sins and lawless acts I will remember no more."</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 31:34</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Sasoa na, ladhe Ama Lamatua saku eele le sasala dhèu, èèna na rèngu parluu heka rèti badha korban, sèna ka pamaho d'ara Lamatua.<bt>That means that if God has already wiped away people's wrongs, they no longer need to bring sacrifices in.order to cool God's insides.” [See NLT.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamaho = kasi dingin (anger, etc.)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pamaho = kasi dingin (anger, etc.)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And where these have been"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And where these have been forgiven, there is no longer any sacrifice for sin.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Èdhi madha'u iia ka lati asa katanga madha Ama Lamatua<bt>We-inc do not need to be fearful coming before God</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />De sèmi ne'e a'ari aa'i-aa'i! Yesus pasuti le raa Na, sèna ka cuhi d'ara Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, limuri ne èdhi madha'u ia ka lati asa katanga madha Na ètu Era Na dhu Mola-Mèci ètu sorga.<bt>So (consequently) it's like this, siblings! Yesus has spilled His blood [NOTE: common figure of speech in region relating to bloodshed/death for a cause, such as political revolution or reform] to cool God's insides. That is why, now we do not need to be fearful anymore about coming before Him in His Most Holy Place in heaven. [NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="CHECK ALL: cuhi dara (not pacuhi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">CHECK ALL: cuhi dara (not pacuhi dara)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore, brothers, since we have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore, brothers, since we have confidence to enter the [Most] Holy Place by the blood of Jesus,</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Pangee ku Kama Luri Mola-Mèci dhu dhui èèna. Ètu era èèna, abhu bèla bhiri ca bèla dhu bhèla aae, dhu pa'abhe sèna ka dhèu baku lasi asa katanga madha Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa dènge mamadhe Yesus èèna, Na bhoke j'ara hiu, ho dhèu bisa padhai lii patoo madha dènge Ama Lamatua.<bt>Think about that old Most Holy Room! There, there was a large/wide curtain which blocked off so people may not enter directly before/fronting up to God. But by Yesus' death, He opened a new way/path, so people are able to talk directly with God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="CIE = abhu bèla bhiri ca"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">CIE = abhu bèla bhiri ca bèla dhu bhèla aae, “ada kain pele satu lembar yg sangat lebar”</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: sarkos. Discuss in Introduction? LITERALLY:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">TERM: sarkos. Discuss in Introduction? LITERALLY: by a new and living way opened for us through the curtain, that is, his body,<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Risi-risi hari, Yesus j'aj'i kètu agama dhu kapai risi, dhu uri dènge lalau-lalo'o isi èmu Ama Lamatua.<bt>Even more than that, Yesus is also the greatest *priest. who serves (doublet) and oversees/guides God's household/family2. [NOTE to daughter translations: check to make sure the “household” word in your lg focuses on the people, not the things.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: and since we have a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: and since we have a great priest over the house of God,</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />De limuri ne èdhi dènge hak. Nèti èèna ka, mai ti maso ho padhai lii patoo madha dènge Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa èdhi hud'i parcaya Ne tare'a-re'a dènge d'ara mola. Te mamadhe Yesus ka dhu pamèu le d'ara èdhi, toke èdhi pangee heka j'ara-j'ara bhelu-katub'a. Aa èdhi hud'i mamuri mola, nuka sèmi ama agama rupa dhui sèra, hud'i diu ku èi, heka maso lasi pakako sasab'a Lamatua.<bt>So (consequently) now we have the right. Therefore, let us enter before God to speak directly with Him. But we must truly believe in Him with a straight/righteous insides. Cuz (elaboration) Yesus' death has cleansed/purified our insides, to the point that we no longer think about evil things (doublet). And we must also live straight/righteous, like priests of the old model had to bathe first before they entered to carry out God2's work. [EXEG: Bruce, Miller, Ellingsworth]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hahera = kotoran"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">hahera = kotoran</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aleethinees kardias: sincere hearts LITERALLY: let"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">aleethinees kardias: sincere hearts LITERALLY: let us draw near to God with a sincere heart in full assurance of faith, having our hearts sprinkled to cleanse us from a guilty conscience, and having our bodies washed with pure water.<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="10:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 8:30, 16:4, Yeskial 36:25</note><v n="23" />Mai ho èdhi kèpe pa'èra-èra kahèi, aa'i-aa'i dhu èdhi mangaku le lula-nèti Ama Lamatua. Aa èdhi hud'i sanao-maena mi Nèngu kahèi, aa pangee ia ka dhu leo, te tatu Na tao madhutu lii pajaji Na.<bt>Let us also hold firmly to everything that we have confessed/acknowledged about God. We must hope (doublet) in Him no longer worrying about other (things/matters), cuz (elaboration) He will surely do according to His promise.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Let us hold unswerving to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Let us hold unswerving to the hope we profess, for he who promised is faithful.</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />De mai èdhi patangi-tenge j'ara ho pamako a'ari èdhi dhèu parcaya sèra, sèna ka èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti pad'elo sasue ae-ae, aa dènge tao rupa-rupa j'ara dhu be'a.<bt>And let us-inc be looking for (doublet) ways to be persuading/coaxing/enticing/cajoling our fellow believers, so that all of us show/demonstrate much love and do various sorts of good things.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haduli = peduli"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">haduli = peduli</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And let us consider how"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And let us consider how we may [spur / stimulate] one another on toward love and good deeds.</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Te ja'a tadèngi le, abhu dhèu cahag'e dhu ro'o heka pakaboko dènge a'ari ra dhèu parcaya. Te ngaa mage miu sèmi èèna! Te miu hud'i pa'asu-pareo ku, ho pa'èra d'ara èci dènge èci. Risi-risi, lula lod'o mamai hari Lamatua dètu le. Pasanèd'e si sèmi èèna!<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I have heard that there are some people who don't want to gather anymore with their fellow believers. But it should not be like that! Cuz (elaboration) you-pl must get together (doublet) to strengthen/ encourage each other's insides. Even more than that, because God2's time for coming back is already very near. Remind/warn them like that!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Let us not give up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Let us not give up meeting together, as some are in the habit of doing, but let us encourage one another--and all the more as you see the Day approaching.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />A'ari pasue! Èdhi te'a le toke lutu-sela, j'ara-j'ara Yesus Kristus dhu mola. Te ngaa ladhe èdhi soro kabodho mi Yesus, aa ad'u-ue taruu sasala, sasoa na, abhu heka korban leo dhu bisa saku eele sasala èdhi.<bt>Dear siblings! We already know in detail (doublet) about Yesus Kristus' straight/true way. But if we turn our backs on Yesus, and keep doing (doublet) wrong, that means that there is no other sacrifice which is able to wipe away our-inc wrongs. [DISCOURSE: NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: If we deliberately keep on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: If we deliberately keep on sinning after we have received the knowledge of the truth, no sacrifice for sins is left.</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Èdhi dhoka mate dènge d'ara madha'u, lula Ama Lamatua mai huku èdhi. Te ai naraka heo robhe-robhe le, ho pakèpu dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu lab'a Lamatua.<bt>We can only wait with fear because God will come and punish us. Cuz (elaboration) the fires of *hell (fully assimilated loan) are already burning fiercely to burn up everyone who opposes/rebels against God2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heo robhe-robhe = blaze, rage ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">heo robhe-robhe = blaze, rage ; pakèpu = burned (can be wounded but not necessarily burned to ashes)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: but only a certain fearful"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: but only a certain fearful expectation of judgment, and of raging fire that will consume the enemies of God.</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 26:11</note><v n="28" />Uru èèna, ladhe abhu ca dhèu dhu tule eele atora Musa, aa abhu dua do tèlu dhèu dhu j'aj'i sakasii, na, dhèu èèna hud'i abhu huku madhe, hia boe ne abho.<bt>Formerly, if there was one person who rejects Musa's regulations, and there were two or three people who were witnesses like that, that person must get death punishment, and there was no forgiveness for him/her. [EXEG: Most sources say this is Gk word “reject, refuse to obey, regard as invalid”, not merely ‘violate, transgress. NRSV is an exception on this.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Anyone who rejected the law"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Anyone who rejected the law of Moses died without mercy on the testimony of two or three witnesses.</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 17:6, 19:15</note><v n="29" />Te ngaa limuri ne, ladhe abhu dhèu dhu pahahe Ana Ama Lamatua, èèna sama sèmi nèngu pakab'ua boe raa Yesus dhu Na pasuti sèna ka pamèu dhèu èèna. Aa no'o boe pane'a dènge lii pajaji dhu Ama Lamatua pa'èki dènge nèngu pake raa èèna ka. Aa nèngu tao Roh Ama Lamatua nasa kahèi. Te Roh èèna ka dhu pad'elo le d'ara hua iia Na mi nèngu. Pangee ku laa! Te dhèu sèmi ne'e ne, tatu pasae nare hahuku dhu bia risi nèti dhèu dhu tule eele atora Musa.<bt>But now, if there is a person who shows contempt for/belittles God's Child, that is the same as if he does not honour/value Yesus' blood, which He has spilled (for a cause) to cleanse/purify that person. And s/he doesn't care about God's promise, which He bound with that person using that blood. And s/he also angers God's Spirit. Cuz (elaboration) that Spirit is the one who has shown/demonstrated goodness/ grace/ kindness/generosity to him/her. Just think! Cuz (elaboration) people of this sort will surely bear a punishment which is far heavier/severe than people who rejected Musa's regulations. [EXEG: Miller]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: How much more severely do"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: How much more severely do you think a man needs to be punished who has trampled the Son of God under foot, who has treated as an unholy thing the blood of the covenant that sanctified him, and who has insulted the Spirit of grace?</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 24:8</note><v n="30" />Ama Lamatua peka nèdhi le, na.<bt>God once spoke, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a dènge hak ho b'ala bhelu-katub'a dhèu.<bt>“I have the right to avenge/pay back people's evil (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa tatu Ja'a hud'i tao ku madhutu sèmi èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>And I will surely do according to that.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Aa dhu suri kahèi, na,<bt>And it is also written, that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Lamatua ne, Ama.<bt>“God2 is Father (in position of respect &amp; authority).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Bèli-camèd'a Na huku dhèu unu Na.&gt;&gt;<bt>He will punish His people.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For we know him who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For we know him who said, "Vengence is mine. I will repay." That's what God said. And again, "The Lord will judge his people."</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 32:35, 36</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Sanèd'e te Ama Lamatua mamuri taa-taa! Dhèu tatu madha'u titu kèna, ladhe Lamatua kèpe nare si!<bt>Remember that God lives forever! People will surely be terrified, if/when God2 has captured/caught/ arrested them!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: It is a [dreadful /"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: It is a [dreadful / terrifying] thing to fall into the hands of the Living God!</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Miu hud'i sanèd'e ku lod'o miu mulai me'a j'ara-j'ara Kristus, ka ngangee miu mulai mèu. Te lod'o èèna, masi ka miu dhoka muri ètu d'ara sasusa dènge j'aj'èra ae-ae, te ngaa miu taha dènge parcaya taruu Kristus.<bt>You-pl must remember when you first began to understand about Kristus, and (result) your thinking became clear. Cuz (elaboration) at that time, even though you got a lot of difficulty2/suffering and trouble/difficulty1, nevertheless you endured and/by continued to believe in Kristus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Remember those earlier days after"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Remember those earlier days after you had received the light, when you endured in a great struggle of suffering.</Message></Annotation><v n="33" />Abhu dhu pamakae dènge pahahe miu ètu madha dhèu ae. Abhu kahèi dhu ra tao sèmi èèna mi angalai miu, dhèu parcaya sèra.<bt>There were those who treated you-pl with contempt, and shamed you before many people. There were also those who did those things to your fellow believers.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Sometimes you were publically exposed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Sometimes you were publically exposed to insult and persecution; at other times you stood side by side with those who were so treated.</Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Miu rasa kasia aa pad'elo d'ara be'a mi dhèu dhu ra pamaso si asa d'ara bèdho. Ladhe dhèu mana'u rèti mèdha-panyau miu, miu mau-mau sène, lula miu me'a, na, bèli-camèd'a miu abhu dhu be'a risi, dhu dhèu bisa heka mana'u rare.<bt>You-pl felt pity/mercy and showed goodness/kindness/ grace/ generosity to people who were thrown into prison. If/when people stole your things/possessions (doublet), you were quiet/calm, because you knew that you would later get/receive things that are far better, which people can no longer steal.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te ngaa masi ka dhèu se,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Te ngaa masi ka dhèu se, kèpe rare miu ho pamaso asa dara bui, miu nasa boe. Masi ka mana'u rèti mèdha panyau miu, miu mau-mau sène, lula miu me'a na, bèli-camèda miu abhu dhu be'a risi dhu dhèu bisa heka mana'u rare.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: You sympathized with those in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: You sympathized with those in prison, and joyfully accepted the confication of your property, because you knew that you yourselves had better and lasting possessions.</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i kèpe pa'èra-èra lalèka miu. Te èèna na Lamatua b'ala hia miu, ae-ae.<bt>That is why you-pl must hold firmly to your belief2. Cuz (elaboration) later God2 will repay many things to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: So do not throw away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: So do not throw away your confidence; it will be richly rewarded.</Message></Annotation><v n="36" />De taha taruu! Te ladhe miu tao madhutu aa'i dad'èi Lamatua, èèna na miu abhu aa'i dhu Na jaji le hia miu.<bt>So (consequently) keep enduring/persevering! Cuz (elaboration) if you do according to all of God2's will, you will get/obtain everything that He has promised you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: You need to persevere, so"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: You need to persevere, so that when you have done the will of God, you will receive what he has promised.</Message></Annotation><v n="37" />Dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua suri le lula-nèti Dhèu dhu neo mai, peka na,<bt>God2's spokespeople have written about the Person Who is Going to Come, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Baku paroe d'ara, te nèbhu boe, Dhèu dhu neo mai èèna, cèu,<bt>“Don't lose hope, cuz (elaboration) it will not be much longer, the Person Who is Going to Come, will appear.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa Na pamate heka.<bt>and He does not wait around/delay.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For in just a very"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For in just a very little while, "He who is coming will come, and will not delay.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="38" />Dhèu dhu d'ara mola,<bt>The person whose insides are straight/righteous,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">èèna na nèngu abhu mamuri,<bt>will be/get saved/life,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula na parcaya Ja'a.<bt>because s/he believes in Me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu pakaj'èu nèti Ja'a,<bt>But if there is someone who distances themselves from Me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">d'ara Ja'a karej'e boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>My insides will not be happy.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But my righteous one will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But my righteous one will live by faith. And if he shrink back, I will not be pleased with him."</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:37-38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Habakuk 2:3-4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Te ngaa èdhi, dhèu dhu pakaj'èu boe nèti Ama Lamatua. Te dhèu dhu pakaj'èu nèti Lamatua, bèli-camèd'a cèri eele nèti Nèngu. Te ngaa èdhi dhèu dhu parcaya Ama Lamatua. Ka Nèngu patabuli èdhi nèti koasa sasala-sasigo èdhi, ho mamuri taruu dènge Ne.<bt>But we-inc are not people who distance ourselves from God. Cuz (elaboration) people who distance themselves from God2, will be cut off/separated off from Him. But we are people who believe in God. So He will save/free/rescue us-inc from our worngs (doublet), to live continually with Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But we are not of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But we are not of those who shrink back and are destroyed, but of those who believe and are saved.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Èdhi hud'i parcaya taruu Ama Lamatua, sama sèmi dhèu uru-uru sèra<bt>We must keep believing in God, like the people of long ago</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="11" />
      <v n="1" />Ladhe èdhi parcaya Ama Lamatua, sasoa na, èdhi lèka tare'a-re'a Nèngu taruu. Te ladhe Na moa le hia èdhi j'ara èci, èdhi te'a, na, tatu Na tao madhutu lii pajaji Nèngu èèna. Masi ka èdhi abhu mèka ngaa-ngaa, èdhi parcaya Ne taruu.<bt>If we-inc believe1 in God, that means we continue to believe2/trust in Him. Cuz (elaboration) if/when He has promised to give something to us, we know that He will surely do according to what He has promised. Even if we have not yet received anything, we just keep believing in Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Bhabhèla na = its width (REDUP)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Bhabhèla na = its width (REDUP) ; bhabhii (asa talora) = agak ke (tengah)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ladhe èdhi parcaya Ama Lamatua, sasoa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Ladhe èdhi parcaya Ama Lamatua, sasoa na, era maena èdhi dhoka Nèngu di. Te, ladhe Na moa hia èdhi mèdha èci, èdhi te'a na, tatu Nèngu hia madhutu lii moa Na. Masi ka èdhi abhu mèka, èdhi parcaya Ne taruu.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Now faith is being sure"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Now faith is being sure of what we hope for and certain of what we do not see.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Abhu bèi-baki èdhi dhu parcaya sèmi èèna kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua sèmi nare si dènge be'a.<bt>There are those among our ancestors (doublet) who believed like that. Because of that, God accepted them well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: This is what the ancients"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: This is what the ancients were commended for.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Rai-haha dènge liru dhu èdhi ladhe tèdhi ne, èdhi te'a, na, Ama Lamatua ka paj'aj'i aa'i mèu-mèu. Te ngaa Na tao boe nèti mèdha dhu j'aj'i le, dhu dhèu bisa rèdhi. Aa'i-aa'i dhu j'aj'i se, j'aj'i nèti lii padhai Na di.<bt>This earth (doublet) and sky which we now see, we believe that God is the one who created all this. But He did not create it using things that already existed, which humans could see. Everything that exists here, came into being because He spoke just using His words/sayings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aorata: Shouldn't imply that there are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">aorata: Shouldn't imply that there are things out there that we can't see, but that God used as the raw material for making the things we can see. Important philosophically. LITERALLY: By faith we understand that the universe was formed at God's command, so that what is seen was not made out of what was visible.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="11:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 1:1, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 33:6, 9, Yohanis 1:3</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Habel [\s2]<bt>Habel [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Habel parcaya Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, nèngu nèti mèdha persembahan dhu be'a risi nèti a'a na Kaen. Ama Lamatua sèmi nare Habel dènge mèdha persembahan na, lula d'ara na mola. De masi ka na madhe nèbhu le, te ngaa èdhi bisa tare conto nèti nèngu, lula lalèka na.<bt>Habel believed in God. Because of that he brought a better offering than his elder-sibling Kaen. God accepted Habel and his offering, because of his straight/right/just insides. So (consequently), even though he has been long dead, we-inc can still learn from him, because of his belief2. [NOTE: the term glossed here and in following verses as "accepted" could also be glossed "accepted favourably".]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith Abel offered God"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith Abel offered God a better sacrifice than Cain did. By faith he was commended as a righteous man, when God spoke well of his offerings. And by faith he still speaks, even though he is dead.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 4:3-10</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Henok [\s2]<bt>Henok [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Henok parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua nedhe nèti ne asa sorga, sèna ka baku madhe. Dhèu patangi-tenge ne, te ngaa rage boe, lula Lamatua dhu paca'e le. Lamatua sèmi nare ne dènge be'a, te Lamatua dhu peka, na, &lt;&lt;Henok ne, dhèu dhu pakarej'e d'ara Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Henok also believed in God. Because of that God took him up to heaven, so that he didn't die. People kept looking for him, but they didn't find him, because God2 had taken him up. God2 accepted him, cuz God2 was saying, “This Henok, is a person who makes My insides happy.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith Enoch was taken"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith Enoch was taken from this life, so that he did not experience death; he could not be found, because God had taken him away. For before he was taken, he was commended as one who pleased God.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 5:21-24</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />De sèmi ne'e a'ari! Dhu lèke ka, Ama Lamatua sèmi nare boe dhèu dhu parcaya boe Nèngu. Te dhèu dhu neo la'e asa madha Ama Lamatua hud'i parcaya, peka na, Lamatua dhu mema-mema. Aa nèngu hud'i parcaya kahèi, peka na, Lamatua soru nare dhèu dhu patangi-tenge Ne.<bt>So (consequently) it's like this, siblings! It is true that God does not accept people who do not trust/believe in Him. Cuz (elaboration) people who want to come before God, must believe, saying/that, God really is/exists. And s/he must believe that God helps people who seek (doublet) Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And without faith it is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And without faith it is impossible to please God, because anyone who comes to him must believe that he exists and that he rewards those who earnestly seek him.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Noh [\s2]<bt>Noh [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Noh parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, Noh parcaya Lamatua ropa Lamatua peka mema dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Noh! Sanèd'e, ee! Èèna na Ja'a palaho eele rai-haha ne, pake èi aae lala dhu dhèu rai-haha ne rèdhi mèka ca tèka sa.&gt;&gt; Masi ka Noh paraga nèdhi mèka sèmi èèna, te ngaa nèngu nanene ka tao madhutu lii Lamatua, hèia na tao kapa, sèna ka nèngu dènge isi èmu na abhu sod'a. Lula lalèka na, ka Lamatua cap ne dhèu d'ara mola. Te ngaa dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu lèka boe sèra, Lamatua hia si hahuku dhu bia.<bt>Noh also believed God. Because of that, Noh believed God2 when He told him beforehand, saying, “Noh! Remember, ee! I will destroy this world using a large flood which humans have never yet seen.” Even though Noh had never encountered anything like that, he listened and obeyed God's instructions, so he made a ship so he and his household could live/be saved. Because of that belief2 of his, God2 stamped/branded/categorized Him as a person with straight/right/just insides. But everyone who didn't believe2, God2 punished them heavily/severely.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mone aanga = companions (age grade"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">mone aanga = companions (age grade mates) @@@</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith, Noah, when warned"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith, Noah, when warned about things not yet seen, in holy fear built an ark to save his family. By faith he condemned the world and became heir of the righteousness that comes by faith.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Nèti èèna ka, Lamatua peka mema"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Nèti èèna ka, Lamatua peka mema dènge ne,</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 6:13-22</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham tèke eele rai èta-èsu na [\s2]<bt>Abraham left his village of origins [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Abraham parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua paroa ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abraham! Kalua nèti rai èta-èsu èu ne, ho lamu asa era dhu pe Ja'a pad'elo dènge mu. Te rai èèna, bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i mi pusaka ana-èpu èu.&gt;&gt; Tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, Abraham tao madhutu, masi ka nèngu ne'a boe la'e asa era mia.<bt>Abraham also believed in God. That is why God called him, saying, “Abraham! Go out leaving behind your-sg origin village to go to a place which I will show you. Cuz (elaboration) that land will become an inheritance to your descendants (doublet).” Hearing that, Abraham did accordingly, even though he didn't know where he was going.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith Abraham, when called"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith Abraham, when called to go to a place he would later receive as his possession, obeyed and went, even though he did not know where he was going.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 12:1-5</note><v n="9" />Ropa Abraham d'ai era èèna, na patitu paleo, ho pea nuka sèmi dhèu tao mai ètu rai èèna dhu Lamatua pajaji le dènge ne. Ka ana na Isak dènge èpu na Yakob pea ètu èèna, te Lamatua dhu padhadha le hia rai ne j'aj'i pusaka rèngu.<bt>When Abraham arrived at that land, he erected his tent, to live as a foreigner on that land which God2 had promised to give to him. Then his child Isak and his grandchild Yakob also lived there, cuz (elaboration) God2 had promised2 to give that land to be their inheritance.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu tao mai = pendatang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">dhèu tao mai = pendatang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith he made his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith he made his home in the promised land like a stranger in a foreign country; he lived in tents, as did Isaac and Jacob, who were heirs with him of the same promise.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 35:27</note><v n="10" />Na sanao, sèna ka nèngu pea ètu kota cue dhu saraga titu kèna. Te Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka dhu gambar ho pakèd'i kota ne.<bt>He hoped that he would later live in a city which was very beautiful. Cuz (elaboration) God himself is the one who made the picture/design to build that city.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For he was looking forward"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For he was looking forward to the city with foundations, whose architect and builder is God.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sara [\s2]<bt>Sara [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Dhèu èmu Abraham, ngara na Sara, parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Masi ka nara iisi nèdhi mèka, aa dhu heka bhora le, te ngaa Lamatua tao ne j'aj'i bèi-baki nèti dhèu ca nau-ca nadha. Te nèngu parcaya, na, tatu Ama Lamatua tao madhutu ngaa dhu Na jaji le.<bt>Sara, Abraham's wife, also believed in God. Even though she had never given birth, and was already old and wrinkled, nevertheless God2 made it so he could could become the ancestor (doublet) to a great ethnic group. Cuz (elaboration) she believed that, God would surely do according to what He had promised. [CHECK ca nau-ca nadha.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ted'i = sonde ada ana (khusus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">ted'i = sonde ada ana (khusus hewan) = ana aad'o (manusia), mandul</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith Sarah, even though"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith Sarah, even though she was sterile and past the age, received power to start a lineage, because she considered him faithful who had made the promise.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 18:11-14, 21:2</note><v n="12" />Nèti èèna ka, masi ka nèngu heka bhora le, nèngu bisa nara iisi era, ka abhu ana-èpu ae-ae, toke ige rare boe. Te dhèu se ae, nuka sèmi hua-hètu ètu dedha-liru, aa sèmi salae nebhe dhasi.<bt>Because of that, even though she was already old and wrinkled, she was still able to give birth and have many descendants (doublet), to the point that nobody is able to count them (successfully). Cuz (elaboration) their quantity is like the stars (doublet) in the sky (doublet), and sand on the beach.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And so from this one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And so from this one man, and he as good as dead, came descendants as numerous as the stars in the sky, and as countless as the sand of the seashore.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 15:5, 22:17, 32:12</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bèi-baki dhu parcaya aa sanao abhu rai èta-èsu cue [\s2]<bt>The forefathers who were believing and hoping for a homeland [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Bèi-baki èdhi Abraham, Isak dènge Yakob parcaya taruu Ama Lamatua, toke madhe. Te ngaa rèngu dhae abhu mèka rai dhu Lamatua pajaji èèna. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa rèngu ma'ète boe sanao dènge d'ara karej'e, te rèngu rèdhi le nèti kaj'èu. Te rèngu dhu mangaku, na, rèngu se dhèu leo rai kara dhu pea manubha ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>Our-inc ancestors Abraham, Isak, and Yakob also continued to believe in God until they died. But they had not yet obtained that land that God2 had promised. Even that being the case, nevertheless they continued to hope with happy insides, because they had already seen (it) from afar. Cuz (elaboration) they had already confessed/ acknowledged that they were foreigners living temporarily on this earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: All these people were still"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: All these people were still living by faith when they died. They did not receive the things promised; they only saw them and welcomed them from a distance. And they admitted that they were foreigners and strangers on earth.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 23:4, 1 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 29:15, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 39:13</note><v n="14" />Aa te ngaa, ladhe dhèu peka sèmi èèna, èdhi te'a, na, rèngu d'èi titu kèna abhu rai cue dhu j'aj'i unu rèngu.<bt>Whereas in fact, for people who speak like that, they already yearn to get a land that they own.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: People who say such things"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: People who say such things show that they are looking for a country of their own.</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ladhe rai dhu bèi-baki èdhi d'èi, nuka rai èta-èsu Abraham, na, tatu rèngu bisa lèpa hari asa era nèi, lod'o mia èèna ka.<bt>If that land that our forefathers had wanted, was Abraham's land of origins, na, surely they could go back home there at any time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: If they had been thinking"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: If they had been thinking about the country they had left, they would have had opportunity to return.</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Te ngaa rai èta-èsu dhu rèngu d'èi titu kèna, nuka rai èta-èsu dhu saraga bia ètu sorga. Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua sèmi nare si dènge be'a, sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu unu Na. Te Na pamèci nare le kota cue hia si ètu sorga.<bt>But that homeland which they yearned for, was a much more beautiful homeland in heaven. Because of that, God accepted them to be His people. Cuz (elaboration) He had already prepared beforehand a city for them in heaven. [CHECK pamèci here]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamèci nare le kota"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pamèci nare le kota</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Instead, they were longing for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Instead, they were longing for a better country--a heavenly one. Therefore, God is not ashamed to be called their God, for he has prepared a city for them.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham saraka ana na Isak [\s2]<bt>Abraham surrendered/turned over/gave up his child Isak [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-18" />Parcaya Abraham hali boe nèti Ama Lamatua, ropa Lamatua uji parcaya na. Nèti èèna ka, na tao madhutu paredha Lamatua, ho saraka ana na Isak j'aj'i korban.<bt>Abraham's faith never wavered from God when God2 was testing his belief. Because of that, he did according to God2's command to give up his child Isak to be a sacrifice.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hali boe = kura boe, tidak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">hali boe = kura boe, tidak berubah</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 22:1-14</note>Aa te ngaa uru èèna, Lamatua dhu moa le, lula-nèti ana ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèti ana mu Isak ne, bèli-camèd'a èu abhu ana-èpu udhu sobhu-sobhu, toke ra j'aj'i suku dhu kapai titu kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Whereas in fact, previously God2 had already promised about that child, saying, “From your-sg child Isak, you will later get a great many (idiom) descendants (doublet), to the point that they become a great (in numbers and/or status/influence) ethnic group.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="udhu sobhu-sobhu = sangat banyak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">udhu sobhu-sobhu = sangat banyak</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Note perfect (affects still valid today)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">Note perfect (affects still valid today) and imperfect [was in the process] tenses prosenenokhen: does not include the idea of 'give up' that the English word 'sacrifice' includes<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>monogenees: unique, one of a kind. Isaac was Abraham's biological son, but he was the only one Abraham recognized legally and socially as his own. Semantic chunks verses 17-19: Abraham/ Made the sacrifice of Isaac (well-known as an example/ When he was put to the test/ He was in the process of sacrificing his only son/ This is the person who had been given the Promises. To him it had been said, "..."/ He figured that God was able to raise the dead/ and it is just as if that is where he got him back from.)<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>LITERALLY: By faith Abraham, when God tested him, offered Isaac as a sacrifice. He who had received the promises was about to sacrifice his one and only son, even though God had said to him, "Through Isaac shall your promised offspring come."</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 21:12</note><v n="19" />Te ngaa Abraham pangee le, na, Ama Lamatua dhu dènge koasa, ho pamamuri hari dhèu madhe. Mema, èèna ka dhu lèke, te lod'o èèna, sama sèmi nèngu abhu hari ana na j'aj'i le mi korban.<bt>But Abraham had already thought that God had the power/authority to bring back to life dead people. That is really true, cuz (elaboration) at that time it was the same as if he got back his child who had been a sacrifice.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Mema, èèna ka dhu lèke, te"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">Mema, èèna ka dhu lèke, te lod'o èèna, nuka sèmi ana na Isak dhu madhe le, te ngaa mamuri hari.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Abraham reasoned that God could"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Abraham reasoned that God could raise the dead, and figuratively speaking, he did receive Isaac back from death.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Isak [\s2]<bt>Isak [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Isak parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, na manèngi ho Lamatua hia mèngi-nale mi ana na, Yakob dènge Esau.<bt>Isak also believed in God. Because of that he asked for God2 to bless his children Yakob and Esau.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith Isaac blessed Jacob"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith Isaac blessed Jacob and Esau in regard to their future.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 27:27-29, 39-40</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob [\s2]<bt>Yakob [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Yakob parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, lod'o nèngu oe madhe, pakaseti kèd'i titu dènge kabodho kabhuku dènge kèpe tatea na, pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua. Hèia manèngi ho Lamatua hia mèngi-nale mi èpu na, ana nèti Yusuf.<bt>Yakob also beleived in God. Because of that, when he was already almost dead, he forced himself to stand leaning with bent back holding his staff, to worship God. And then he asked for God2 to give blessing to his grandchildren, the children of Yusuf.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith Jacob, when he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith Jacob, when he was dying, blessed each of Joseph's sons, and worshiped as he leaned on the top of his staff.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 47:31--48:20</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf [\s2]<bt>Yusuf [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Yusuf parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Lod'o na oe madhe, nèngu parcaya, na, Ama Lamatua pe lere nèti dhèu Na, dhèu Isra'el sèra, kalua nèti rai Masir. Nèti èèna ka, na moa tèke mi rèngu, ho rèti rui na ropa rèngu tèke eele rai Masir.<bt>Yusuf also believed in God. When he was about to die, he believed that God would later lead His Isra'el people out from the land of Masir. That is why he promised (also means made s.o. promise) that they must bring home his bones when they went leaving behind the land of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith Joseph, when his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith Joseph, when his end was near, spoke about the exodus of the Israelites from Egypt and gave instructions about his bones.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 50:24-25, Kalua nèti Masir 13:19</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ina-ama Musa [\s2]<bt>Musa's parents (doublet) [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ina-ama Musa parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Lod'o ina na nara iisi ne, ra pahuni ne toke d'ai tèlu hèru kateme, lula ra ladhe na mone iia. Aa ra madha'u boe dhèu aae Masir, masi ka paredha le dhèu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Pamadhe aa'i ana-ana mone Ibrani dhu rara iisi hiu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Musa's parents also believed in God. When his mother had given birth to him, they hid him for three months, because they saw he was healthy/solid/well built (body). And they were not afraid of the king of Masir, even though he had commanded his people, saying, “Kill off every Ibrani male child, who is a newborn!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabèbu = gemuk, sehat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">kabèbu = gemuk, sehat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith Moses' parents hid"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith Moses' parents hid him for three months after he was born, because they saw he was no ordinary child, and they were not afraid of the king's edict.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 2:2, 1:22</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Musa [\s2]<bt>Musa [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa Musa kapai mai, na parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Te uru èèna, ana bhèni dhèu aae Masir, dhu ded'e nare le nèngu sèna ka j'aj'i mi ana na. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Musa d'èi boe ladhe dhèu pangee, na, nèngu ne a'ari nèti dhèu aae Masir.<bt>When Musa had grown up, he also believed in God. Cuz (elaboration) previously the king of Masir's daughter had elevated/adopted him to be her child. Even that being the case, nevertheless he did not want people to think of him as the king of Masir's family.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith Moses, when he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith Moses, when he had grown up, refused to be known as the son of Pharaoh's daughter.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 2:10-12</note><v n="25" />Te na pangee, na, be'a risi nèngu mamuri j'èra sama-sama dènge dhèu unu Lamatua sèra. Sad'i nèngu baku mamuri karej'e dènge j'ara bhelu-katub'a, dhu dhoka ètu d'ara ciki oo'e di.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) he thought it would be better to live in difficulty/suffering together with God2's people. As long as he didn't live happily/easily with evil (doublet) ways that only last momentarily.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: He chose to be mistreated"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: He chose to be mistreated along with the people of God rather than to enjoy the pleasures of sin for a short time.</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Nèngu soro tèke dhèu pahahe ne, lula nèngu sanao-maena taruu mi Kristus, nuka Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua pajaji le neo hia Na mai. Nèngu taha sèmi èèna, lula ne'a, na, bèli-camèd'a Lamatua bagi hia ne hadia dhu be'a risi nèti mèdha aa'i-aa'i ètu rai Masir.<bt>He allowed people to treat him with contempt, because he was continuing to hope (doublet) in Kristus, the Person whom God had promised to send. He endured/persevered like that, because he knew that God2 would repay him with a reward/compensation (loan) that is far better than all the wealth/possessions that existed in the land of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: He regarded disgrace for the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: He regarded disgrace for the sake of Christ as of greater value than the treasures of Egypt, because he was looking ahead to his reward.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Musa parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi, lod'o na manèngi isin nèti dhèu aae Masir, ho lere nèti bèi-baki èdhi kalua nèti rai Masir. Masi ka dhèu aae nasa titu kèna, te ngaa Musa madha'u boe dènge ne. Musa lèka taruu Ama Lamatua, masi ka tèdhi boe senu-salao Na, te ngaa nuka sèmi Musa dhu nèdhi.<bt>Musa also believed in God when he asked permission from the king of Masir to lead our ancestors out from the land of Masir. Even though the king was already furious, nevertheless Musa was not afraid of him. Musa kept believing2 in God, even though we-inc can not see (Him) visibly (doublet), but it was just like Musa had seen Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bege = taku ; senu-salao ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">bege = taku ; senu-salao = tidak kentara, tidak ada bayangan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith he left Egypt,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith he left Egypt, not fearing the king's anger; he persevered because he saw him who is invisible.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 2:15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Musa parcaya Lamatua kahèi, ropa rèngu pa'èra neo kalua nèti rai Masir. Te nèngu madhutu mèno paredha Lamatua, aa pua bèi-baki èdhi tao Paska hiu-hiu, dènge roro kahib'i-kalèbho, sèna ka tao badha korban. Hèia rare raa kahib'i-kalèbho sèra, sèna ka tao tadha mi babèdho èmu ra. Mèda èèna, ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga puru mai pamadhe ana uuru aa'i-aa'i ètu rai Masir. Te ngaa na pamadhe boe ana uuru ètu èmu dhèu Isra'el, lula ladhe nèdhi raa dhu ra pici ètu babèdho èmu.<bt>Musa also believed in God2 when they were ready to go out from the land of Masir. Cuz (elaboration) he did exactly according to God2's commands, and ordered our ancestors (doublet) to do the first Paska and killed a sheep (doublet) to be an animal sacrifice. Then they took the blood of that sheep (doublet) to place/put a sign on the doorway of their houses. That night, God2's angel came and killed all the oldest children in the land of Masir. But he didn't kill the oldest child in the houses of the Isra'el people, because he saw that blood sprinkled/brushed on the doorways of their houses. [EXEG: doorways, Bruce, Miller] [NOTE to daughter translations: If you have a good word for ceremonial sprinkling, put it in the last sentence, “...lia itu dara (yang dong su percik) di dong pung pintu.”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhutu mèno = iko persis, iko"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">madhutu mèno = iko persis, iko terus</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith he kept the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith he kept the Passover and the sprinkling of blood, so that the destroyer would not touch their firstborn.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 12:21-30</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bèi-baki èdhi [\s2]<bt>Our-inc ancestors [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Lod'o bèi-baki èdhi kalua nèti rai Masir, rèngu parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Lula lalèka ra, ka Lamatua cèri eele èi dhasi mi dua ètu Dhasi Mea, sèna ka rèngu kako asa cabèka dènge be'a, ètu dedha rai mango. Te ngaa sordad'u Masir dhu bata si sèra, madhe aa'i ètu d'ara dhasi, ropa neo pège asa cabèka.<bt>When our ancestors (doublet) went out from the land of Masir, they also believed in God. Because of their belief2, God2 divided/separated the sea in two in the Red Sea, so they walked crossing safely on dry land. But the Masir soldiers who chased/hunted them, died in the sea when they attempted to cross to the other side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sèg'i = belah (kayu) ; bata"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">sèg'i = belah (kayu) ; bata = buru ; pège = langgar, menyebrang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith the people passed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith the people passed through the Red Sea as on dry land; but when the Egyptians tried to do so, they were drowned.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 14:21-31</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rahab [\s2]<bt>Rahab [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Lod'o bèi-baki èdhi maso asa rai Kana'an, rèngu parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi. Te rèngu madhutu paredha Na, dènge kako rai-reo re li'u tembok ètu kota Jeriko, toke pidhu lod'o kateme. Ka tembok ne guri laho mae-mae.<bt>When our ancestors (doublet) had entered the land of Kana'an, they also believed in God. Cuz (elaboration) they followed His commands, and walked around (doublet) the city of Yeriko's outer wall/outside the wall for seven days. Then that wall fell down completely destroyed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai-reo re li'u = kuliling lewat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">rai-reo re li'u = kuliling lewat bagian luar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith the walls of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith the walls of Jericho fell, after the people had marched around them for seven days.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yosua 6:12-21</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Lod'o èèna, Rahab ètu kota èèna kahèi. Uru èèna, nèngu j'aj'i bhèni kajeo. Lula na parcaya Ama Lamatua, nèti èèna ka na sèmi nare mata-mata dhèu Isra'el, aa palu'u si ètu d'ara èmu na. Hèia Lamatua pamadhe aa'i dhèu Jeriko, lula ro'o boe nanene Nèngu. Te ngaa Lamatua hia mamuri mi Rahab, lula na lèka Ne.<bt>There was also Rahab in that city. Formerly, she had been a whore/prostitute. Because she believed in God, that's why she received well the spies of the people of Isra'el, and hid them in her house. Then God2 killed all the people of Yeriko, because they didn't want to listen to/obey Him. But God2 saved Rahab, because of her belief/faith2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palu'u = sembunyikan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">palu'u = sembunyikan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By faith the prostitute Rahab,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By faith the prostitute Rahab, because she welcomed the spies, was not killed with those who were disobedient.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yosua 6:22-25, 2:1-21</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu leo, ae ka dhu parcaya Ama Lamatua kahèi [\s2]<bt>Many other people also believed in God [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ja'a bisa padhai lii madhera hari era, j'ara-j'ara dhèu leo dhu parcaya Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa ja'a abhu boe lod'o taleo, ho lole toke lutu, lula-nèti Gideon, Barak, Simson, Yefta, Daud, Samuel, dènge dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu leo sèra.<bt>I could still talk at length about ways other people believed in God. But I don't have the time/opportunity to narrate in detail about Gideon, Barak, Simson, Yefta, Daud, Samuel, and God's other spokespeople/prophets.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And what more shall I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And what more shall I say? I do not have time to tell about Gideon, Barak, Samson, Jephthah, David, Samuel and the prophets,</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Tuka Pama'ète Lii Langu6:11--8:32, 4:6--5:31, 13:2--16:31, 11:1--12:7, 1 Samuel 16:1--1 Dhèu Aae sèra 2:11, 1 Samuel 1:1--25:1</note><v n="33" />Rèngu se aa'i-aa'i ra parcaya Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, abhu dhu segi dhèu aae-dhèu aae. Abhu dhu pakako paredha dènge d'ara mola, ho sarii dhèu dhu sala boe, aa huku dhèu dhu sala. Abhu dhu sèmi rare ngaa dhu Lamatua jaji le. Aa abhu kahèi segi badha singa.<bt>They all believed in God. Because of that, there were those who conquered kings. There were those who ruled/governed with straight/righteous insides, to defend people who had no wrongs (=innocent), and punish the people who were wrong (=guilty). There were those who received what God2 had promised. And there were those who beat/overcame lions.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: who by faith conquered kingdoms,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: who by faith conquered kingdoms, administered justice, and gained what was promised; who shut the mouths of lions, basileias: the whole governmental system, not just the king<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="11:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 6:1-27</note><v n="34" />Abhu dhu pamadhe ai dhu heo robhe-robhe. Abhu dhu Ama Lamatua ère nare si nèti dhèu dhu neo pamadhe si pake samala. Abhu dhu roe, te ngaa Ama Lamatua pa'èra si. Abhu dhu Lamatua tao si ho èra aae ètu d'ara pamusu, toke musu rai.<bt>There were those who extinguished fires with big flames. There were those whom God2 saved/rescued from people who wanted to kill them using fighting swords. There were those who were weak, but God strengthened them. There were those whom God2 made to be outstanding in war, to the point that their enemies fled.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: quenched the fury of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: quenched the fury of the flames, and escaped the edge of the sword; whose weakness was turned to strength; and who became powerful in battle and routed foreign armies.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 3:1-30</note><v n="35" />Abhu kahèi ina-ina dhu paraga hari dènge dhèu rèngu dhu Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari si nèti mamadhe ra.<bt>There were also mothers who met again with their families (members), whom God had brought back to life from their death.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa abhu dhèu dhu lèke j'aj'èra, lula parcaya Ama Lamatua. Rèngu d'èi risi madhe, sèna ka baku tèke eele parcaya rèngu mi Ama Lamatua. Te rèngu pa'èci taruu dènge Ne. De rèngu dhu sanao-maena, na, bèli-camèd'a Lamatua neo ded'e ra, sèna ka abhu mamuri dhu be'a risi hari ètu sorga.<bt>But there were people who experienced torture/ persecution, because they believed in God. They preferred to die, so that they would not abandon their faith in God. Cuz (elaboration) they were united with Him continually. So (consequently), they were hoping (doublet) that God2 would later elevate them/raise them up to get an even better life in heaven. [EXEG: NLT, Ex. Summ.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="UBS says it is better to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">UBS says it is better to not begin a new paragraph in the middle of the verse, but de in the middle of 35 is the only conjunction in the whole series, and it is adversative. LITERALLY: Women received back their dead, raised to life again. Others were tortured and refused to be released, so that they might gain a better resurrection.<span class="Italic">(35)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="11:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 17:17-24, 2 Dhèu Aae sèra 4:25-37</note><v n="36" />Abhu dhu pa-aape si, aa abhu dhu lèke gama. Abhu dhu leo dhu lèke ngapi haga ra dènge ngangapi ètu d'ara bui.<bt>There are those who scoffed at them, and those who were beaten/whipped. There were still others whose feet were clamped in stocks inside prison. [NOTE to daughter translations. should be as in Acts 16:24]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Some faced jeers and flogging,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Some faced jeers and flogging, while still others were chained and put in prison,</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:36" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 22:26-27, 2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 18:25-26, Yermia 20:2, 37:15, 38:6</note><v n="37" />Abhu dhu madhe, lula lèke pèci dènge hadhu. Abhu dhu roro pamadhe si, pake raroro. Abhu dhu dhèu pare pamadhe si pake samala. Abhu dhu mamuri dènge boe unu, toke ra pake ka'uri badha, lula abhu dhèu dhu paj'èra dènge pasusa si, toke babèga eele si,<bt>There are those who died, because they were stoned with rocks. There were those who died, because people sliced them to death using saws. There were those who died, because they were killed with a sword. There were those who live in poverty and only wore clothes from animal skins, because people tortured/persecuted and caused difficulty for them, to the point that they evicted/chased them out,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="epristheesan: Acts 19:13 'go all ova'."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">epristheesan: Acts 19:13 'go all ova'. thlibomenoi, kakoukhoumenoi: reversed order sounds better in Pidgin.<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>LITERALLY: They were stoned; they were sawed in two; they were put to death by the sword. They went about in sheepskins and goatskins, destitute, persecuted and mistreated--</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 24:21</note><v n="38" />ka rai lasi asa pad'a sod'a, ledhe-ledhe, d'ara loe, dènge asa d'ara ro'a rai. Ra tao dhèu se'e dhu laku-laku boe, aa babège-lalèta si asa era dhu karehe. Aa te ngaa lalèka ra èra titu kèna, toke dhèu ètu rai-haha ne nia boe pa'èci dènge dhèu sèmi se'e se.<bt>so they fled going to live in empty land, in the mountains, in caves, and in holes in the ground. People treated these people as worthless/no-gooders, and chased (doublet) them out to go live in places that were not good. Whereas in fact, their belief2 was very strong, to the point that this world's best place(s), to the point that the people in this world are not deserving to live among people like them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sentence order shift: Pidgin discourse puts"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">Sentence order shift: Pidgin discourse puts conclusion last, not in the middle. LITERALLY: the world was not worthy of them. They wandered in deserts and mountains, and in caves and holes in the ground.<span class="Italic">(38)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Lamatua koa dhèu sèmi se'e se, lula ra parcaya Ne. Te ngaa toke ra madhe, rèngu abhu mèka ngaa dhu Lamatua padhadha tèka.<bt>God2 commended/praised all those people, because they believed in Him. But until they died, they had not yet received what God2 had promised2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: These were all commended for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: These were all commended for their faith, yet none of them received what had been promised.</Message></Annotation><v n="40" />Lamatua neo tao madhutu lii padhadha Na dènge j'ara dhu be'a risi. Lula Na d'èi, sèna ka èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti bisa mamuri toke d'ai mia-mia dènge Ne: nuka èdhi tadhe mèu le Kristus, dènge rèngu dhu madhe uuru sèra.<bt>God2 will do according to His promise, using a better way. Because He wanted all of us to be able to live continually together with Him: we who now know Christ personally and those who died long ago.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="peri: not &quot;for&quot;, but &quot;involving&quot;. LITERALLY:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">peri: not "for", but "involving". LITERALLY: God had planned something better for us, so that only together with us would they be made perfect.<span class="Italic">(40)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="12" />
      <v n="1" />De tasamia dènge èdhi dhu mamuri lod'o limuri ne? Èdhi cakaraa dhèu dhu madhutu pa'uji rai. Bèi-baki èdhi dhu parcaya Ama Lamatua, rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra nuka sèmi dhèu dhu titu lingu rare èdhi, ho pa'èra d'ara èdhi. Te ngaa èdhi dhu pa'èki dènge sasala era, sèra sa ka dhu pabia haga èdhi ka rai tara boe. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi hud'i core eele ku sasala sèra aa'i-aa'i, sèna ka èdhi bisa rai èra. Te Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka dhu pili èdhi, ho madhutu pa'uji rai ne, de èdhi hud'i taha ku, sèna ka rai taruu toke d'ai lane.<bt>So (consequently), what about we-inc who are living now? We are like people who participate in a running race. Our ancestors (doublet) who believed in God long ago, are like viewers who are standing around us to strengthen/encourage our insides. But those of us who are still bound to/by wrongs, that makes our legs heavy so we can't run (well/successfully). That is why we must throw away all those wrongs, so that we can run strongly. Cuz (elaboration) God himself has chosen us to participate in this race, so we must endure/persevere to keep running until the finish line.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'uji rai = lomba lari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pa'uji rai = lomba lari</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore, since we are surrounded"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore, since we are surrounded by such a large cloud of witnesses, let us throw off everything that hinders, and the sin that so easily entangles, and let us run with perseverance the race marked out for us.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Aa èdhi hud'i rai, mage piku g'ana-kariu, te ngaa ladhe dhoka asa Yesus di. Te Nèngu ka dhu bhoke j'ara, ho èdhi bisa parcaya Ama Lamatua. Aa èèna na Nèngu soru-bara èdhi, sèna ka èdhi parcaya taruu toke èle. Sanèd'e, do aad'o? Lod'o Yesus dui j'aj'èra ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha, dhèu pahahe Ne, te ngaa Na taha taruu, lii boe-ugu boe. Te ne'a, na, j'aj'èra Na èle kèna, ka d'ara Na j'aj'i karae. Èèna ka dhu lèke. Te Na madhe, hèia Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne, èle ka Na nedhe pamadhèdi Kristus ètu baboa g'ana Na, ho paredha sama-sama dènge Ne.<bt>And we must run, not looking left-right, but just staring at Yesus. Cuz (elaboration) He is the one who opened the way for us-inc to be able to believe in God. And He will help (doublet) so we can continue believing until the end. Do you remember, or not? When Yesus was suffering on the cross (doublet), people kept scoffing at Him, but He kept persevering. Cuz (elaboration) He knew that when His suffering was finished, His insides would be happy. That's true. Cuz (elaboration) He died, and God brought Him back to life, then He seated Him at His right side, to govern together with Him. [CHECK visual of nedhe pamadhèdi Ne] [NOTE to daughter translations: CHECK that it's not a problem that Christ died, and then God took him up to heaven here (his corpse?) Resurrection is left implicit. Many local discourse patterns require the missing step to be filled in. This problem was brought to our attention by MTTs and is consistent with discourse patterns widespread in the region.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="NOTE: not utter a word above"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">NOTE: not utter a word above is justified from reinforcing his response to mockers ; UNS tangare = 1) lihat, 2) tanganga ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Let us fix our eyes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Let us fix our eyes on Jesus, the Pioneer and Perfecter of our faith, who for the joy set before him endured the cross, scorning the shame, and sat down at the right hand of the throne of God.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Masi ka dhèu paj'èra bia Ne, te ngaa Na taha taruu. De miu baku bhèlu dènge j'aj'èra Yesus, sèna ka miu bisa taha mere, aa baku roe.<bt>Even though people made trouble for Him, nevertheless He kept persevering. So (consequently), you-pl should not forget Yesus' sufferings, so that you can also keep persevering, and not grow weary/weak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Consider him who endured such"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Consider him who endured such opposition of sinful people against himself, so that you will not grow weary and lose heart.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua neo kai èdhi, sèna ka nori ti sama sèmi ama aj'a ana na<bt>God wants to scold us to advise us like a father teaches his child</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Miu lab'a le j'ara bhabhelu-katub'a, te ngaa lalab'a miu èra mèka, toke raa miu suti. Tare'a si!<bt>You-pl have opposed evil (doublet) things/ways, but you have not yet opposed strongly so that your blood has spilled. That's true, right?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: In your struggle against sin,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: In your struggle against sin, you have not yet resisted to the point of shedding your blood.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ele boe miu bhèlu Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua dhu Na peka le dènge miu, nuka sèmi ca dhèu ama padhai lii dènge ana na, peka na,<bt>Perhaps/probably you have forgotten God's Words/Sayings which He has made known to you, like a father speaking to his child, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ana, ee!<bt>“Child, ee!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ladhe Ama èdhi dhu huku ho aj'a èu, sèna ka èu mamuri madhutu j'ara dhu lèke, na,<bt>If/when our-inc Father punishes to teach you-sg, so that you live according to the right/true path,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">èu baku pamud'e!<bt>na, you should not trivialise it!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa ladhe Na kai ho aj'a èu, na,<bt>And if/when He is scolding/admonishing/warning in order to teach you,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">èu baku paroe d'ara.<bt>na, you should not weak insides (=discouraged, depressed, disappointed).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katange pa'era dara = mengeraskan hati"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">katange pa'era dara = mengeraskan hati</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Have you forgotten the word"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Have you forgotten the word of encouragement that addresses you as sons: "My son, do not make light of the Lord's correction, and do not lose heart when he rebukes you, paideia: upbringing, training, instruction, discipline, correction<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>elegkhoo: proof, (punishment, discipline)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Te Ama èdhi kai ho aj'a dhèu dhu Na sue.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) our-inc Father scolds/admonishes in order to teach/correct/ punish people whom He loves.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mema dhèu-dhèu dhu Na sèmi nare j'aj'i ana Na,<bt>Really every person whom He accepts as His child,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Nèngu kai ho aj'a si.&gt;&gt;<bt>He will surely scold/admonish/warn in order to teach them.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: because the Lord disciplines those"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: because the Lord disciplines those whom he loves, and he reproves everyone he accepts as a son" mastigow: punish, chastise, reprove<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="12:5-6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ayub 5:17, Lii Hini 3:11-12</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />De ladhe Ama Lamatua kai ho aj'a miu sèna ka mamuri madhutu j'ara dhu lèke, na, taha taruu aa sèmi mere. Na tao sèmi èèna, lula miu j'aj'i le ana Na. Te ama aa'i-aa'i hud'i kai ho aj'a ana na, toke ana na bisa mamuri madhutu j'ara dhu lèke.<bt>So (consequently), if God is scold in order to teach you-pl to live according to the right/correct path, na, just endure/persevere and accept it. He does that, because you have become/are His child(ren). Cuz (elaboration) each father must scold in order to teach his child, to the point that his child can live according to the right/correct way.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Endure correction; God is treating"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Endure correction; God is treating you as sons. For what son is not disciplined by his father?</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Te ladhe Ama Lamatua kai boe ho aj'a miu sama sèmi ana Na dhu leo sèra, sasoa na, miu se ana Nèngu boe.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if God does not scold to teach you-pl like His other children, that means that you are not His child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: If you are not disciplined"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: If you are not disciplined (and everyone is), then you are illegitimate children, and not true sons.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Èdhi tema pakab'ua ama matana èdhi ètu rai-haha ne, lula na kai ho aj'a-nori ti, lod'o èdhi dhu ana iiki era. Dhu lèke na kèna. Te ngaa dhu be'a risi hari, èdhi hud'i nanene ku Ama Lamatua dènge be'a, lula Nèngu ne, Ama èdhi ètu sorga, aa Na kai ho aj'a-nori èdhi, sèna ka èdhi mamuri madhutu j'ara Na dhu lèke.<bt>We-inc normally show respect to our birth father on this earth, because he teaches/instructs us when we are still small. That is true. But even more than that, we must listen to/obey God well, because He is our Father in heaven, and He wants to scold to teach (doublet) us to live according to His true/right/correct path.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Moreover, we have all had"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Moreover, we have all had human fathers, who diciplined us, and we respected them for it. How much more should we submit to the Father of [our] spirits [/our spiritual Father], and live!</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ama matana èdhi kai ho aj'a èdhi, dhoka d'ara ciki oo'e di, madhutu ngaa dhu na ngee na be'a. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua dhu ne'a risi, ngaa dhu èdhi parluu te'a. Nèti èèna ka, Na kai ho aj'a èdhi, sèna ka mamuri mola-mèci sama sèmi Nèngu.<bt>Our birth fathers teach us for only a moment (limited period of time), according to what he considers to be good. But God knows better what we need to learn/know. That is why He scolds to teaches us to live clean/pure/holy (doublet) like Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Our fathers disciplined us for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Our fathers disciplined us for a little while as they thought best; but God disciplines us for our good, that we may share in his holiness.</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Mema èdhi d'èi boe ladhe abhu lii kai. Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu, d'ara èdhi j'aj'i mau, lula te'a tare le mamuri madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua.<bt>It really is not nice/pleasant if we experience scolding/reprimand. But eventually our insides are also calm/inner peace/quiet, because we know (how to) live according to God2's will/ways.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: No discipline seems pleasant at"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: No discipline seems pleasant at the time, but painful. Later on, however, it produces a harvest of righteousness and peace for those who have been trained by it.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12-13" />A'ari aa'i-aa'i! Pa'èra kacui-aai miu dhu roe, aa pasamaa haga miu dhu bia. Baku rai piku g'ana-kariu, te ngaa rai mola taruu, sèna ka pa'èra d'ara rèngu dhu roe-bhilu ho bisa rai taruu. Miu hud'i pa'èra d'ara miu, sèna ka taha taruu ètu d'ara parcaya mi Kristus.<bt>Siblings! Strengthen your hands that are tired, and lighten your feet that are heavy. Don't run off-track to the left-right, but keep running straight, to strengthen the insides of those who are weak (doublet) and unable keep running. You-pl must strengthen/encourage your insides to keep enduring/ persevering believing in Kristus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasamaa = kasi ringan ; piku"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pasamaa = kasi ringan ; piku = serong</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paremenas: listless, drooping paraluw: coming loose|i(12)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">paremenas: listless, drooping paraluw: coming loose<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>LITERALLY: Therefore, strengthen your feeble arms and weak knees. LITERALLY: Make level paths for your feet, so that the lame may not be disabled, but rather healed.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="12:12-13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 35:3; Lii Hini 4:26</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku tule eele d'ara hua iia Ama Lamatua<bt>Don't reject God's good insides (grace) to you</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />A'ari dhu parcaya Kristus! Miu hud'i pa'èra ngi'u mi, sèna ka mamuri padame èci dènge èci. Aa baku loe tenge j'ara ho mamuri mola-mèci. Te dhèu dhu mola-mèci boe, bisa boe rèdhi Ama Lamatua.<bt>Siblings who believe in Kristus! You-pl must strengthen yourselves to live in (relational) peace with each other. And don't cease to look for ways to live clean/pure/holy (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) a person who is not clean/pure/holy (doublet), cannot see God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eireeneen: different sense from 11. Is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">eireeneen: different sense from 11. Is this a section break or not? holiness 10, peace 11, peace-holiness chiasm 14<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>LITERALLY: Make every effort to live at peace with all people, and to be holy. Without holiness no one will see the Lord.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Pa'èra d'ara èci dènge èci, sèna ka mage dhoka abhu nèti miu dhu rai, toke rasa heka d'ara hua iia Ama Lamatua. Aa j'aga paie ho baku soro tèke ladhe abhu dhu papèd'a d'ara ètu talora aae miu. Te èèna nuka sèmi raco dhu pa'ele iie dhèu ae.<bt>Strengthen/encourage one another so that there are none among you-pl who withdraw/retreat to the point that they do not taste/experience God's goodness/grace/kindness/ generosity. And guard/ watch carefully to not allow the feeling of pained insides (=hate, resentment, anger) in your-pl midst. Cuz (elaboration) that is like poison which destroys many people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: See to it that no"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: See to it that no one misses the grace of God, and that no bitter root grows up to cause trouble and defile many.</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 29:18</note><v n="16" />Mage-mage aa j'aga ho baku abhu dhèu nèti miu dhu tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe dhèu èmu-kamali nèngu. Aa mage-mage aa j'aga ho baku abhu dhèu nèti miu dhu pusi-pahae boe Ama Lamatua, nuka sèmi Esau. Esau ne, ana uuru Isak. Ca lod'o, Esau lèpa dènge kabake manganga. Na manèngi nganga'a ca pega nèti ari na Yakob, ho b'ae pake hak ana uuru.<bt>Be careful and guard so that there are none of you who are doing shameful things with someone who is not their spouse (implies sexual). And2 be careful and guard so that there are none of you who ignore/not care about God, like Esau (did). Esau, was Isak's oldest child. One day, Esau came home with a hungry stomach. He asked for a plate of food from his younger-sibling Yakob, and paid using his elder-sibling rights.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: See that no one is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: See that no one is sexually immoral, or is godless like Esau, who for a single meal sold his inheritance rights as the oldest son.</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 25:29-34</note><v n="17" />Te ngaa èdhi te'a, nèbhu boe ka, Esau manyasa. Te ropa Isak neo manèngi Lamatua hia mèngi-nale mi ana uuru na Esau, te ngaa bisa heka, lula Esau dhu hia iia d'ara le hak ana uuru na. Nèti èèna ka, masi ka na tangi roma iisi, tasamia èèna ka, nèngu bisa heka abhu ngaa dhu uru èèna nèngu core eele.<bt>But not long after that, we-inc know that Esau regretted (his action). Cuz (elaboration) when Isak wanted to ask God2 to give blessing to his eldest child, he couldn't do it anymore, because Esau had already given away freely that elder sibling right of his. That is why even though he wept bitterly, he could not get back what he had earlier thrown away.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Afterward, as you know, when"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Afterward, as you know, when he wanted to inherit this blessing, he was rejected. He could bring about no change of mind, though he sought the blessing with tears.</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 27:30-40</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Sèmi ne'e a'ari! Èdhi bisa lati le asa madha Ama Lamatua, madhutu j'ara hiu dhu Na bhoke nare le hia èdhi. Te ngaa uru-uru sèra, bèi-baki èdhi bisa mèka sèmi èèna. Te lod'o Ama Lamatua pa'èki lii pajaji dènge rèngu, rèngu padètu dènge ledhe Sinai. Ètu dedha ledhe ne, abhu ai dhu heo. Abhu ngèlu aae kahèi. Aa maroga saguru nare ledhe ne, ka dhèu se madha'u titu kèna.<bt>It's like this, siblings! We-inc can already come before God, following the new path/way which He has opened for us. But long ago our ancestors (doublet) were not yet able to do that. Cuz (elaboration) when God was binding a promise with them, they were near mountain/hill Sinai. On that mountain there was a fire flaming/burning. There was also stormy wind. And that mountain was also covered with pitch dark (Idiom: blind dark), so the people were terrified.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: You have not come to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: You have not come to a mountain that [can be touched--NIV / that you can feel--TEV] and that is burning with fire; to darkness, gloom, and storm;</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Rèngu tadèngi lii tiu tèbhe kahèi, hèia lii dhu mèdhu aae nèti Lamatua kalua nèti ledhe ne. Ropa tadèngi lii Lamatua, hèia asa ra madha'u, toke ra manèngi Musa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Ji'i bisa heka taha dènge lii nèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>They also heard the sound of a trumpet blowing, and then God2's loud voice came out from that mountain. Hearing God2's voice (=sound, or what He was saying), they were increasingly afraid, to the point that they asked Musa, saying, “Ira ii! We-exc can no longer stand to hear/listen to this sound/voice!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tiu tèbhe = tarompet ; lii"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">tiu tèbhe = tarompet ; lii mèdhu = 1) suara keras, 2) bunyi muntah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: to a trumpet blast, or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: to a trumpet blast, or to such a voice speaking words, so that those who heard it begged that no further word be spoken to them,</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:18-19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 19:16-22, 20:18-21, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 4:11-12, 5:22-27</note><v n="20" />Rèngu mema bisa boe taha, lula ngaa dhu Lamatua paredha èèna, bia titu kèna. Te Na peka, na, &lt;&lt;Ca dhèu sa bisa boe j'èli ledhe ne! Masi ka dhèu, do badha! Te dhèu cee dhu j'èli ledhe ne, hud'i lèke pèci toke madhe.&gt;&gt;<bt>They really couldn't endure it, because what God2 was commanding, was too heavy (=difficult). Cuz (elaboration) He told them, “Nobody may step on this mountain! Whether human or, animal! Cuz (elaboration) whoever steps on this mountain, must be stoned to death.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: because they could not bear"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: because they could not bear what was commanded: "If even an animal touches the mountain, it must be stoned."</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 19:12-13</note><v n="21" />Ngaa dhu rèngu ladhe rèdhi ètu ledhe ne, mema pamadha'u tare'a, toke Musa karèbha kahèi.<bt>What they saw on that mountain was really horrible/terrifying, to the point that Musa himself was also trembling.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: The sight was so terrifying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: The sight was so terrifying that Moses said, "I am trembling with fear."</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 9:19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa limuri ne, j'ara asa Lamatua bhoke tèke le, aa èdhi bisa patoo madha padhai lii dènge Ne. Limuri ne, èdhi lati asa ledhe cue, ngara na Sion. Ètu era ne'e, abhu kota Yerusalem. Kota Yerusalem ne, ètu boe rai-haha ne, te ngaa kota Yerusalem hiu ètu sorga, era pea Ama Lamatua. Ètu nèi, abhu ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ae-ae, toke riho-riho, dhu loe boe tao pesta.<bt>But now, the way to God2 is already open, and we-inc can talk directly to Him. Now we come to a mountain named Sion. And there, there is the city of Yerusalem. This city of Yerusalem is not on earth, but a new city of Yerusalem in heaven, the place where God lives/stays. In that (remote) place, there are many of God's angels, to the point of thousands (upon thousands), who do not cease to make festive celebrations.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But you have come to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But you have come to Mount Zion, to the heavenly Jerusalem, the city of the living God. You have come to thousands upon thousands of angels in joyful assembly,</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ètu kota nèi kahèi, j'aj'i le era pakaboko dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu parcaya Kristus. Te Ama Lamatua dhu tao nare le daftar, ho suri ngara ra èci-èci ètu sorga. Ètu era nèi kahèi, Ama Lamatua neo parisa aa tai-dadoo mamuri dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra. Aa ètu nèi kahèi, pakaboko dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu uru èèna Ama Lamatua sèmi nare si dènge be'a, lula ra parcaya Ne. Ètu nèi, rèngu j'aj'i kateme ètu madha Lamatua.<bt>That city (remote) has also become a gathering place for all people who believe in Kristus. Cuz (elaboration) God has made a list (loan) to write each of their names in heaven. Also at that place, God will investigate/examine and evaluate everyone's lives. And also in that place, there are gathered everyone whom formerly God accepted, because they believed in Him. There (remote), they become full/complete/whole in God's eyes/view.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dadoo = timbang dadoo-tatai ~ tai-dadoo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">dadoo = timbang dadoo-tatai ~ tai-dadoo @@@</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ekkleesiaai proototokoon: not Jesus as the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">ekkleesiaai proototokoon: not Jesus as the Firstborn, but the assembly of people to all of whom God has given the same status as if they were all his firstborn children. pneumasin? Not the Bon Festival or the Day of the Dead<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>LITERALLY: to the church of the firstborn, whose names are written in heaven. You have come to God, the judge of all men, to the spirits of righteous men made perfect,</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Aa Yesus kahèi ètu era nèi, dhu j'aj'i mi kalete hia Ama Lamatua dènge dhèu rai-haha. Yesus madhe, pasuti raa Na, sèna ka Ama Lamatua bisa pa'èki lii pajaji hiu dènge èdhi. Nèti èèna ka, raa Yesus ne, cuhi d'ara Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa raa Yesus leko-leo nèti raa Habel ètu d'ara Sasuri Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka. Te lod'o Kain pamadhe Habel, raa Habel dhu suti èèna, papana d'ara Ama Lamatua, toke Na huku Kain.<bt>And Yesus is also in that place, as a/the bridge between God and humans. Yesus died spilling His blood (implies for a purpose/cause), so that God could bind a new promise with us-inc. That is why Yesus' blood cools God's insides [Idiom: causes anger (=hot) to dissipate]. But Yesus' blood is different from Habel's blood in that Story of First Beginnings (=Genesis). Cuz (elaboration) when Kaen murdered Habel, Habel's blood which had been poured out, made God's insides hot (=angry), to the point that He punished Kaen.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="proserchomai: You now have a relationship"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">proserchomai: You now have a relationship with Jesus rantismou: metonym for sacrifice<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>TERM: Make the deal go into effect. 1 Cor 11:25 "Dis cup mean dat God wen make one new kine deal fo you guys, an I gotta bleed an mahke fo make um happen lidat. " OK. LITERALLY: to Jesus, the mediator of a new covenant, and to the sprinkled blood that speaks a better word than the blood of Abel.<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="12:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 4:10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Pasa dhilu pabe'a-be'a, ho nanene ngaa dhu Ama Lamatua neo peka dènge miu. Baku tao sèmi bèi-baki èdhi dhu ro'o boe nanene lii padhai Musa, lod'o na j'aj'i dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua ètu rai-haha ne. Nèti èèna ka Lamatua huku si. Ngaa hari dènge èdhi se! Ladhe èdhi to'o boe nanene lii Na nèti sorga, tatu Nèngu huku èdhi bia risi eele!<bt>Fasten your ears well to listen to what God wants to say to you-pl. Don't do the same as our ancestors (doublet), who didn't want to listen to what Musa had to say, when he was God's spokesman on this earth. That is why God2 punished them. Even more with us-inc! If we do not want to listen to/obey what He has to say from heaven, surely He will punish us even heavier/more severely!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Moses needs to be introduced by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">Moses needs to be introduced by name to make the tie back to v. 21. chreematizonta: divine oracle. Content is not specifically positive or negative except as context requires.<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>LITERALLY: See to it that you do not refuse him who speaks. If they did not escape when they refused him who warned them on earth, how much less will we [escape], if we turn away from him who warns us from heaven?</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:22</note><v n="26" />Lod'o bèi-baki èdhi titu ètu ledhe Sinai, lii Lamatua dhu mèdhu èèna, tao rai opo. Limuri ne Na moa, na,<bt>When our ancestors were standing on Sinai mountain, God2's loud/harsh voice made the ground shake. Now, He is promising, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Bèli-camèd'a Ja'a tao ne opo ca tèka hari.<bt>“I will make the ground shake one more time.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mesa boe rai di opo,<bt>It will not be only the ground that is shaken,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">te ngaa liru opo kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>but the sky will also be shaken.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: At that time his voice"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: At that time his voice shook the earth, but now he has promised, "Once more I will shake, not only the earth, but the heavens."</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Hagai 2:6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Lod'o Lamatua peka, na, Nèngu neo tao opo aa'i-aa'i &lt;&lt;ca tèka hari&gt;&gt;, sasoa na, Lamatua neo pagaged'o aa'i-aa'i dhu Na paj'aj'i ètu dedha-liru dènge ètu rai-haha ne, toke abhu dhu bisa boe taha. Ele aa'i si. Te dhu taha di, nuka dhu pea taruu.<bt>When God2 said that He was going to make everything shake “one more time”, that means that God2 wanted to shake everything that He had made in the sky (doublet) and on the earth (doublet), to the point that they couldn't stand it/endure. They all disappeared. Cuz (elaboration) that which is able to endure, will remain continually/forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&quot;shake da earth&quot; OR &quot;make da"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">"shake da earth" OR "make da earth shake"? "shake" OR "shake up"?<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>Doesn't hang together. "Da stuff dat no shake" should be things like faith and love. Adding "ony" helps. OK. LITERALLY: The words "once more" indicate the removing of what can be shaken--that is, created things--so that what cannot be shaken may remain.<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pagaged'o = shake up ; ate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">pagaged'o = shake up ; ate = sisa</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ama Lamatua nèd'u paredha ètu sorga. Èèna bisa boe laho. Ngaa-ngaa tao boe! Lula Na neo sèmi nare, na, miu maso j'aj'i mi dhèu unu Na ètu nèi. De mai ho èdhi manèngi makasi mi Nèngu, pahaha iisi mi Nèngu, aa ded'e padedha-dedha Ne, lula dadedha Na.<bt>God is ruling/governing in heaven. That cannot be destroyed/brought to ruin. Nothing will happen! Because He wants to receive you, you should enter as His people there. So (consequently) let us-inc give thanks to Him, worship Him, and elevate Him on high because of His high-ness/glory! [EXEG: “receiving a kingdom” Ellingsworth = citizens - occupying an eternally safe “place” where God reigns for ever with Christ at his right hand.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èdhi ho tèdu paredha dènge Ne"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">èdhi ho tèdu paredha dènge Ne ètu sorga toke dai mia-mia. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi hud'i manèngi makasi mi Nèngu, aa pahaha iisi asa Ne, lula Nèngu kapai titu kèna.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Therefore, since we are receiving"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Therefore, since we are receiving a kingdom that cannot be shaken, let us be thankful, and so worship God acceptably with reverence and awe,</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Te ngaa èdhi baku pamud'e kahèi, lula nanasa Ama Lamatua nuka sèmi ai dhu na'e pakèpu aa'i mèu-mèu.<bt>But we must also be careful, because God's anger, is like fire which burns everything up until it is gone.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: for our God is a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: for our God is a consuming fire.</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 4:24</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Èdhi hud'i mamuri pabe'a èci dènge èci<bt>We must live in right relationships to one another</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="13" />
      <v n="1" />De a'ari aa'i-aa'i! Abhu pèri-pèri j'ara dhu ja'a neo pasanèd'e miu.<bt>So (consequently) siblings! There are several matters that I want to remind/warn you-pl about.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Baku bhèlu pasue taruu a'ari dhèu parcaya.<bt>Don't forget to mutually-love continually your fellow believers. [NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="menetoo: Rienecker thinks it implies that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">menetoo: Rienecker thinks it implies that there was a problem, but that doesn't fit with either the letter as a whole, or the other advice in this chapter. LITERALLY: Keep on loving each other as brothers.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Baku bhèlu bhoke d'ara sèna ka sèmi mere dhèu dhu miu tadhe boe asa d'ara èmu mi. Te abhu pèri-pèri a'ari dhu sèmi rare dhèu, te ngaa re'a boe, na, dhèu sèra, ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga.<bt>Don't forget to open your insides (=be receptive) to receive people you do not know into your homes. Cuz (elaboration) there are some siblings who have received people like that, and it turned out that those people were God's angels (from heaven).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="asyndeton = for example (vs 2-7)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">asyndeton = for example (vs 2-7) make house: does it mean long time? or just 'stay'?<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>LITERALLY: Do not forget to entertain strangers, for by so doing some people have entertained angels without knowing it.</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 18:1-8, 19:1-3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Baku bhèlu tao ai-hèb'a mi dhèu ètu d'ara bui, te ra kèpa si lula ra parcaya Kristus. Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i soru-bara si, nuka sèmi miu ka dhu ra kèpe rare.<bt>Don't forget to pay attention to (Idiom: place hand-mouth) people in prison, cuz (elaboration) they have been arrested because they believe in Kristus. That is why you-pl must help them, just like you yourselves have been arrested. [EXEG: Bruce, Ell. Miller, CEV]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Aa mage bhèlu soru-bara dhèu dhu lèke j'aj'èra nèti dhèu. Lalau si pabe'a-be'a, nuka sèmi miu mesa mi ka dhu abhu j'aj'èra èèna.<bt>And don't forget to help (doublet) people who are being persecuted/tortured by other people. Take care of their (needs) well/ carefully, just like it is you yourselves who are getting/experiencing that difficulty.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&quot;Body&quot; metonymy OK here, &quot;you are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">"Body" metonymy OK here, "you are capable of feeling the same thing". LITERALLY: Remember those in prison as if you were their fellow prisoners, and those who are mistreated as being yourselves also in the body.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Paleo èmu èèna, mola-mèci. Te ngaa mage paleo èmu dhu mola-mèci ne, j'aj'i mi kaj'alu. Te tatu Ama Lamatua huku dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu èmu nèngu boe.<bt>Marriage is clean/pure/holy (doublet). But may it not be that marriage which is clean/holy (doublet) becomes dirty/filthy/ defiled. Cuz (elaboration) God will surely punish everyone who does shameful things with a person who is not their husband or wife.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Marriage is honorable, and the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Marriage is honorable, and the marriage bed [pure / undefiled], for God will judge the adulterer and all the sexually immoral.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Baku manga'a doi-dhari. Te ngaa miu hud'i mamuri nèti ngaa dhu miu abhu, te èèna d'ai le. Ama Lamatua dhu peka le, na,<bt>Don't be greedy for money (doublet). But you-pl must live from what you have, cuz (elaboration) it is enough. God has spoken, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a bhèlu boe miu.<bt>“I will not forget you-pl.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a soro tèke boe miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will not leave/abandon you.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Keep yourselves free from love"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Keep yourselves free from love of money and be content with what you have, because God has said, "I will never leave you; I will never abandon you."</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 31:6, 8, Yosua 1:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />De pa'èra d'ara miu, nuka sèmi dhu ra suri, na,<bt>So (consequently) strengthen/encourage your insides, just like someone wrote, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Lula Lamatua ja'a neo soru-bara ja'a,<bt>“Because my Master/Lord/God2 wants to help me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nèti èèna ka, ja'a madha'u boe.<bt>that is why I am not afraid.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te abhu boe ca dhèu sa hèi,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) there is not even one person,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu bisa cèri eele ja'a nèti Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>who can separate/divorce me from God." [Ex.Summ. Miller “harm”][NOTE to daughter translations: Be careful to avoid untrue statements like “nobody can cause me trouble/difficulty”. From context, force of this statement should be in the direction of “nobody can truly disturb my confidence/assurance (of salvation), even though they might disrupt my life or torture me” “nobody can distance me from God”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: So we say with confidence,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: So we say with confidence, "The Lord is my helper; I will not be afraid. What can man do to me?"</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 118:6</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Madhutu ia ka atora agama dhu dhui, te ngaa parcaya taruu Yesus<bt>Don't go back and follow the old religious regulations, but keep believing in Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Baku bhèlu dhèu-dhèu dhu uru sèra aj'a-nori miu Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua. Pajiko paie-iie j'ara mamuri ra, aa madhutu lalèka ra. Te, dhu rèngu parcaya, nuka:<bt>Don't forget the people who have taught you God's Words/Sayings. Think/observe carefully the way theu live (moral, social, relational, values), and follow their beliefs2. Cuz (elaboration) what they believe is: [NOTE to daughter translations: If finding a generic and/or gender inclusive word for “leaders” is too problematic, leave it implicit and just use “people”, so as to not skew the focus. Gk is verbal focusing on the function, not nominal or institutional.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Remember your leaders, who spoke"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Remember your leaders, who spoke the word of God to you. Consider the outcome of their way of life and imitate their faith.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />Yesus Kristus ub'a nèdhi boe.<bt>Yesus Kristus never changes.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèti uru, doe ne'e, toke d'ai mia-mia la'e,<bt>From long ago, until now, and until forever,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Nèngu hali boe.<bt>He does not waver.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Jesus Christ is the same"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Nèti èèna ka, miu baku madhutu rii nèti a'aj'a dhu sala. Ama Lamatua tao pa'èra le d'ara miu, lula Na pad'elo le d'ara hua iia Na dènge miu. Lula boe nèti miu madhutu atora nganga'a-nganginu dhu guna boe.<bt>Because of that, you-pl should not just go along with the currents of wrong teachings. God strengthens/ encourages your insides, because He has shown/ demonstrated His goodness/grace/ kindness/ generosity to you. Not because you followed the useless regulations about eating-drinking.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Do not be carried away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Do not be carried away by all kinds of strange teachings. It is good for our hearts to be strengthened by grace, not by ceremonial foods, which have no value to those who eat them.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Uru-uru sèra, ètu madha Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua, abhu mei èci dhu era tèka badha korban. Ama agama ka dhu lalau ètu sèra, dhu dènge hak ra'a sisi dhu sisa nèti dedha mei ne. Te ngaa limuri ne, èdhi dhu dènge le mei leo.<bt>Long ago, in that yard in God's Tent of Prayer there is a table, a place to sacrifice animals. The *priests who serve there, have the rights to eat the leftover meat from that table. But now, we have a different table.</bt><note reference="13:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu dhèu cahag'e dhu peka na, mei ne, mei perjamuan, aa te ngaa aad'o sèmi èèna. Mei ne'e paj'uj'u mi mamadhe Yesus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Èdhi b'ala korban Nèngu èèna, dènge tèti persembahan lii koa-kio taruu mi Ama Lamatua. Ladhe ayat 15 re haha ne.<bt>There are people who say this is about the communion table, but it's not. This table points to Yesus' death on the cross (doublet). We respond to His sacrifice by bringing offerings of praise (doublet) continually to God. See verse 15 below.</bt></note>Aa ama agama rupa dhui dènge boe hak ra'a ètu mei èèna.<bt>And *priests of the old model have no rights to eat there. [NOTE: because of the collocation with ‘eat’, in KM we go to ‘table’ here, rather than ‘sacrifice table (altar)’.] [EXEG: TH, Bruce, Miller, Ellingsworth are all unanimous that this is not talking about communion (a position held until recently by the Catholics), but in the context of vs.10-17, is clearly about Christ's sacrifice being qualitatively different to the old system, and evoking a different kind of response.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: We have an altar from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: We have an altar from which those who minister at the tabernacle have no right to eat.</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Uru èèna, tèu mai-tèu mai kètu kapai risi agama nèti raa badha korban, sèna ka tèke asa d'ara Kama Luri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua. Dènge j'ara ne'e, Lamatua pabhèlu eele sasala ra. Èle na, pasae rèti badha ne lasi tunu asa li'u rae.<bt>Formerly, each year the *high priest brought blood from animal sacrifices to go place it inside God's Most Holy Room. In that way, God2 completely forgets their wrongs. Then they take that animal, to burn/roast outside the village.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: The high priest carries the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: The high priest carries the blood of animals into the Most Holy Place as a sin offering, but the bodies are burned outside the gate.</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 16:27</note><v n="12" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge Yesus. Nèngu j'aj'i korban kahèi, sèna ka Ama Lamatua bisa saku eele sasala dhèu rai-haha. Aa lod'o j'aj'èra Na èèna, ra nuni rèti Ne kahèi, ho pamadhe Ne asa li'u kota Yerusalem.<bt>It's the same way with Yesus. He also became a sacrifice so God could wipe away human's wrongs. And when He was suffering, they also dragged Him off, to go kill Him outside the city of Yerusalem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And so Jesus also suffered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And so Jesus also suffered outside da city gate to make his people holy through his own blood.</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Nèti èèna ka, mai ka èdhi lati asa Yesus, ho parcaya Ne taruu. Masi ka dhèu pahahe èdhi, èdhi hud'i pa'èra sèmi tare ne, nuka sèmi Yesus.<bt>Because of that, let us-inc go to Yesus, to keep believing in Him. Even though people treat us with contempt, nevertheless we must be prepared to accept it, just like Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Let us, then, go to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Let us, then, go to him outside the camp, bearing the disgrace he bore.</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Te èdhi dhoka manubha taha ètu rai-haha ne. Te ngaa èdhi sanao-maena, sèna ka pea ètu kota hiu cue ètu sorga toke d'ai mia-mia la'e.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) we are only living temporarily on this earth. But we are hoping (doublet) to live in a new city in heaven forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: For here we do not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: For here we do not have an enduring city, but we are looking for the city that is to come.</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Lula Yesus j'aj'i le korban pala èdhi, nèti èèna ka èdhi parluu heka tèti badha korban asa Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa abhu mèdha korban dhu leo era, dhu èdhi hud'i tèti ku hia Ne, nuka, koa-kio dhu ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Na.<bt>Because Yesus has become a sacrifice for us, that is why we no longer need to bring animal sacrifices to give to God. But there are still other sacrifices which we must keep bringing to Him, that is, praises (doublet) which lift up/exalt His name/reputation.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Through Jesus, therefore, let us"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Through Jesus, therefore, let us continually offer to God a sacrifice of praise--the fruit of lips that confess his name.</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Aa mage bhèlu tao j'ara be'a hia dhèu leo. Ladhe ra parluu ngaa, lami soru-bara si. Te sèra sa, j'aj'i nuka sèmi mèdha persembahan dhu pakarej'e d'ara Ama Lamatua.<bt>And do not forget to do good things to/for other people. If they need something, go help (doublet) them. Cuz (elaboration) all that is also like an offering which makes God's insides happy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And do not forget to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And do not forget to do good and to share with others, for God is pleased with such sacrifices.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Miu hud'i nanene ku dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu uri miu. Te dhèu se'e ka dhu j'aga miu mèda-mèu ètu d'ara mamuri miu dènge Ama Lamatua. Bèli-camèd'a rèngu hud'i lapor ku sasab'a rèngu asa Ama Lamatua. De nanene paie si, sèna ka ra bisa sab'a aa lapor dènge d'ara karej'e. Mage dhoka ra peka dènge d'ara dhu laho mae-mae, lula miu tèke eele j'ara mamuri Yesus Kristus. Te ladhe sèmi èèna, na, miu oto boe.<bt>You-pl must listen to/obey every person who is managing/looking after/taking care of/dealing with you. Cuz (elaboration) these people are the ones who guard/watch over you day-night (=at all times) in your life with God. They will have to report about their work to God. So (consequently) listen to/obey them carefully, so they can work and report with a happy insides. May it not be that they report with a crushed insides/ dismay, because you have left behind/abandoned Yesus Kristus' way of life. Cuz (elaboration) iif it's like that, you have no benefit. [NOTE to daughter translations: /jiwa/ is problematic in two ways. Some lgs don't have a clear word for it, and if they do it is primarily associated with talking about dead people, not ones still alive. Avoid “guard your lives” as that gives permission for abuse of authority. ALT: “guard you day-night in your lives with God1”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samanga = soul (but tends to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">samanga = soul (but tends to primarily evoke in relation to dead people, not living) ; manad'u = samanga (let not know, Mika has heard of it) ; mamuri manad'u = kehidupan rohani ?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Obey your leaders and submit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Obey your leaders and submit to their authority. They keep watch over you as men who must give an account. Obey them so that their work will be a joy, not a burden, for that would be of no advantage to you.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhu suri sasuri ne, manèngi makasi dènge sabaj'a hia dhèu Ibrani<bt>The one who writes this letter gives thanks and prays for the Hebrew people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Sabaj'a taruu hia ji'i. Te d'ara ji'i mema mola, aa ji'i neo tao j'ara be'a taruu.<bt>Keep praying for us-exc. Cuz (elaboration) our insides are really straight/right/just, and we want to do good things continually.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Pray for us. We are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Pray for us. We are sure that we have a clear conscience and desire to live honorably in every way.</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Aa be'a risi hari, sabaj'a sèna ka ja'a bisa lèpa malai asa miu.<bt>Even more than that, pray so I can return quickly to you-pl.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: I especially urge you to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: I especially urge you to pray that I may be restored to you soon.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20-21" />Ama Lamatua ka dhu pamau d'ara èdhi. Ja'a manèngi sèna ka Na soru-bara miu, ho miu bisa madhutu aa'i dad'èi Na. Ja'a manèngi kahèi, ho Na soru-bara èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti, sèna ka te'a pakarej'e d'ara Na. Te Ama Lamatua pake le raa Yesus Kristus dhu suti èèna, sèna ka pa'èki lii pajaji hiu dènge èdhi. Lii pajaji ne j'aj'i taruu toke d'ai mia-mia. Ka Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus. De Yesus ka dhu ladhe-leru èdhi limuri ne, nuka sèmi dhèu madhenga badha dhu be'a risi. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi ded'e kolongara Na padedha-dedha, aa koa-kio Ne taa-taa! Èèna ka dhu lèke.<bt>God is the one who calms (inner peace) our-inc insides. I ask Him to help (doublet) you, so you can do according to all of His will/ways. I also ask Him to help (doublet) us-inc all, so we know how to please His insides. Cuz (elaboration) God has used Yesus Kristus' blood which has been spilled, to bind a new promise with us. That promise continues in effect forever. And God brought back to life Yesus Kristus, our Head/Leader. So (consequently) Yesus is the one who is serving/looking after (doublet) us like the best shepherd/herder. That is why we lift His name/ reputation up high/exalt Him, and keep praising (doublet) Him! That's what is right. [NOTE to daughter translations: Great Shepherd here should collocate with what shepherds do with sheep, not with what kings do to subjects, so err towards the “best (good)” rather than “best (strongest)”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: May the God of peace,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: May the God of peace, who through the blood of the eternal covenant brought back from the dead our Lord Jesus, that great Shepherd of the sheep, LITERALLY: equip you with everything good for doing his will, and may he work in us what is pleasing to him, through Jesus Christ, to whom be glory forever and ever. Amen.<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Saloom<bt>Greetings/leave-takings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />A'ari pasue! Ja'a manèngi sèna ka miu sèmi mere lii holo ja'a ne dènge d'ara kateme. Te sasuri ne bab'a iiki di.<bt>Dear siblings! I ask for you-pl to receive this advice of mine wholeheartedly. Cuz (elaboration) this letter is short.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii holo = haholo ; baba"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">lii holo = haholo ; baba = gong ; bab'a = pendek, singkat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Brothers, I urge you to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Brothers, I urge you to bear with my word of exhortation, for I have written you only a short letter.</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Abhu lii lolo dhu ja'a neo miu aa'i-aa'i mi me'a, nuka: a'ari èdhi Timotius dhu kalua le nèti d'ara bui. Ladhe na mai malai paraga dènge ja'a, èèna na ji'i dua mi palere-lere dhiu asa miu.<bt>There is news that I want all of you to know. That is: our-inc sibling Timotius has gotten out of prison. If/when he comes quickly to meet me, the two of us-exc will go together to visit you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="abhu lii = ada masalah, perkara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">abhu lii = ada masalah, perkara ; abhu lii lolo = ada kabar/cerita</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: I want you to know"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: I want you to know that our brother Timothy has been released. If he arrives soon, I will come with him to see you.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ja'a pa'adhu lii maho'o hia kètu miu sèra, aa lii maho'o hia miu aa'i-aa'i dhu parcaya Yesus Kristus. A'ari nèti propensi Italia hia miu lii maho'o kahèi.<bt>I send greetings to your-pl leaders, and greetings to all of you who believe in Yesus Kristus. The siblings in the propinsi of Italia also send greetings. [CHECK kadhod'o]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadhod'o = kepala (kelompok sosial), pimpinan,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z">kadhod'o = kepala (kelompok sosial), pimpinan, orang besar (UNS not know) ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Greet all your leaders and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Greet all your leaders and all God's people. Those from Italy send you their greetings.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ja'a manèngi sèna ka Ama Lamatua pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na dènge miu aa'i-aa'i mi.<bt>I ask that God continue to show His goodness/ grace/ kindness/generosity to all of you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Grace be with you all."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:57:06Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Grace be with you all.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">D'ai sange ne'e ka!<bt>That's all for now! [common discourse closure]</bt></p>
  </book>
</bible>